WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.200
[Amit Varma]: This episode of The Seen and The Unseen is brought to you by Intel.

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:12.760
[Amit Varma]: How do we see the world?

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:14.920
[Amit Varma]: A glib answer to that is differently.

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:18.680
[Amit Varma]: You and I can stand at a crowded intersection and look out into the world

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:20.440
[Amit Varma]: and see totally different things.

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:23.800
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, we could look at the same rock and see two different rocks.

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:28.240
[Amit Varma]: The world is the seen and the unseen, and the scene is such a small part of it.

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:30.160
[Amit Varma]: This is why I love reading literature.

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:33.200
[Amit Varma]: Books open windows for us into other worlds,

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:35.280
[Amit Varma]: even when they are set in the same world as ours.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:37.880
[Amit Varma]: For those who don't read, you have one life to live.

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:41.560
[Amit Varma]: For those who do read, there is no end to lives and to seeing.

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:46.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, while I do read a lot, my biggest complaint about myself is that I don't see enough.

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:50.040
[Amit Varma]: I go places, I do things, but I remain stuck inside my own head.

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:52.440
[Amit Varma]: But a writer has to learn to see.

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:55.160
[Amit Varma]: How else can you build worlds for others?

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:58.240
[Amit Varma]: This is why I enjoy chatting with novelists on the show.

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:01.120
[Amit Varma]: Each of them sees the world in a unique way.

00:01:01.440 --> 00:01:04.840
[Amit Varma]: And when they share some of that with me, I can also see a little better.

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:21.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:28.120
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Saira Rai, a writer, a novelist who straddles multiple languages and multiple worlds.

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:32.360
[Amit Varma]: Saira is a granddaughter of the great Munshi Premchand, the giant of Hindi literature.

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:35.400
[Amit Varma]: But she doesn't often like this fact mentioned because, hey,

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:39.720
[Amit Varma]: she stands out as a literary figure and as a person in her own right.

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:42.720
[Amit Varma]: She's equally at ease with Hindi, Urdu and English.

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:45.320
[Amit Varma]: And all her fiction, in fact, is written in Hindi.

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:50.760
[Amit Varma]: But she's translated writers like Vinod Kumar Shukla into English, as well as some of her own work.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:56.360
[Amit Varma]: I met Saira when I agreed to be on the jury of the JCB Literature Prize this year, and Saira was ahead of the jury.

00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:59.960
[Amit Varma]: These are COVID times, so our jury meetings would happen on Zoom.

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:04.760
[Amit Varma]: The five of our jury members would gather to discuss a fixed number of books every week,

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:09.080
[Amit Varma]: and Saira would lead the discussion by talking about each book in detail.

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:13.240
[Amit Varma]: For me, and I think for all the other jury members, it was a jaw-dropping experience.

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:18.840
[Amit Varma]: She would talk about each book with such depth that she taught us not just something about the book all of us had read,

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:21.040
[Amit Varma]: but also something about reading itself.

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:25.840
[Amit Varma]: I figured that whenever we could meet in person, I simply had to record an episode with Saira.

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:29.440
[Amit Varma]: So finally, in the second week of November, we made it happen.

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:34.040
[Amit Varma]: She was passing through Mumbai, I invited her home for lunch and a recording in my home studio,

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:36.240
[Amit Varma]: and we had the conversation you will hear now.

00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:39.840
[Amit Varma]: I loved having this conversation, and I loved listening to it again later,

00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:43.440
[Amit Varma]: because I love books and writing, and Saira reminds me why.

00:02:43.640 --> 00:02:45.440
[Amit Varma]: Listen in, I think you'll like it as well.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:48.840
[Amit Varma]: But before that, a quick commercial break.

