00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:52.240
[Amit Varma]: Saira, welcome to the Scene in the Unseen.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:57.640
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit. I'm so pleased to be here, and so nice to meet you finally in person.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:01.240
[Amit Varma]: I've kind of been waiting for a long time to record this episode,

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:04.840
[Amit Varma]: but one of the things that I wasn't very happy about while researching for the episode is that

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:07.840
[Amit Varma]: there's so little of your writing actually available in English.

00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:11.040
[Amit Varma]: Like I read a couple of great stories by you which we'll talk about,

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:16.040
[Amit Varma]: and also this wonderful essay you wrote for Caravan, which was so rich in impressions and ideas.

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:21.440
[Amit Varma]: But as you came in, you just mentioned that you've also got other essays in the pipeline,

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:26.040
[Amit Varma]: including one that talks about memories and the layers of memories that builds one's life.

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:28.640
[Amit Varma]: And you kindly offered to read it out for us.

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:30.640
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to take you up on that offer.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:33.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about this essay and then go ahead.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:39.640
[Guest]: Amit, basically it's going to form the preface to my book of autobiographical essays that I'm writing.

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:43.440
[Guest]: The book is almost done. I think maybe one more essay left to write.

00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:49.840
[Guest]: And it's basically a family memoir kind of thing, but it's not actually a linear thing.

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:55.840
[Guest]: Like all the essays are separate. They are usually about a place, a house or a person,

00:04:56.040 --> 00:05:00.040
[Guest]: various people in my family. So they are all interconnected essays,

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:04.040
[Guest]: but they are not necessarily one continuous narrative like that.

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.440
[Guest]: So this piece that I wrote, which is quite a short piece really,

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:11.640
[Guest]: I mean, I intended it as a preface. I'm still not very sure whether I should use it as a preface.

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:17.640
[Guest]: But it's basically about living in a house, which is a family house in Allahabad, in Raman Road.

00:05:17.840 --> 00:05:20.640
[Guest]: In it, the house is also a character.

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:26.440
[Guest]: The house is a character in the sense that, I mean, it describes the house, the rooms inside,

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:31.440
[Guest]: and how people lived in it, and my memories of those people who are not there anymore.

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:37.440
[Guest]: So it sort of starts off like that. So that's the beginning of my...

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:40.040
[Guest]: Wonderful. I can't wait to hear it. Let's go.

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:41.240
[Guest]: So should I read it out now?

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:42.240
[Amit Varma]: Please. Absolutely.

00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:45.840
[Guest]: Right. So the piece is called Palimpsest.

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:50.240
[Guest]: And well, anyway, I'll just read it out. So I don't have to, I mean,

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:54.440
[Guest]: I'm not going to explain what it is about because the listeners will get the sense of it.

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:56.240
[Guest]: It's called Palimpsest.

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:01.440
[Guest]: There is something melancholy in the act of writing about one's past.

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:08.440
[Guest]: This is especially the case if most of that past has taken place in the same house in which you still live.

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:15.240
[Guest]: It is your family home, the same house where you have always lived, and yet it is different.

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:20.440
[Guest]: There were people who lived here, but many of them are no longer alive.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:23.040
[Guest]: Absent, they are still palpable.

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:29.240
[Guest]: The air is saturated with their presence, their invisible script written upon each corner of the house.

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:33.640
[Guest]: You pull the door, and with a creaking of springs, it opens.

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:38.640
[Guest]: The rooms are all there. You feel the volume of the space.

00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:45.040
[Guest]: You know the pictures that were on the walls, the exact position of the furniture, the objects in the room.

00:06:45.240 --> 00:06:49.040
[Guest]: Nothing has changed, but everything feels changed.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:57.840
[Guest]: You remember the way light fell from the skylights, some of which are now blocked up or have disappeared in changes made to the house.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:04.840
[Guest]: There are cobwebs hanging from ceilings too high to be cleaned, not that you want to clean them.

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:12.840
[Guest]: There are termites, too, that swarm out of the ground and make mud tubes, reaching the most unlikely of places.

00:07:12.840 --> 00:07:21.640
[Guest]: You can, if you listen hard, hear the quiet clicking sounds they make as they move and munch away at the woodwork, hidden from sight.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:32.640
[Guest]: You want to disturb nothing. Each space in the house has a history, and it's as if everything in it casts a shadow, has a sort of ghost life.

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:38.640
[Guest]: You try to catch the shadows, to pin them down, but it is not easy.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:45.440
[Guest]: The harder you try, the more elusive becomes the business of shadows, and you come away with nothing.

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:52.440
[Guest]: You become obsessed with mirrors. Some mirrors are blind and reveal nothing.

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:58.440
[Guest]: There are others in which you look and find in your face your mother or your grandmother.

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:03.440
[Guest]: You see resemblances and patterns you had not noticed before.

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:12.240
[Guest]: You hold up your hand to the mirror and look at the blue veins on your hands that taper into the fingers with their neatly paired nails.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:17.240
[Guest]: The prominent, busy lines intersect and connect with the lesser ones,

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:23.240
[Guest]: like so many rivers meeting with their tributaries on the triangular delta of your hand.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:27.240
[Guest]: With a start you realise that it is your mother's hand you are looking at.

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:32.240
[Guest]: It is then that you know that you cannot ever be separated from your history.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:41.040
[Guest]: Your past is embedded in your body, but sometimes mirrors are false, distorted, damaged or askew.

00:08:41.240 --> 00:08:49.040
[Guest]: These are the abstract mirrors, mirrors that you have imagined into being and that can play a trick on you.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:58.040
[Guest]: There is a patch of black chillies in the garden, black leaves, deep mauve flowers and the little chillies like black tongues.

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:02.840
[Guest]: They look mysterious with a hint of virulence about them.

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:07.840
[Guest]: Watch out for those black tongues, they can put a hex on you.

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:12.840
[Guest]: The black tongues curse and the curse comes true.

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:19.840
[Guest]: You think of the chillies when you look at a photograph taken on Nowruz in the year 1971.

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:24.840
[Guest]: White was the colour for that year, it was the year of peace.

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:30.640
[Guest]: Everyone in the photo is dressed in white and all the food on the dastarkhan is also white.

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:39.640
[Guest]: You look at the faces in the photo and realise that all of those 12 people except for you and your sister are dead.

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:42.640
[Guest]: There is nothing strange about that, everyone dies.

00:09:42.840 --> 00:09:45.640
[Guest]: This is no narrative of loss.

00:09:45.840 --> 00:09:48.640
[Guest]: Dying is merely a function of living.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:55.440
[Guest]: But then you see your mother, she is wearing a white saree printed with a paisley pattern in green.

00:09:55.640 --> 00:10:01.440
[Guest]: Short-sighted, she always wears glasses and these particular ones have an onion pink frame.

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:06.440
[Guest]: The family has gathered round the teapot in the front veranda of the house.

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:14.440
[Guest]: Uncharacteristically, she does not participate at all in the conversation while a mysterious smile plays on her lips.

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:19.240
[Guest]: Quite suddenly, with an absolutely impassive face, she winks.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:24.240
[Guest]: Only then do you see that the lens from that side of her spectacles is missing.

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:32.240
[Guest]: It is a comic moment and everyone laughs but it also brings home to you that there is much that you do not see.

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:36.240
[Guest]: Your father comes to you when you are not thinking about him.

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:40.240
[Guest]: He is laughing, he does not speak but he laughs.

00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:45.040
[Guest]: His laughter is loud and resonant and the whole room rings with it.

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:51.040
[Guest]: It flows down the stairs in a stream of gushing sound and it gathers in a pool at the bottom of the steps.

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:58.040
[Guest]: It rests on the laburnum that is in full bloom, startling into flight a flock of roosting sparrows.

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:01.040
[Guest]: His body shakes, his eyes fill with tears.

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:05.040
[Guest]: It is not clear whether the laughter is happy or despairing.

00:11:05.040 --> 00:11:10.840
[Guest]: One day you enter a room and you find your brother sitting there.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:16.840
[Guest]: He leans back and closes his eyes, as he does when he does not want to listen to what is being said.

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:18.840
[Guest]: His wife is speaking.

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:20.840
[Guest]: She is always speaking.

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:24.840
[Guest]: A complicated web of lies floats just beneath her skin.

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:28.840
[Guest]: For 26 years he has tried to get to the meaning of what she says.

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:35.640
[Guest]: But the truth can just be glimpsed in flashes, for it can be found only in what she has not said.

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:37.640
[Guest]: None of this happens of course.

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:42.640
[Guest]: It cannot, because none of these people are here any longer.

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:50.640
[Guest]: It's the mirror again, your personal mirror that keeps reflecting the past moments of which your life is composed.

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:57.640
[Guest]: It invents some of those moments too and you can never be sure if something really happened.

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:03.440
[Guest]: The strange thing about living in the same house all your life is that you cannot go back to it,

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:08.440
[Guest]: because for you are still in it, and yet you keep going back.

00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:12.440
[Guest]: It is not the house that you are returning to, but a time.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:15.440
[Guest]: The house merely holds the accumulations of the years,

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:21.440
[Guest]: evidence to the many layers of living in it that are transposed one upon another.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:26.440
[Guest]: You turn the things of the house over in your hands, curious objects,

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:34.240
[Guest]: threadbare fabric, rusty biscuit tins holding loose clattering buttons of all description,

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:42.240
[Guest]: old watches that stopped long ago, opaque lamp chimneys, issues of Lilliput magazine yellowed with age,

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:45.240
[Guest]: and you don't want to let go of anything.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:50.240
[Guest]: For those things, unbeknownst to you, have become part of who you are.

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:53.240
[Guest]: Sitting on the terrace, you look about you.

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:59.040
[Guest]: The Algeria nervosa has spread its abundant foliage all over one side of the house.

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:02.040
[Guest]: It's the elephant creeper. It grows rapidly,

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:09.040
[Guest]: so quickly in fact that you feel it has grown another tendril or two in the moment that you looked away.

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:14.040
[Guest]: You wonder if its roots go as deep into the earth as the plant does into the air.

00:13:14.240 --> 00:13:18.040
[Guest]: It has the house, and you, firmly in its grip.

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:21.040
[Guest]: You shake yourself and try to leave.

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:27.840
[Guest]: You've been trying to leave for years, fearing that in this stationary town with its two rivers and its narrow roads,

00:13:28.040 --> 00:13:30.840
[Guest]: you will become a pumpkin or a gourd.

00:13:31.040 --> 00:13:33.840
[Guest]: You look at other houses in other cities.

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:36.840
[Guest]: Other lives flash across your mind.

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:39.840
[Guest]: Hypothetical lives lived hypothetically.

00:13:40.040 --> 00:13:42.840
[Guest]: For you know that you will never go away.

00:13:43.040 --> 00:13:46.840
[Guest]: The house will never let you go.

00:13:46.840 --> 00:13:52.640
[Amit Varma]: That's so beautiful and very moving and I love that image of a pumpkin or a gourd in this small town.

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:56.640
[Amit Varma]: This reminded me of a poem by Constantine Cavafy called The City. Have you read that?

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:58.640
[Amit Varma]: Oh yes, I love that poem. It's one of my favorites.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:00.640
[Guest]: Let me read it out for my listeners.

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:01.640
[Guest]: Yes, please.

00:14:01.840 --> 00:14:03.640
[Amit Varma]: This was so reminiscent of that.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:05.640
[Amit Varma]: The City by C.P. Cavafy.

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:10.640
[Amit Varma]: You said, I'll go to another country, go to another shore, find another city better than this one.

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:14.640
[Amit Varma]: Whatever I do is fated to turn out wrong and my heart lies buried like something dead.

00:14:14.640 --> 00:14:17.440
[Amit Varma]: How long can I let my mind moulder in this place?

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:21.440
[Amit Varma]: Wherever I turn, wherever I look, I see the black ruins of my life here

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:25.440
[Amit Varma]: where I've spent so many years, wasted them, destroyed them totally.

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And now there's a stop quote within the poem and the narrator continues.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:31.440
[Amit Varma]: You won't find a new country, won't find another shore.

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:33.440
[Amit Varma]: This city will always pursue you.

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:36.440
[Amit Varma]: You'll walk the same streets, grow old in the same neighborhoods,

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:38.440
[Amit Varma]: turn grey in these same houses.

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:40.440
[Amit Varma]: You'll always end up in this city.

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:41.440
[Amit Varma]: Don't hope for things elsewhere.

00:14:41.640 --> 00:14:43.440
[Amit Varma]: There's no ship for you, there's no road.

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:46.240
[Amit Varma]: Now that you wasted your life here in this small corner,

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:48.240
[Amit Varma]: you've destroyed it everywhere in the world.

00:14:48.440 --> 00:14:49.240
[Amit Varma]: Beautiful.

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:50.240
[Guest]: It's such a lovely poem.

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:51.240
[Guest]: It's a very nice poem.

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:52.240
[Guest]: I love that.

00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:54.240
[Guest]: I mean, Cavafy is also one of my favorite poets.

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:55.240
[Guest]: Wow.

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:58.240
[Guest]: Out of the other poems, I like this one too.

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:01.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I kind of love this one the most actually out of all his work

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:03.240
[Guest]: because it speaks so much to me.

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:05.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, yeah, exactly.

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:09.240
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, one of the things that I think all our listeners would have noticed

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:12.240
[Amit Varma]: while you read that passage out and that I constantly kept noticing

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:14.040
[Amit Varma]: when I read all your essays and your stories,

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:17.040
[Amit Varma]: and I'll come back to that, you know, as we reach those particular pieces,

00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:19.040
[Amit Varma]: is your power of observation.

00:15:19.240 --> 00:15:22.040
[Amit Varma]: Like all these little details that you're coming out with.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:25.040
[Amit Varma]: Like one thing I tell my writing students all the time is avoid the abstract.

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:26.040
[Amit Varma]: Go for the concrete.

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:28.040
[Amit Varma]: There's a lot of richness there.

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:32.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, I'm kind of curious about is this power of observation

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:35.040
[Amit Varma]: something that was always part of you

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:39.040
[Amit Varma]: or is it something that you felt the need to cultivate as a writer

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:41.040
[Amit Varma]: because another sort of journey you've spoken about

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:42.840
[Amit Varma]: is of being a young writer.

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:45.840
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, you've spoken of the bungalows of Allahabad

00:15:46.040 --> 00:15:47.840
[Amit Varma]: and how they were also far away from each other

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:51.840
[Amit Varma]: and you were like an island and you had no sense of that larger society around you.

00:15:52.040 --> 00:15:53.840
[Amit Varma]: So you were like a writer without material.

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:56.840
[Amit Varma]: You knew there was a writer inside you, but you had no material,

00:15:57.040 --> 00:15:58.840
[Amit Varma]: which is how when I look back on my 20s,

00:15:59.040 --> 00:16:01.840
[Amit Varma]: it was kind of exactly like that, that you want to write,

00:16:02.040 --> 00:16:03.840
[Amit Varma]: but you haven't lived enough to write.

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:06.840
[Amit Varma]: So this acute power of observation,

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:09.840
[Amit Varma]: has it always been there even before you had this consciousness

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:11.640
[Amit Varma]: of wanting to write?

00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:18.640
[Guest]: Amit, I think the power of observation also comes from dullness.

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:22.640
[Guest]: I know it sounds like the complete opposite of what we are trying to get at,

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:27.640
[Guest]: but it's the dull day on which nothing is happening.

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:30.640
[Guest]: You are there quietly by yourself and you're looking around,

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:32.640
[Guest]: you're looking at things.

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:36.640
[Guest]: So you tend to notice much more because your mind is not distracted

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:41.440
[Guest]: and I mean what you said about the bungalows and how I lived,

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:45.440
[Guest]: I mean I spent my early years and I still do in fact live in the same bungalow,

00:16:45.640 --> 00:16:47.440
[Guest]: though the city itself has changed quite a lot.

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:51.440
[Guest]: But my early years were very quiet years in the sense that nothing was happening.

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:54.440
[Guest]: These bungalows, Allahabad is a city of bungalows

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:56.440
[Guest]: that had been built by the Brits long ago

00:16:56.640 --> 00:16:59.440
[Guest]: and many of those bungalows have now gone.

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:03.440
[Guest]: They've been demolished, but ours is one of the few bungalows that remains.

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:07.240
[Guest]: So my life in those bungalows was one of solitude.

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:10.240
[Guest]: I would say even as a child, I mean there were not many people to be met

00:17:10.440 --> 00:17:16.240
[Guest]: and neighbours were far away and we were not really particularly interacting with the neighbours.

00:17:16.440 --> 00:17:21.240
[Guest]: So it was a lot of space around you and you could sort of wander about in that space,

00:17:21.440 --> 00:17:25.240
[Guest]: climb trees, I even chewed leaves to find out if they're poisonous.

00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:27.240
[Guest]: Were they? Obviously not.

00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:29.240
[Guest]: Yeah, so I survived that.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:32.240
[Guest]: But I mean there were all these experiments that could be done

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:35.040
[Guest]: and you could just observe nature and observe.

00:17:35.240 --> 00:17:40.040
[Guest]: I mean it became like examining everything under a microscope really

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:45.040
[Guest]: because I mean nothing else was going on to take your attention.

00:17:45.240 --> 00:17:48.040
[Guest]: There were birds, bird calls, all these things you were noticing.

00:17:48.240 --> 00:17:53.040
[Guest]: So it was in a sense an idyllic life, but of course it was far away from other people.

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:58.040
[Guest]: So while writing stories, one also has to know those people

00:17:58.240 --> 00:18:01.040
[Guest]: and in India that already comes with a challenge

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:06.840
[Guest]: because all the names for instance of people, they come with their background.

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:11.840
[Guest]: You know, Mr. Jhunjhunwala or Mr. Gupta or Mr. Srivastava, Mrs. Dhondi or whatever,

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:18.840
[Guest]: you know, these people all have different sets of geographical and also cultural sort of features.

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:23.840
[Guest]: So you already don't have that, which was what I found difficult in the beginning

00:18:24.040 --> 00:18:26.840
[Guest]: when I started to write that living in a bungalow like this,

00:18:26.840 --> 00:18:32.640
[Guest]: basically you don't really, I mean there's the linguistic aspect also of it,

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:36.640
[Guest]: which is that in the kind of house that I grew up,

00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:39.640
[Guest]: there were many books and books in several languages

00:18:39.840 --> 00:18:44.640
[Guest]: and the languages that I heard around me like we spoke Hindustani at home,

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:50.640
[Guest]: in school it was English and we were supposed to be fined if we spoke in Hindi.

00:18:50.840 --> 00:18:52.640
[Guest]: So that never really happened.

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:54.640
[Guest]: I mean we were not fined and people spoke in Hindi all the time,

00:18:54.640 --> 00:18:59.440
[Guest]: but that was the thing that they did not encourage speaking in Hindi in school

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:04.440
[Guest]: and at home we were embarrassed to speak in English

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:07.440
[Guest]: because our family had a sort of linguistic pride.

00:19:07.640 --> 00:19:11.440
[Guest]: I did not sort of, nobody, none of us spoke in English at home

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:15.440
[Guest]: and then there was the Avadhi that was spoken around us like people,

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:19.440
[Guest]: the servants for instance, they spoke Avadhi and other people around

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:22.440
[Guest]: who had a rural background, they were speaking in Avadhi.

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:26.240
[Guest]: My grandmother spoke Bhojpuri because I mean she came from,

00:19:26.440 --> 00:19:30.240
[Guest]: I mean from that side, further east UP,

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:34.240
[Guest]: Banaras was mine, I mean Lamahi, actually that's a village called Lamahi

00:19:34.440 --> 00:19:39.240
[Guest]: which is about three miles away from Banaras and there's Bhojpuri spoken over there.

00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:44.240
[Guest]: So she would speak Bhojpuri and Bangla, my father was a fluent Bangla speaker

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:47.240
[Guest]: and well he spoke Bangla quite obviously.

00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:50.240
[Guest]: If he found out that you knew Bangla, he would always prefer to speak in Bangla

00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:53.040
[Guest]: and not in Hindi or Bhojpuri, but he spoke to his mother in Bhojpuri.

00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:58.040
[Guest]: So there was all these sort of sounds sort of falling,

00:19:58.240 --> 00:20:01.040
[Guest]: kind of multilingual sort of thing that was constantly

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:05.040
[Guest]: and that's not my situation particularly in India

00:20:05.240 --> 00:20:08.040
[Guest]: because there are many people who would have a similar experience

00:20:08.240 --> 00:20:10.040
[Guest]: of many languages being spoken around them.

00:20:10.240 --> 00:20:13.040
[Guest]: So there was this thing of which language to write in.

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:17.040
[Guest]: When I started out writing, I mean I wondered because English,

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:19.840
[Guest]: I was quite fluent with English, my reading was in English,

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:21.840
[Guest]: in school we were taught to write in English.

00:20:22.040 --> 00:20:24.840
[Guest]: So it seemed that perhaps one should write in English,

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:27.840
[Guest]: but then while speaking I was more comfortable with Hindustani.

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:30.840
[Guest]: So there was this whole struggle going on,

00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:34.840
[Guest]: groping for language as it were, which language to write in

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:40.840
[Guest]: and this sort of lack of a language and then the lack of material

00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:43.840
[Guest]: because I didn't really know anyone around.

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:47.640
[Guest]: So all these kind of added up to a sort of angst about writing,

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:50.640
[Guest]: which I was not able to overcome for a very long time

00:20:50.840 --> 00:20:53.640
[Guest]: and this flight of writing from writing fiction

00:20:53.840 --> 00:20:56.640
[Guest]: pursued me for a long time, long long time.

00:20:56.840 --> 00:21:00.640
[Guest]: And I think finally in my 40s I started writing something like that.

00:21:00.840 --> 00:21:03.640
[Amit Varma]: So I'll take your point about dullness being a factor for noticing,

00:21:03.840 --> 00:21:07.640
[Amit Varma]: but the point is generations of people went through the similar dullness

00:21:07.840 --> 00:21:11.640
[Amit Varma]: and didn't emerge with, didn't have those powers of observation frankly.

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:15.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean I kind of didn't, I mean that is if there is one thing that I think I lacked,

00:21:15.640 --> 00:21:19.440
[Amit Varma]: it was this looking at everything with that acute glance.

00:21:19.640 --> 00:21:22.440
[Amit Varma]: Very often I've kind of eaten a meal and you could ask me later

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:24.440
[Amit Varma]: what did it taste like and I wouldn't have noticed

00:21:24.640 --> 00:21:26.440
[Unknown]: because that mindfulness is just not there.

00:21:26.640 --> 00:21:30.440
[Amit Varma]: So a lot of threads to pick up on, but when you spoke about languages,

00:21:30.640 --> 00:21:34.440
[Amit Varma]: like elsewhere you've spoken about how your mother Zerahera

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:38.440
[Amit Varma]: and her sister Mogul Mosud, you know they used to write in Urdu

00:21:38.440 --> 00:21:43.240
[Amit Varma]: and then they used to publish it in Hindi because you know easier to get published that way

00:21:43.440 --> 00:21:47.240
[Amit Varma]: and they would tell each other stories and they would add a first sound, F sound

00:21:47.440 --> 00:21:49.240
[Unknown]: so that other people couldn't make out what they were saying

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:52.240
[Unknown]: because this one consonant would be really prominent and all that.

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:57.240
[Amit Varma]: And I imagine that that would lead to a heightened mindfulness of language itself.

00:21:57.440 --> 00:22:02.240
[Amit Varma]: Like what is it doing, you know what, how are the different sounds interacting,

00:22:02.440 --> 00:22:05.240
[Amit Varma]: how does something sound, how different kind of words come together.

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:10.040
[Amit Varma]: Like the exact same example that I mentioned about food could be a very bad habit for a writer.

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:13.040
[Unknown]: If you're not mindful of language at all,

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:17.040
[Amit Varma]: and of course most of the writing one does is kind of an autopilot,

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:22.040
[Amit Varma]: but you arrive at that autopilot and you build that reflexive style by first being mindful.

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:25.040
[Unknown]: So was there a sense when you were kind of growing up,

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:27.040
[Amit Varma]: was there a sense where language was important,

00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:30.040
[Amit Varma]: were you thinking of language differently from say,

00:22:30.240 --> 00:22:33.040
[Amit Varma]: you know the people you went to school with at St. Mary's or whatever,

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:36.840
[Amit Varma]: was there that kind of close attention to what words are being used,

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:39.840
[Amit Varma]: how a story is being constructed and so on?

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:44.840
[Guest]: Well actually in my family, language was one thing that was constantly spoken about.

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:48.840
[Guest]: I mean people, if there was some word for instance that appeared that you did not know,

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:53.840
[Guest]: immediately a dictionary would be fished out and the word would be made clear.

00:22:54.040 --> 00:22:56.840
[Guest]: And also sometimes going to the root of that word,

00:22:57.040 --> 00:22:59.840
[Guest]: whether it was coming from Arabic or Persian or whatever,

00:22:59.840 --> 00:23:03.640
[Guest]: you know depends which language the word belonged to.

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:07.640
[Guest]: So there was this very heightened consciousness of language in my family

00:23:07.840 --> 00:23:12.640
[Guest]: and as you said, I mean my mother and my aunt both wrote their stories first in Urdu,

00:23:12.840 --> 00:23:14.640
[Guest]: which was their primary language.

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:20.640
[Guest]: And then because of ease of publication and just wider reach of publication,

00:23:20.840 --> 00:23:24.640
[Guest]: they switched and they wrote their scripts out again in Hindi.

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:30.440
[Guest]: And they were constantly, I mean their early education, they did not go to school.

00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:33.440
[Guest]: The Maulvi used to come at home to teach them.

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:38.440
[Guest]: And of course they had many tales about how they used to give the Maulvi the slip.

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:42.440
[Guest]: Like he would come and Maulvi Sahab was very fond of his opium.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:47.440
[Guest]: So he'd come and he'd sit down and he'd set them the work for that day

00:23:47.640 --> 00:23:50.440
[Guest]: and he'd put on, have his opium and then he'd fall into a deep sleep.

00:23:50.640 --> 00:23:53.440
[Guest]: So these kids, I mean they were really wicked kids I think.

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:57.240
[Guest]: I mean they were sort of, they were pretending to sort of move backward and forward

00:23:57.440 --> 00:24:00.240
[Guest]: learning their Farsi and learning their poetry and all that.

00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:06.240
[Guest]: And then they would go to the kitchen and pick up this huge tin thali from there

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:09.240
[Guest]: and bang on it with a huge stone.

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:13.240
[Guest]: So this sounded like the bell that came from the town hall at 12 o'clock or whatever

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:15.240
[Guest]: and they'd sort of, Maulvi Sahab would wake up suddenly and say,

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:17.240
[Guest]: oh what was that? Is it time?

00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:20.240
[Guest]: As the gajar baj gaya, gajar bajta tha.

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:22.240
[Guest]: So gajar baj gaya meant that his lesson was over.

00:24:22.240 --> 00:24:26.040
[Guest]: So haan haan Maulvi Sahab, humlo toh ek ghante se padh rahe hain.

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:29.040
[Guest]: And then he'd shuffle off and the lesson would be over

00:24:29.240 --> 00:24:33.040
[Guest]: and then they'd be free to do all their little pranks all over the place.

00:24:33.240 --> 00:24:36.040
[Guest]: So I mean, so they never really had a formal education in that sense

00:24:36.240 --> 00:24:39.040
[Guest]: but even so they were really well versed in their Farsi

00:24:39.240 --> 00:24:42.040
[Guest]: and they would do and they knew all these couplets

00:24:42.240 --> 00:24:45.040
[Guest]: and for every occasion they'd come up with a suitable couplet.

00:24:45.240 --> 00:24:50.040
[Guest]: So all this whole thing of many languages was already there at home.

00:24:50.040 --> 00:24:54.840
[Guest]: You know, one could hear this and these languages sort of went into

00:24:55.040 --> 00:24:57.840
[Guest]: a sleeping pool of languages, I would say, inside me

00:24:58.040 --> 00:24:59.840
[Guest]: which never emerged at that point.

00:25:00.040 --> 00:25:02.840
[Guest]: But there's this whole mysterious thing about writing

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:06.840
[Guest]: that when you sit down to write, it's like one word follows another

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:11.840
[Guest]: and somehow what emerges is what you may have felt say 40 years ago

00:25:12.040 --> 00:25:14.840
[Guest]: and you don't know which bird it was singing in the pine tree

00:25:15.040 --> 00:25:17.840
[Guest]: on which particular Sunday or which line someone said

00:25:17.840 --> 00:25:20.640
[Guest]: that is suddenly going to surface when you're writing

00:25:20.840 --> 00:25:23.640
[Guest]: and you will not be able to think of that when you're actually not writing.

00:25:23.840 --> 00:25:26.640
[Guest]: So it's a very mysterious and a very magical process.

00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:28.640
[Guest]: So language too is part of that.

00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:31.640
[Guest]: You know, the words for these things come when you're actually writing them

00:25:31.840 --> 00:25:33.640
[Guest]: and they are somewhere in your submerged memory

00:25:33.840 --> 00:25:34.640
[Guest]: and you don't remember them.

00:25:34.840 --> 00:25:38.640
[Guest]: If you consciously try to remember them, they will not come out.

00:25:38.840 --> 00:25:41.640
[Guest]: So that's how languages have worked for me.

00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:46.640
[Guest]: You know, it's something, it's more a process of absorption.

00:25:46.640 --> 00:25:49.440
[Guest]: You know, it's just something that is going inside you

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:51.440
[Guest]: and is waiting for that time.

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:55.440
[Guest]: So, I mean, when you put it down on paper,

00:25:55.640 --> 00:25:59.440
[Guest]: it's just something just, it's like when you put this lemon juice on,

00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:02.440
[Guest]: you know, if you write something with lemon juice and you iron it,

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:04.440
[Guest]: then the writing appears, otherwise it's invisible.

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:06.440
[Guest]: So it's a bit like that, you know.

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:08.440
[Guest]: So these things are already within you

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:12.440
[Guest]: and when you write, they just, you recognize them rather than remember them.

00:26:12.640 --> 00:26:15.440
[Amit Varma]: That's beautiful. So the writing is already there

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:17.240
[Unknown]: and the process of writing is like the act of ironing.

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:20.240
[Unknown]: Yes, yes, absolutely.

00:26:20.440 --> 00:26:23.240
[Amit Varma]: I'm also fascinated by a sort of another thread

00:26:23.440 --> 00:26:25.240
[Amit Varma]: that came up when you were reading that piece

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:27.240
[Amit Varma]: that comes up now, that comes up in your other work,

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:29.240
[Amit Varma]: which is sort of the thread of memory.

00:26:29.440 --> 00:26:31.240
[Amit Varma]: Like I did an episode with Anshul Malhotra

00:26:31.440 --> 00:26:34.240
[Amit Varma]: who had done a very fine book on partition.

00:26:34.440 --> 00:26:37.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, just looking at the objects people carried with them

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:40.240
[Amit Varma]: during partition and the memories that they carried.

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:42.240
[Amit Varma]: And like while researching for that,

00:26:42.240 --> 00:26:46.040
[Amit Varma]: one of the things I realized was that how memory works in the brain

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:49.040
[Amit Varma]: is that when you remember something, you're remembering what happened.

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:53.040
[Amit Varma]: But every subsequent time you're remembering the last remembering of it.

00:26:53.240 --> 00:26:56.040
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, over a period of time,

00:26:56.240 --> 00:26:59.040
[Amit Varma]: your memories can grow richer or can fade

00:26:59.240 --> 00:27:01.040
[Amit Varma]: or can have other layers painted onto them by whatever,

00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:04.040
[Amit Varma]: which is why, you know, sometimes if you shared a memory

00:27:04.240 --> 00:27:07.040
[Amit Varma]: with someone 20 years ago and you both discuss it,

00:27:07.240 --> 00:27:10.040
[Amit Varma]: you might find that both of you remember it completely differently.

00:27:10.040 --> 00:27:12.840
[Unknown]: While one would assume the instant after it happened,

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:13.840
[Amit Varma]: it would have been the same thing.

00:27:14.040 --> 00:27:15.840
[Amit Varma]: But over time, it's kind of changed.

00:27:16.040 --> 00:27:18.840
[Amit Varma]: And what I find in your essays and so on

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:21.840
[Amit Varma]: is that there is a lot of very deep remembering.

00:27:22.040 --> 00:27:25.840
[Amit Varma]: And I say deep remembering, not just in a sense of events,

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:28.840
[Amit Varma]: but also all these impressionistic details

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:30.840
[Amit Varma]: that are kind of all over the place.

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:34.840
[Amit Varma]: I saw my father struggle with Parkinson's before he passed away.

00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:37.840
[Amit Varma]: And his memory was kind of going before that for a few years.

00:27:37.840 --> 00:27:41.640
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that, one of the common phenomena

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:45.640
[Amit Varma]: in people whose memory goes in old age and which I saw in my father

00:27:45.840 --> 00:27:47.640
[Amit Varma]: was that the edges remain very stark.

00:27:47.840 --> 00:27:49.640
[Amit Varma]: So you remember what happened yesterday

00:27:49.840 --> 00:27:51.640
[Amit Varma]: and you remember what happened when you were 10

00:27:51.840 --> 00:27:55.640
[Amit Varma]: and it's those middle periods which kind of tend to go.

00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:58.640
[Amit Varma]: And I remember once he asked me that, you know,

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:00.640
[Amit Varma]: what were you like growing up? Because I don't remember.

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:02.640
[Amit Varma]: I think about that because when I look back

00:28:02.840 --> 00:28:04.640
[Amit Varma]: on my own process of remembering things,

00:28:04.840 --> 00:28:06.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, some people that never had meaning

00:28:06.640 --> 00:28:09.440
[Amit Varma]: suddenly have meaning because of the way I have changed

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:13.440
[Amit Varma]: or just the nature of memory changes and one forgets so much.

00:28:13.640 --> 00:28:18.440
[Amit Varma]: So since you have both been someone who is playing around a lot

00:28:18.640 --> 00:28:20.440
[Amit Varma]: in that pool of memories, both in your writing

00:28:20.640 --> 00:28:23.440
[Amit Varma]: and I'm sure in these autobiographical essays as well,

00:28:23.640 --> 00:28:24.440
[Amit Varma]: which I can't wait to read.

00:28:24.640 --> 00:28:27.440
[Amit Varma]: And as someone who is deeply self-reflective,

00:28:27.640 --> 00:28:29.440
[Amit Varma]: what are sort of your thoughts on this?

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:32.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there a sense in which your life at 10

00:28:32.640 --> 00:28:35.440
[Amit Varma]: is being more richly lived now than it was when you were 10?

00:28:35.440 --> 00:28:40.240
[Guest]: I think that is true because actually I have always thought,

00:28:40.440 --> 00:28:42.240
[Guest]: in fact, I wrote about this in my novel also,

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:45.240
[Guest]: that the past actually never dies.

00:28:45.440 --> 00:28:48.240
[Guest]: The past becomes present for you when you remember it.

00:28:48.440 --> 00:28:51.240
[Guest]: So in a sense, there is no past.

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:54.240
[Guest]: I mean, everything, at the moment of remembering,

00:28:54.440 --> 00:28:58.240
[Guest]: you are living it, right? I mean, sort of, it's just there for you.

00:28:58.440 --> 00:29:01.240
[Guest]: So, and also memory is changing.

00:29:01.440 --> 00:29:03.240
[Guest]: You said that you may remember something

00:29:03.240 --> 00:29:05.040
[Guest]: and last time it was completely different.

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:07.040
[Guest]: I think that's what fiction is all about.

00:29:07.240 --> 00:29:09.040
[Guest]: Perhaps life is a fiction, you know,

00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:12.040
[Guest]: because you live things and later you remember them.

00:29:12.240 --> 00:29:13.040
[Guest]: It's something else you remember

00:29:13.240 --> 00:29:16.040
[Guest]: and when you're writing about it, some other thing happens.

00:29:16.240 --> 00:29:20.040
[Guest]: You know, so it's all part of this whole mysterious universe of words

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:23.040
[Guest]: and memories and how words recall those memories,

00:29:23.240 --> 00:29:25.040
[Guest]: which keeps changing.

00:29:25.240 --> 00:29:29.040
[Guest]: And if two people have, say, been through some incident together,

00:29:29.240 --> 00:29:32.040
[Guest]: their remembering of it can be completely different.

00:29:32.040 --> 00:29:32.840
[Guest]: We just don't know.

00:29:33.040 --> 00:29:36.840
[Guest]: It's also the individual perception of things that comes into play

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:39.840
[Guest]: and some person may remember a certain thing about that day,

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:41.840
[Guest]: the other person may remember something else.

00:29:42.040 --> 00:29:44.840
[Guest]: So it just becomes like that, different memories.

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:49.840
[Guest]: So it sees various layers and various sort of submersions,

00:29:50.040 --> 00:29:52.840
[Guest]: I would say, and things that you come up with

00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:56.840
[Guest]: that just add to the whole persona of the writer, I think.

00:29:57.040 --> 00:29:59.840
[Guest]: I mean, it's just, people do a lot of detective work.

00:29:59.840 --> 00:30:02.640
[Guest]: For instance, when you're writing something, you publish a story.

00:30:02.840 --> 00:30:04.640
[Guest]: So people go, oh, this is about this one.

00:30:04.840 --> 00:30:07.640
[Guest]: You know, people say, and it's a very irritating question for any writer

00:30:07.840 --> 00:30:10.640
[Guest]: because when I'm writing, for instance,

00:30:10.840 --> 00:30:12.640
[Guest]: the story has to be grounded somewhere.

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:14.640
[Guest]: You can't base it in some fictional place.

00:30:14.840 --> 00:30:17.640
[Guest]: It has to be a place that you know and you can write the details of.

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:21.640
[Guest]: But the story itself, when it's put into that background,

00:30:21.840 --> 00:30:24.640
[Guest]: into that ground, rather, is a fictional story.

00:30:24.840 --> 00:30:28.640
[Guest]: So, I mean, it's not about so-and-so or, you know,

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:31.440
[Guest]: people always try to find parallels,

00:30:31.640 --> 00:30:35.440
[Guest]: especially people who know you try to find parallels in your stories.

00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:38.440
[Guest]: But I think that is a completely sort of

00:30:38.640 --> 00:30:42.440
[Guest]: not a good way of looking at sort of writing like that.

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:47.440
[Guest]: But I think we live our lives largely as fiction, you know,

00:30:47.640 --> 00:30:51.440
[Guest]: and the memories that get created are also fiction from that point of view.

00:30:51.640 --> 00:30:53.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, fascinating to think of it like that.

00:30:53.640 --> 00:30:55.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit more about your childhood because,

00:30:55.440 --> 00:30:59.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, got this collection of your grandfather Munshi Premchand's

00:30:59.440 --> 00:31:03.240
[Amit Varma]: collected stories, which had an introduction by you.

00:31:03.440 --> 00:31:06.240
[Amit Varma]: And in that introduction, you wrote, and I'll read this bit out.

00:31:06.440 --> 00:31:08.240
[Amit Varma]: A mention of Babuji would crop up in conversation,

00:31:08.440 --> 00:31:10.240
[Amit Varma]: the simplicity with which he chose to live his life,

00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:12.240
[Amit Varma]: his idealism and high moral standards,

00:31:12.440 --> 00:31:14.240
[Amit Varma]: his loud and infectious laughter,

00:31:14.440 --> 00:31:17.240
[Amit Varma]: his writing at odd hours of the night, early in the morning,

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:19.240
[Amit Varma]: often by light of a hurricane lamp,

00:31:19.440 --> 00:31:21.240
[Amit Varma]: his commitment to the oppressed and downtrodden,

00:31:21.440 --> 00:31:23.240
[Amit Varma]: his belief that money corrupts.

00:31:23.240 --> 00:31:26.040
[Amit Varma]: The notion that being poor is somehow spiritually exalting,

00:31:26.240 --> 00:31:30.040
[Amit Varma]: a little hypocritically permeated the atmosphere in our well-to-do home,

00:31:30.240 --> 00:31:34.040
[Amit Varma]: so much so that as a child, when asked once what I'd like to be when I grew up,

00:31:34.240 --> 00:31:36.040
[Amit Varma]: I answered that I'd like to be poor.

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:39.040
[Amit Varma]: His inability to clear a qualifying entrance exam for college

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:40.040
[Amit Varma]: because his maths was weak,

00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:42.040
[Amit Varma]: the particular vegetables he'd been advised not to eat

00:31:42.240 --> 00:31:44.040
[Amit Varma]: because of his poor digestion,

00:31:44.240 --> 00:31:46.040
[Amit Varma]: talk about him was frequent and he was never far from us,

00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:48.040
[Amit Varma]: hovering benignly in our consciousness,

00:31:48.240 --> 00:31:51.040
[Amit Varma]: a somewhat larger-than-life figure in the family cupboard

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:52.840
[Amit Varma]: to be thought of with pride, stop quote.

00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:56.840
[Amit Varma]: How was it like growing up in Premchand's household,

00:31:57.040 --> 00:31:58.840
[Amit Varma]: whose outside the household, of course,

00:31:59.040 --> 00:32:01.840
[Amit Varma]: is a legend and much loved by people in a very visceral way,

00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:03.840
[Amit Varma]: as you go on to describe later in the essay,

00:32:04.040 --> 00:32:05.840
[Amit Varma]: but at the same time,

00:32:06.040 --> 00:32:09.840
[Amit Varma]: like your answer about how I'd like to be poor when I grow up,

00:32:10.040 --> 00:32:13.840
[Amit Varma]: I guess, did that aura of Premchand,

00:32:14.040 --> 00:32:17.840
[Amit Varma]: and also your family was very literary,

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:20.640
[Amit Varma]: both your parents were artists and they were accomplished,

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:24.640
[Amit Varma]: in fact, your grandmother herself was a very formidable person

00:32:24.840 --> 00:32:26.640
[Amit Varma]: and I'll ask you more about her later,

00:32:26.840 --> 00:32:28.640
[Amit Varma]: but growing up then, as you did,

00:32:28.840 --> 00:32:30.640
[Amit Varma]: what was that like?

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:32.640
[Amit Varma]: Did it set you apart from everyone else?

00:32:32.840 --> 00:32:35.640
[Amit Varma]: Did you have this sort of feeling that I have to live up to this?

00:32:35.840 --> 00:32:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Like earlier you mentioned you were scared to speak English at home

00:32:37.840 --> 00:32:40.640
[Amit Varma]: because, hey, you know, the greatest Hindi writer is home.

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:44.640
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how that played out.

00:32:44.640 --> 00:32:48.440
[Guest]: It was actually a fear of standing apart, you know, I mean,

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:52.440
[Guest]: because in school, I mean, in the Hindi book,

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:55.440
[Guest]: obviously, I mean, every year we would have a Premchand story

00:32:55.640 --> 00:32:57.440
[Guest]: in the book that we were taught

00:32:57.640 --> 00:33:00.440
[Guest]: and I would sort of think of it with dread,

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:02.440
[Guest]: the day when that story would be read,

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:04.440
[Guest]: because the teacher would point me out at once.

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:06.440
[Guest]: Oh, that's her grandfather who wrote this

00:33:06.640 --> 00:33:08.440
[Guest]: and everyone would turn around to look at me.

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:11.440
[Guest]: So it was a moment of pride for me,

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:13.440
[Guest]: but it was also a moment of dread.

00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:16.240
[Guest]: I was a very shy child, I was a pathologically shy child

00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:18.240
[Guest]: and then to have everyone notice you

00:33:18.440 --> 00:33:21.240
[Guest]: and, you know, maybe talk about you, think about you.

00:33:21.440 --> 00:33:23.240
[Guest]: So all that somehow made you stand apart

00:33:23.440 --> 00:33:26.240
[Guest]: and it was not something that I quite enjoyed.

00:33:26.440 --> 00:33:29.240
[Guest]: Inside, I was very pleased that, look, my grandfather was so great

00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:31.240
[Guest]: that everyone knows about him and all that.

00:33:31.440 --> 00:33:33.240
[Guest]: But it was his very largeness,

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:36.240
[Guest]: the very, you know, his greatness outside the home

00:33:36.440 --> 00:33:39.240
[Guest]: that made him somehow out of reach for me.

00:33:39.440 --> 00:33:41.240
[Guest]: I mean, of course, I read the stories.

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:43.040
[Guest]: Firstly, we all went to an English medium school.

00:33:43.240 --> 00:33:45.040
[Guest]: So Hindi was not a language

00:33:45.240 --> 00:33:47.040
[Guest]: that one was reading on a regular basis.

00:33:47.240 --> 00:33:50.040
[Guest]: Of course, one read the textbook and all that,

00:33:50.240 --> 00:33:53.040
[Guest]: but I actually came to reading Hindi much later.

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:56.040
[Guest]: I've also discussed this in that essay that I wrote,

00:33:56.240 --> 00:33:59.040
[Guest]: when my father was choosing stories for Kahani

00:33:59.240 --> 00:34:02.040
[Guest]: and all these whole bunch of stories would come

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:04.040
[Guest]: and, you know, there were too many.

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:06.040
[Guest]: So he'd asked me also to sift through some of them.

00:34:06.240 --> 00:34:08.040
[Guest]: So then I started reading Hindi.

00:34:08.040 --> 00:34:11.040
[Guest]: But Hindi literature as such, as far as Premchand went,

00:34:11.240 --> 00:34:13.840
[Guest]: I had not really read very much Premchand when I was a child.

00:34:14.040 --> 00:34:16.840
[Guest]: And also there was this feeling somehow that

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:19.840
[Guest]: I'm related to him, you somehow have inhaled his writing

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:21.840
[Guest]: without having read it.

00:34:22.040 --> 00:34:23.840
[Guest]: You know, this very peculiar feeling.

00:34:24.040 --> 00:34:25.840
[Guest]: So that was there too.

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:27.840
[Guest]: And then slowly, of course,

00:34:28.040 --> 00:34:30.840
[Guest]: one became aware of the writing

00:34:31.040 --> 00:34:33.840
[Guest]: and I read it much later in my college years

00:34:34.040 --> 00:34:35.840
[Guest]: and when this Kahani thing happened

00:34:35.840 --> 00:34:38.640
[Guest]: and one was reading more comfortably in Hindi,

00:34:38.840 --> 00:34:41.640
[Guest]: I actually tutored myself to read in Hindi

00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:43.640
[Guest]: and to write in Hindi because,

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:45.640
[Guest]: when people used to ask me,

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:48.640
[Guest]: even when my collection of Hindi stories had been published,

00:34:48.840 --> 00:34:50.640
[Guest]: that did you write them in Roman?

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:52.640
[Guest]: How did you write them in Hindi?

00:34:52.840 --> 00:34:55.640
[Guest]: It was always this linguistic kind of migration

00:34:55.840 --> 00:34:57.640
[Guest]: that was happening all the time in me.

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:00.640
[Guest]: I was thinking in Hindi or sometimes in English sometimes

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:03.640
[Guest]: and the reading and the writing were crossing

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:06.440
[Guest]: and the whole process of translation, for instance,

00:35:06.640 --> 00:35:09.440
[Guest]: also began as a sort of groping for language

00:35:09.640 --> 00:35:12.440
[Guest]: and which language is as to find

00:35:12.640 --> 00:35:15.440
[Guest]: which language was I was the most comfortable in.

00:35:15.640 --> 00:35:17.440
[Guest]: And that process has never really changed.

00:35:17.640 --> 00:35:19.440
[Guest]: It's still the same, you know, I still fumble.

00:35:19.640 --> 00:35:20.440
[Guest]: I still fumble.

00:35:20.640 --> 00:35:22.440
[Guest]: I think maybe this will be better in English,

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:24.440
[Guest]: that this will be better in Hindi.

00:35:24.640 --> 00:35:27.440
[Guest]: The knowledge of Urdu also complicated it a little bit

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:30.440
[Guest]: because then there's Urdu also to be reckoned with, you know.

00:35:30.640 --> 00:35:32.440
[Guest]: So, I mean, it's all these,

00:35:32.440 --> 00:35:34.240
[Guest]: but I don't think of them as a disadvantage.

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:37.240
[Guest]: Rather, they contributed to a kind of richness of voice.

00:35:37.440 --> 00:35:39.240
[Guest]: I think if you know other languages,

00:35:39.440 --> 00:35:41.240
[Guest]: they are always pushing up between,

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:43.240
[Guest]: beneath the language that you're writing in.

00:35:43.440 --> 00:35:47.240
[Guest]: So, you get a sense of a larger sort of linguistic culture

00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:49.240
[Guest]: when you're writing, say, in Hindi, for instance.

00:35:49.440 --> 00:35:51.240
[Guest]: I like to write in Hindi because

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:53.240
[Guest]: things around me are happening in Hindi, you know.

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:56.240
[Guest]: I mean, everything that's taking place is happening in Hindi

00:35:56.440 --> 00:35:58.240
[Guest]: and Hindi also has the advantage

00:35:58.440 --> 00:36:01.240
[Guest]: that you can lace it with things from other languages

00:36:01.240 --> 00:36:03.040
[Guest]: like registers are important.

00:36:03.240 --> 00:36:06.040
[Guest]: For instance, if there's someone who's swearing

00:36:06.240 --> 00:36:09.040
[Guest]: or some vendors calling out,

00:36:09.240 --> 00:36:12.040
[Guest]: you know, jamun, kali hai, dilwali hai,

00:36:12.240 --> 00:36:14.040
[Guest]: you know, little phrases like that

00:36:14.240 --> 00:36:16.040
[Guest]: which are impossible to translate in English.

00:36:16.240 --> 00:36:20.040
[Guest]: And English already has a sort of middle-class feel to it.

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:23.040
[Guest]: I mean, it seems to me that middle-class homes,

00:36:23.240 --> 00:36:28.040
[Guest]: only people in middle-class homes mostly know English.

00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:30.040
[Guest]: And that is the world that they know.

00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:32.840
[Guest]: So, when you write about a person walking on the street,

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:35.840
[Guest]: you can't do street speak in English

00:36:36.040 --> 00:36:39.840
[Guest]: because the speech is actually much more colourful

00:36:40.040 --> 00:36:41.840
[Guest]: in the colloquial language.

00:36:42.040 --> 00:36:43.840
[Guest]: So, English has that disadvantage.

00:36:44.040 --> 00:36:45.840
[Guest]: I mean, it has sort of,

00:36:46.040 --> 00:36:50.840
[Guest]: the reach is not as great as the regional languages, I think.

00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:54.840
[Guest]: So, I mean, it's a whole world that is closed

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:57.840
[Guest]: in a sense to the writer in English, I feel.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:01.640
[Guest]: I mean, of course, people are writing, but somehow,

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:04.640
[Guest]: I mean, I feel that the languages can get that much better.

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:07.640
[Guest]: Hindi, for instance, which is why I decided.

00:37:07.840 --> 00:37:10.640
[Guest]: And my father, of course, wanted me to write in Hindi.

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:13.640
[Guest]: So, that was also one reason why I started writing,

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:15.640
[Guest]: started thinking about writing in Hindi.

00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:18.640
[Guest]: But there was this whole lot of other reasons too.

00:37:18.840 --> 00:37:20.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think you mentioned in your essay

00:37:20.840 --> 00:37:23.640
[Amit Varma]: that your father had this belief that whatever is the language of your birth,

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:25.640
[Unknown]: your mother tongue, you must write in it.

00:37:25.640 --> 00:37:28.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, Premchand once said that he wrote Hindi in the morning,

00:37:28.640 --> 00:37:30.440
[Amit Varma]: Urdu in the afternoon, stop quote.

00:37:30.640 --> 00:37:33.440
[Amit Varma]: And he also used to take notes for his stories in English

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:36.440
[Amit Varma]: because it just seemed to lend itself to that,

00:37:36.640 --> 00:37:38.440
[Unknown]: the kind of economy of the language,

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:40.440
[Amit Varma]: the precision of the language and all of that.

00:37:40.640 --> 00:37:44.440
[Amit Varma]: And it just strikes me, as someone who's only really good at one of these languages,

00:37:44.640 --> 00:37:47.440
[Amit Varma]: the other languages I understand, I speak,

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:51.440
[Amit Varma]: but English is the only one I've really thought deeply about and written in.

00:37:51.640 --> 00:37:54.440
[Amit Varma]: And it just strikes me that they're all fundamentally

00:37:54.440 --> 00:37:56.240
[Amit Varma]: so different from each other that

00:37:56.440 --> 00:37:58.240
[Amit Varma]: there are things you can express in one

00:37:58.440 --> 00:38:01.240
[Amit Varma]: that you just cannot express in the other, for example.

00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:04.240
[Amit Varma]: So, is it then the case that the language that you then

00:38:04.440 --> 00:38:09.240
[Amit Varma]: choose to use at a particular moment is what is appropriate for that task?

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Like, I imagine if you were writing, say, a business-like email to your bank,

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:14.240
[Amit Varma]: you would, of course, do it in English

00:38:14.440 --> 00:38:16.240
[Amit Varma]: because you're just putting down a bunch of points.

00:38:16.440 --> 00:38:19.240
[Amit Varma]: But if you want to capture the ambience around your local paanwala,

00:38:19.440 --> 00:38:21.240
[Amit Varma]: you cannot capture that in English.

00:38:21.440 --> 00:38:23.240
[Amit Varma]: You have to do that in Hindi.

00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:26.040
[Amit Varma]: I just find that, you know, being multilingual myself,

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:28.040
[Amit Varma]: at least at a sense of speaking these languages,

00:38:28.240 --> 00:38:31.040
[Amit Varma]: I feel that I'm more fortunate than people in the West

00:38:31.240 --> 00:38:33.040
[Amit Varma]: who might only know one language

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:36.040
[Amit Varma]: because it's kind of richer this way.

00:38:36.240 --> 00:38:39.040
[Amit Varma]: So, is that something you feel at all?

00:38:39.240 --> 00:38:43.040
[Amit Varma]: And has there been like a process where you've come to peace

00:38:43.240 --> 00:38:47.040
[Amit Varma]: with knowing that you have all these languages

00:38:47.240 --> 00:38:50.040
[Amit Varma]: with all their different flavours for all their different uses

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:54.840
[Amit Varma]: and not have to think about, this is my language?

00:38:55.040 --> 00:38:58.840
[Guest]: I don't know if the question of which one is mine comes into it

00:38:59.040 --> 00:39:01.840
[Guest]: because, I mean, these are all the languages that compose

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:04.840
[Guest]: the universe that is around me, you know.

00:39:05.040 --> 00:39:07.840
[Guest]: And even if I'm, for instance, translating,

00:39:08.040 --> 00:39:10.840
[Guest]: the language that I choose to translate in will also,

00:39:11.040 --> 00:39:13.840
[Guest]: even if it's English, it will have different registers

00:39:14.040 --> 00:39:17.840
[Guest]: from what I have absorbed from my surroundings.

00:39:17.840 --> 00:39:21.640
[Guest]: So, all these languages compose the environment where I come from.

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:24.640
[Guest]: So, I don't really sort of think of it as this one is mine

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:26.640
[Guest]: and this one is not, you know.

00:39:26.840 --> 00:39:28.640
[Guest]: It's just something that you have grown up with

00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:30.640
[Guest]: and something that has become part of you.

00:39:30.840 --> 00:39:32.640
[Guest]: So, all these languages are part of me.

00:39:32.840 --> 00:39:35.640
[Guest]: English is something that I have read a lot in.

00:39:35.840 --> 00:39:38.640
[Guest]: Most of my reading, in fact, has been in English.

00:39:38.840 --> 00:39:40.640
[Guest]: This has also been an advantage in the sense that

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:43.640
[Guest]: it has shaped my sensibility in a certain way.

00:39:43.640 --> 00:39:48.440
[Guest]: And when you read something and it also kind of

00:39:48.640 --> 00:39:50.440
[Guest]: hones a kind of critical register in you.

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:53.440
[Guest]: So, when you read something else, for instance, in Hindi

00:39:53.640 --> 00:39:57.440
[Guest]: and you know the horizons that are there in Western literature,

00:39:57.640 --> 00:40:00.440
[Guest]: which is, you know, many other languages,

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:02.440
[Guest]: which, of course, we get those in translation,

00:40:02.640 --> 00:40:05.440
[Guest]: but even in translation, I mean, you can get a sense

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:09.440
[Guest]: of all these other worlds that exist outside India.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:14.240
[Guest]: And you sort of use that lens to look at what is around you,

00:40:14.440 --> 00:40:17.240
[Guest]: what you are reading, even in the languages what you are reading.

00:40:17.440 --> 00:40:19.240
[Guest]: So, you get a kind of critical faculty

00:40:19.440 --> 00:40:22.240
[Guest]: and your sensibility has got shaped by the reading.

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:25.240
[Guest]: So, reading has been very important for me.

00:40:25.440 --> 00:40:27.240
[Guest]: I mean, reading has been one of the primary things

00:40:27.440 --> 00:40:29.240
[Guest]: that I have done. I mean, I've been more of a reader

00:40:29.440 --> 00:40:31.240
[Guest]: rather than a writer, I would say, because, I mean,

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:35.240
[Guest]: I've been reading from the age of, what, five or whatever it is.

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:37.240
[Guest]: I'm very young age and, you know, you sort of go through

00:40:37.240 --> 00:40:40.040
[Guest]: all these authors and you sort of pick up something.

00:40:40.240 --> 00:40:42.040
[Guest]: And, like, when I was eight years old,

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:44.040
[Guest]: I think I wrote my first story in English,

00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:47.040
[Guest]: which was modelled on the Enid Blyton stories

00:40:47.240 --> 00:40:50.040
[Guest]: that I would read and it was picked up.

00:40:50.240 --> 00:40:53.040
[Guest]: I mean, Arvind Mehrotra and my cousins Alok and Amit,

00:40:53.240 --> 00:40:59.040
[Guest]: who died later, they were bringing out this magazine called Damn You.

00:40:59.240 --> 00:41:03.040
[Guest]: It was on the pattern of the New York little magazine called Fuck You.

00:41:03.240 --> 00:41:05.040
[Guest]: So, they named it Damn You.

00:41:05.040 --> 00:41:08.840
[Guest]: And they were all a bunch of teenagers themselves then.

00:41:09.040 --> 00:41:10.840
[Guest]: They were in University, Allahabad University,

00:41:11.040 --> 00:41:14.840
[Guest]: and they decided to sort of bring out this cyclostyle magazine.

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:17.840
[Guest]: So, they used it in that because they were running out of material.

00:41:18.040 --> 00:41:20.840
[Guest]: Who's going to give the material to these bunch of teenagers?

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:22.840
[Guest]: So, anyways, they were looking for material at that point.

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:24.840
[Guest]: Of course, it became very famous later

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:28.840
[Guest]: and now it's become part of this world sort of magazine thing, you know.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:31.840
[Guest]: But at that point, so my story,

00:41:31.840 --> 00:41:35.640
[Guest]: the early story in English was published in that, Damn You.

00:41:35.840 --> 00:41:38.640
[Guest]: So, my journey, in a sense, started with English.

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:41.640
[Guest]: But then, of course, as it went along,

00:41:41.840 --> 00:41:43.640
[Guest]: there was a huge gap in my writing.

00:41:43.840 --> 00:41:47.640
[Guest]: It started at that age, but then I wasn't writing very much for many years.

00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:50.640
[Guest]: And for all these reasons that I was groping for a language

00:41:50.840 --> 00:41:54.640
[Guest]: and just thinking and agonising about how I was not being able to write

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:56.640
[Guest]: and looking at the shape of my hands, for instance,

00:41:56.840 --> 00:41:58.640
[Guest]: or looking into my eyes in the mirror and thinking,

00:41:58.640 --> 00:42:02.440
[Guest]: oh, this looks like a writer, but I could not somehow,

00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:04.440
[Guest]: the writer and I could never meet.

00:42:04.640 --> 00:42:06.440
[Guest]: You know, it was like having a star-crossed lover.

00:42:06.640 --> 00:42:10.440
[Guest]: You know, you couldn't meet the writer and I were just, you know, away from each other.

00:42:10.640 --> 00:42:14.440
[Guest]: So, anyway, so and in that time I came to this,

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:16.440
[Guest]: there was this, there's this word Shabd,

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:20.440
[Guest]: which in Hindi means sound and it also means word.

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:24.440
[Guest]: So, this somehow created this bridge for me.

00:42:24.440 --> 00:42:29.240
[Guest]: It was, it came to my, I mean, I thought about it in that way that it's a bridge

00:42:29.440 --> 00:42:32.240
[Guest]: between the heard and the written, you know,

00:42:32.440 --> 00:42:35.240
[Guest]: because it's a sound also and Shabd is a word also.

00:42:35.440 --> 00:42:36.240
[Guest]: So, it's the written word.

00:42:36.440 --> 00:42:39.240
[Guest]: So, that somehow seemed very important to me at that point.

00:42:39.440 --> 00:42:45.240
[Guest]: It became like, it created a kind of bridge between the heard and the written literature.

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:50.240
[Guest]: I mean, there was this language of sound, I thought, which had no meaning behind it.

00:42:50.240 --> 00:42:56.040
[Guest]: For instance, the whistle of an engine or the sound, the chak-chak sound of the pump.

00:42:56.240 --> 00:42:59.040
[Guest]: I heard it in the village where I went once,

00:42:59.240 --> 00:43:02.040
[Guest]: or the sound of the bullock cart wheels grinding away on the road.

00:43:02.240 --> 00:43:06.040
[Guest]: These are all sounds and it's a kind of language of sound,

00:43:06.240 --> 00:43:10.040
[Guest]: but it leads to nothing else, but the language of words leads somewhere else.

00:43:10.240 --> 00:43:15.040
[Guest]: So, I mean, I don't know how, but it created this thing that there's something,

00:43:15.040 --> 00:43:19.840
[Guest]: the writing can be auditory as well as, you know, something that is written down.

00:43:20.040 --> 00:43:24.840
[Guest]: So, that was an important moment for me and gradually all these sort of,

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:29.840
[Guest]: all this thinking about language finally led to my first story.

00:43:30.040 --> 00:43:32.840
[Guest]: I think I was, must have been in my early 40s, something like that,

00:43:33.040 --> 00:43:35.840
[Guest]: when I wrote the first story, which was in Hindi.

00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:40.840
[Guest]: So, that's how my writing career started and I started quite late.

00:43:41.040 --> 00:43:42.840
[Guest]: I'm a slow writer also, so, you know.

00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:46.640
[Amit Varma]: So, I have like three or four questions arising from here and one of them is this,

00:43:46.840 --> 00:43:50.640
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, you've spoken about how a lot of your early reading was English

00:43:50.840 --> 00:43:54.640
[Amit Varma]: and it blighted and then by the age of 13 you discover Sartre and all the Russians

00:43:54.840 --> 00:43:57.640
[Amit Varma]: and Catherine Mansfield and so on and so forth.

00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:00.640
[Amit Varma]: Now, it strikes me that the different literatures,

00:44:00.840 --> 00:44:03.640
[Amit Varma]: different world literatures evolved in different ways

00:44:03.840 --> 00:44:07.640
[Amit Varma]: to be something completely different and to have different sets of values, right?

00:44:07.640 --> 00:44:12.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, David Rubin in The World of Premchand wrote about Premchand himself.

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:13.440
[Amit Varma]: He wrote, quote,

00:44:13.640 --> 00:44:17.440
[Amit Varma]: To Premchand belongs a distinction of creating the genre of the serious short story

00:44:17.640 --> 00:44:20.440
[Amit Varma]: and the serious novel as well in both Hindi and Urdu.

00:44:20.640 --> 00:44:24.440
[Amit Varma]: Virtually single-handed, he lifted fiction in these languages

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:27.440
[Amit Varma]: from a quagmire of aimless romantic chronicles

00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:31.440
[Amit Varma]: to a high level of realistic narrative comparable to European fiction of the time.

00:44:31.640 --> 00:44:36.440
[Amit Varma]: And in both languages, he has, in addition, remained an unsurpassed master

00:44:36.440 --> 00:44:41.240
[Amit Varma]: and elsewhere Sheldon Pollock kind of expressed a view that Premchand believed in social realism

00:44:41.440 --> 00:44:44.240
[Amit Varma]: and he kind of looked down on what he called the feminine quality,

00:44:44.440 --> 00:44:47.240
[Amit Varma]: the tenderness and emotion of contemporary Bengali literature.

00:44:47.440 --> 00:44:52.240
[Amit Varma]: And even at the level at which Premchand was writing that he's, you know,

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:56.240
[Amit Varma]: and I'm taking Rubin's words for it because I haven't read enough to come to my own judgment,

00:44:56.440 --> 00:45:00.240
[Amit Varma]: but even at the level at which he is writing where he has lifted it to more serious,

00:45:00.440 --> 00:45:03.240
[Amit Varma]: it is still very different from the European literature that you read.

00:45:03.440 --> 00:45:05.240
[Amit Varma]: Like, when I read your stories, for example,

00:45:05.240 --> 00:45:09.040
[Amit Varma]: you're using details and actions a lot.

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:12.040
[Amit Varma]: So it's all show-don't-tell in a sense.

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if I look at a story like your translation of Premchand's Idgah,

00:45:15.240 --> 00:45:20.040
[Amit Varma]: for example, the second last paragraph, when the grandmother realizes what the boy has done,

00:45:20.240 --> 00:45:24.040
[Amit Varma]: and it's all tell, Premchand is just describing her emotions and the way she feels.

00:45:24.240 --> 00:45:29.040
[Amit Varma]: Whereas a more modern writer, a more Western writer would show her doing something

00:45:29.240 --> 00:45:33.040
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, with more economy, just through actions and a detail,

00:45:33.040 --> 00:45:36.840
[Amit Varma]: bring out the same emotion in the reader. These are different values at play.

00:45:37.040 --> 00:45:40.840
[Amit Varma]: And again, one doesn't want to make a value judgment on these different values.

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:43.840
[Amit Varma]: These are literatures evolving in different kinds of direction.

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:49.840
[Amit Varma]: So then the thing is that as someone whose sensibilities are shaped by Western literature,

00:45:50.040 --> 00:45:55.840
[Amit Varma]: by, you know, the precision, the economy, the sort of all the values of Western literature,

00:45:56.040 --> 00:46:01.840
[Amit Varma]: would you have to slip into a different mode while reading Hindi and Urdu literature?

00:46:01.840 --> 00:46:07.640
[Guest]: As far as Premchand goes, I mean, the reason why he's doing this,

00:46:07.840 --> 00:46:09.640
[Amit Varma]: firstly, he's coming from a different time.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:10.640
[Amit Varma]: Of course, of course.

00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:13.640
[Guest]: And secondly, Premchand was in a hurry. I mean, he had a mission.

00:46:13.840 --> 00:46:18.640
[Guest]: He is trying to change things. I mean, he has this mission and so very often

00:46:18.840 --> 00:46:23.640
[Guest]: he's writing at great speed and he died early and he's written so much.

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:26.640
[Guest]: I don't think anyone in the world have been thinking about it.

00:46:26.840 --> 00:46:30.640
[Guest]: I don't think any writer in the world has probably written sort of so much.

00:46:30.640 --> 00:46:33.440
[Guest]: I mean, he's written short stories, he's written novels, he's written plays,

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:37.440
[Guest]: he's written letters, he's written essays, he's done translations.

00:46:37.640 --> 00:46:40.440
[Guest]: I mean, there's a whole huge range of what he's done, you know.

00:46:40.640 --> 00:46:45.440
[Guest]: So it's, I mean, I'm constantly foxed by this.

00:46:45.640 --> 00:46:48.440
[Guest]: I mean, how can a man who is in ill health, he has poor health throughout,

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:52.440
[Guest]: he dies at the age of 56, how has he managed to write so much?

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:57.440
[Guest]: And he's like fired with some kind of creative instinct

00:46:57.440 --> 00:47:02.240
[Guest]: and he has to change things. He just believes in change

00:47:02.440 --> 00:47:05.240
[Guest]: and he just writes and he's seen all these things around him.

00:47:05.440 --> 00:47:09.240
[Guest]: So he's writing about the reality which is still pretty relevant actually

00:47:09.440 --> 00:47:11.240
[Guest]: because nothing much has changed in the countryside.

00:47:11.440 --> 00:47:15.240
[Guest]: So he's writing and he's writing across a whole range of things.

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:19.240
[Guest]: You know, he's also not just a social realist, I think.

00:47:19.440 --> 00:47:22.240
[Guest]: There are many stories that are not socially realist stories.

00:47:22.440 --> 00:47:26.240
[Guest]: There's one tiny story, I don't know if Arvind and I have translated.

00:47:26.240 --> 00:47:29.040
[Guest]: In fact, we've been working on that project too, which is,

00:47:29.240 --> 00:47:31.040
[Guest]: we've done about 8 to 10 stories.

00:47:31.240 --> 00:47:34.040
[Guest]: We want to do some more and then maybe find a publisher for them.

00:47:34.240 --> 00:47:39.040
[Guest]: So in that story, it's called Darwaza in Hindi

00:47:39.240 --> 00:47:41.040
[Guest]: and it's about a door and a little child.

00:47:41.240 --> 00:47:45.040
[Guest]: This man is sitting with a little child and this child is just looking

00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:50.040
[Guest]: and he's chasing a bird, he's doing this, that and the door is open all the while

00:47:50.240 --> 00:47:53.040
[Guest]: and the child is not bothered about the door

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:57.840
[Guest]: and then suddenly somebody goes past on the road and he's selling sweetmeats

00:47:58.040 --> 00:47:59.840
[Guest]: or something he's selling and the child wants that.

00:48:00.040 --> 00:48:03.840
[Guest]: And this father who he's sitting with refuses to buy him that.

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:08.840
[Guest]: So he gets into this temper and he rushes to his mother

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:12.840
[Guest]: but the door which has been open all this while has suddenly banged shut

00:48:13.040 --> 00:48:15.840
[Guest]: and the child who so far had not been bothered with the door

00:48:16.040 --> 00:48:17.840
[Guest]: is now suddenly very anxious that the door is shut.

00:48:18.040 --> 00:48:20.840
[Guest]: So he starts crying and he runs towards the door.

00:48:20.840 --> 00:48:24.640
[Guest]: And it's a very tiny story, it's about, I think, two pages or something like that,

00:48:24.840 --> 00:48:25.640
[Guest]: a very, very short story.

00:48:25.840 --> 00:48:28.640
[Guest]: So it's not about social realism at all.

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:31.640
[Guest]: I mean, it's a very moving, very lovely story

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:34.640
[Guest]: and just a moment, he's caught this moment of this child.

00:48:34.840 --> 00:48:39.640
[Guest]: So he's written a whole range of things, many other kinds of things also

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:45.640
[Guest]: and even if he sometimes uses, he uses all sorts of devices to get his point across.

00:48:45.640 --> 00:48:51.440
[Guest]: So I don't know whether it would be right to call him primarily, he is primarily a social realist

00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:55.440
[Guest]: but there are other examples of stories that are not in that mode.

00:48:55.640 --> 00:48:59.440
[Amit Varma]: I didn't mean the example as a criticism of Premchand or anything of the sort

00:48:59.640 --> 00:49:03.440
[Amit Varma]: and we'll discuss it more but I was just kind of leading to the question of how

00:49:03.640 --> 00:49:06.440
[Amit Varma]: these different kinds of literatures, how does one look at them?

00:49:06.640 --> 00:49:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Does one look at them with different lenses?

00:49:08.640 --> 00:49:11.440
[Amit Varma]: My next question was also, for example, going to be about languages

00:49:11.440 --> 00:49:17.240
[Amit Varma]: which is a related question that languages also seem to have qualities of their own

00:49:17.440 --> 00:49:20.240
[Amit Varma]: which lend themselves to a certain kind of expression.

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:25.240
[Amit Varma]: So it's always seemed to me that say Urdu and Bengali are very expressionistic languages

00:49:25.440 --> 00:49:30.240
[Amit Varma]: whereas languages like say Japanese and Korean are much more minimalistic

00:49:30.440 --> 00:49:34.240
[Amit Varma]: and you see that in the kind of literature that emerges from these languages

00:49:34.440 --> 00:49:37.240
[Amit Varma]: and English is in a kind of a middle ground.

00:49:37.240 --> 00:49:42.040
[Amit Varma]: So if you just do a direct translation say like a lot of translations of Tagore for example

00:49:42.240 --> 00:49:46.040
[Amit Varma]: and I'm half Bengali so I know a bit of Bengali fail completely to me

00:49:46.240 --> 00:49:48.040
[Amit Varma]: because they are gorgeous and beautiful in Bengali

00:49:48.240 --> 00:49:52.040
[Amit Varma]: but if you just try a literal translation it simply doesn't work

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:55.040
[Amit Varma]: because it just seems too overblown and purple and all of that.

00:49:55.240 --> 00:49:59.040
[Amit Varma]: So as someone who looks at literature and you know you've presumably

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:02.040
[Amit Varma]: then imbibed all the values of the Western literature that you're reading.

00:50:02.240 --> 00:50:04.040
[Amit Varma]: How does one adjust one's lens?

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:09.840
[Amit Varma]: Like of course one adjusts it for context if someone like Premchand is writing in the early 20th century

00:50:10.040 --> 00:50:14.840
[Amit Varma]: there's only so much you can expect, only so many influences that he was open to

00:50:15.040 --> 00:50:17.840
[Amit Varma]: but apart from that how does one sort of…

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:22.840
[Guest]: I think possibly we generalize too much about literatures.

00:50:23.040 --> 00:50:25.840
[Guest]: I mean Western literature is also hugely sort of different

00:50:26.040 --> 00:50:27.840
[Guest]: and Indian literature too is hugely different.

00:50:28.040 --> 00:50:32.840
[Guest]: So to say that these are Western values and we're trying to apply them to Indian reality

00:50:32.840 --> 00:50:37.640
[Guest]: that also does not work I think because Indian reality comes from a particular milieu.

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:41.640
[Guest]: I mean you are sort of… so you have to look at it from sort of…

00:50:41.840 --> 00:50:43.640
[Guest]: you base yourself in that milieu and then look at it.

00:50:43.840 --> 00:50:48.640
[Guest]: So for instance a writer like Vinod Kumar Shukla, I mean where is he coming from?

00:50:48.840 --> 00:50:53.640
[Guest]: I mean he's writing about these small towns, very ordinary day

00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:57.640
[Guest]: some man is walking down the street and some other man is observing him

00:50:57.840 --> 00:51:01.640
[Guest]: and he thinks oh this man went this way and he again he's going this way

00:51:01.640 --> 00:51:03.440
[Guest]: without having come back even once you know.

00:51:03.640 --> 00:51:08.440
[Guest]: So there's this absurd kind of quality to it and it gives a sort of space

00:51:08.640 --> 00:51:13.440
[Guest]: to very lower middle class lives that are normally one would think are very cramped

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:16.440
[Guest]: and living in very sort of poor circumstances whatever

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:21.440
[Guest]: but I mean he adds this kind of very sort of almost playful element to the whole thing.

00:51:21.640 --> 00:51:23.440
[Guest]: So I mean he is one writer.

00:51:23.640 --> 00:51:25.440
[Guest]: I mean there are so many writers who are writing different things

00:51:25.640 --> 00:51:29.440
[Guest]: even in Hindi or in Bangla there'd be possibly many more

00:51:29.440 --> 00:51:32.240
[Guest]: and Bangla is sort of very well-developed literature.

00:51:32.440 --> 00:51:36.240
[Guest]: Malayalam as we have seen has so many different registers.

00:51:36.440 --> 00:51:41.240
[Guest]: So it's very hard to say you know that we can train a particular kind of lens

00:51:41.440 --> 00:51:43.240
[Guest]: you know to look at these things.

00:51:43.440 --> 00:51:47.240
[Guest]: You just have to adapt to what is being written and where it's set

00:51:47.440 --> 00:51:51.240
[Guest]: and you know you judge it on its own ground you know it happens like that I think

00:51:51.440 --> 00:51:56.240
[Guest]: and also this whole thing of languages being expressionist or minimalistic.

00:51:56.240 --> 00:52:01.040
[Guest]: Okay Japanese one can say yes it is minimalistic but for instance Urdu.

00:52:01.240 --> 00:52:06.040
[Guest]: I think Urdu is so difficult to translate because I think it's one of the languages

00:52:06.240 --> 00:52:08.040
[Guest]: in which the form is the content.

00:52:08.240 --> 00:52:13.040
[Guest]: I mean the way you say a thing is what it is you know it's just there's nothing else.

00:52:13.240 --> 00:52:16.040
[Guest]: So that form is very difficult to express in another language.

00:52:16.240 --> 00:52:19.040
[Guest]: It's a very light, it's a very weightless language

00:52:19.240 --> 00:52:24.040
[Guest]: and it has these very fine sentiments a lot of subtlety.

00:52:24.040 --> 00:52:27.840
[Guest]: For instance I was telling someone just the other day that there's this person I know

00:52:28.040 --> 00:52:31.840
[Guest]: the son of my famous I mean the writer I'm very fond of Nair Masood

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:33.840
[Unknown]: whose book you have right here.

00:52:34.040 --> 00:52:35.840
[Guest]: So he's my absolute favorite in Urdu.

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:37.840
[Guest]: So his son is called Timsal.

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:40.840
[Guest]: So I wondered what Timsal meant.

00:52:41.040 --> 00:52:44.840
[Guest]: Then someone told me that it means a crack in a mirror.

00:52:45.040 --> 00:52:45.840
[Unknown]: Wow.

00:52:46.040 --> 00:52:47.840
[Guest]: So I wondered where that came from.

00:52:48.040 --> 00:52:51.840
[Guest]: So I went into it a little bit and found out that this boy is so beautiful

00:52:51.840 --> 00:52:55.640
[Guest]: that when he looks at himself in the mirror, the mirror cracks.

00:52:55.840 --> 00:52:59.640
[Guest]: So the subtlety of that thought you know a mirror can actually crack

00:52:59.840 --> 00:53:03.640
[Guest]: when someone is looking into it because it can't take the beauty.

00:53:03.840 --> 00:53:06.640
[Guest]: So that's a thought that comes in a language like Urdu.

00:53:06.840 --> 00:53:09.640
[Guest]: I don't know which other French possibly I mean some language

00:53:09.840 --> 00:53:14.640
[Guest]: would have to have a very fine kind of it comes after years and years of

00:53:14.840 --> 00:53:19.640
[Guest]: you know thinking and feeling and delicate sensibility.

00:53:19.640 --> 00:53:23.440
[Guest]: So there are I mean examples in all the languages that prove

00:53:23.640 --> 00:53:25.440
[Guest]: the other example to be untrue.

00:53:25.640 --> 00:53:30.440
[Guest]: So one can't really generalize my whole take on this language thing.

00:53:30.640 --> 00:53:33.440
[Amit Varma]: I'm also struck by another thing you said about Premchand is that

00:53:33.640 --> 00:53:37.440
[Amit Varma]: he was a man in a hurry and obviously he wrote more than a dozen novels

00:53:37.640 --> 00:53:41.440
[Amit Varma]: 300 stories, essays, editorials, letters, plays, biographies, blah blah blah

00:53:41.640 --> 00:53:45.440
[Amit Varma]: all of that and actually one writer I can think of who's more prolific

00:53:45.640 --> 00:53:48.440
[Amit Varma]: but obviously a complete outlier is a French writer Georges Simenon

00:53:48.440 --> 00:53:50.240
[Guest]: who wrote some 400 novels.

00:53:50.440 --> 00:53:52.240
[Guest]: Yeah but he wrote only novels.

00:53:52.440 --> 00:53:54.240
[Amit Varma]: He wrote only novels yeah but 400 of them.

00:53:54.440 --> 00:53:58.240
[Guest]: 400 novels and they are completely like quite a few of them are mystery stories.

00:53:58.440 --> 00:54:00.240
[Guest]: I mean at least the ones that I've read.

00:54:00.440 --> 00:54:02.240
[Amit Varma]: A bunch of them are the May Gray books.

00:54:02.440 --> 00:54:03.240
[Guest]: Yeah the May Gray books.

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:05.240
[Guest]: But his serious stuff is really good.

00:54:05.440 --> 00:54:09.240
[Guest]: I haven't actually read very much of Simenon except these

00:54:09.440 --> 00:54:12.240
[Guest]: and I think one more which is also very different

00:54:12.440 --> 00:54:15.240
[Guest]: but I wouldn't put them in the same category.

00:54:15.440 --> 00:54:16.240
[Unknown]: Sure, sure, sure.

00:54:16.240 --> 00:54:20.040
[Guest]: Because I mean and I think of say for instance Charles Dickens

00:54:20.240 --> 00:54:24.040
[Guest]: or the major writers of the West Dickens or Maupassant

00:54:24.240 --> 00:54:27.040
[Guest]: or you know people I mean they've all written very fine stuff

00:54:27.240 --> 00:54:29.040
[Guest]: but nobody has actually written such a lot.

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:30.040
[Unknown]: So much, so much.

00:54:30.240 --> 00:54:34.040
[Guest]: And so Premchand is not just a writer he's an influencer of that age

00:54:34.240 --> 00:54:38.040
[Guest]: you know he just he's forming that age you know he's like shaping the times.

00:54:38.240 --> 00:54:39.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:54:39.240 --> 00:54:41.040
[Amit Varma]: The times are shaping him and he's shaping the times.

00:54:41.240 --> 00:54:45.040
[Amit Varma]: And one of the reasons that you mentioned in that lovely essay

00:54:45.040 --> 00:54:47.840
[Amit Varma]: at the start of that book The History of Selected Stories which you edited

00:54:48.040 --> 00:54:51.840
[Amit Varma]: is you speak about how he saw art as always having a purpose

00:54:52.040 --> 00:54:52.840
[Amit Varma]: his writing is having a purpose.

00:54:53.040 --> 00:54:56.840
[Amit Varma]: And like in 1936 he gave the speech at the Progressive Writers Conference

00:54:57.040 --> 00:54:59.840
[Amit Varma]: where he was a chairman where which is called the aim of literature

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:03.840
[Unknown]: where he spoke about you know how these social aims

00:55:04.040 --> 00:55:08.840
[Amit Varma]: are so incredibly important in you know showing the lives of the underprivileged

00:55:09.040 --> 00:55:12.840
[Amit Varma]: and exposing oppression and all of those things.

00:55:12.840 --> 00:55:17.640
[Amit Varma]: What do you sort of feel about that because Milan Kundera of course

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:21.640
[Amit Varma]: among so many others has written about how that the moment literature

00:55:21.840 --> 00:55:25.640
[Amit Varma]: goes towards polemic or goes towards having a particular political purpose

00:55:25.840 --> 00:55:27.640
[Amit Varma]: it ceases to be literature it ceases to be art.

00:55:27.840 --> 00:55:32.640
[Amit Varma]: And in your own writing the very little of it that I've read in English

00:55:32.840 --> 00:55:35.640
[Amit Varma]: though I plan to kind of read all of it soon

00:55:35.840 --> 00:55:38.640
[Amit Varma]: in your own writing you show no signs of that.

00:55:38.840 --> 00:55:41.640
[Amit Varma]: Your own writing show an interior life of the characters that they are

00:55:41.640 --> 00:55:46.440
[Amit Varma]: and they do to me what you know I think great art does

00:55:46.640 --> 00:55:48.440
[Amit Varma]: is that it awakens something in me.

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:52.440
[Amit Varma]: It captures a little bit of the human condition to use that slightly pompous cliche.

00:55:52.640 --> 00:55:57.440
[Amit Varma]: So what is your conception therefore of literature like people will often ask

00:55:57.640 --> 00:56:01.440
[Amit Varma]: that like on the one hand I you know tell my writing students for example

00:56:01.640 --> 00:56:04.440
[Amit Varma]: that be an indiscriminate reader if you enjoy reading something read it.

00:56:04.640 --> 00:56:07.440
[Amit Varma]: Don't pass value judgment that this is a pulp book

00:56:07.640 --> 00:56:10.440
[Amit Varma]: and this is serious literature and all of that.

00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:14.240
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time you know there is literature and there is non-literature.

00:56:14.440 --> 00:56:18.240
[Amit Varma]: It's very nebulous and I find it hard to kind of define that.

00:56:18.440 --> 00:56:22.240
[Amit Varma]: So what would your sense of that be like where does your sense grow

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:25.240
[Amit Varma]: like as a kid of course you're reading in this indiscriminately

00:56:25.440 --> 00:56:28.240
[Amit Varma]: as all of us who grew up in India before a certain year did

00:56:28.440 --> 00:56:31.240
[Amit Varma]: because books were so hard to get hold of we read everything we get.

00:56:31.440 --> 00:56:35.240
[Amit Varma]: But at what stage does you begin to realize that this is something

00:56:35.440 --> 00:56:39.240
[Amit Varma]: called literature and I want to do it and this is how it is different

00:56:39.240 --> 00:56:46.040
[Amit Varma]: and do you feel that Premchand's sort of having this sort of social objective

00:56:46.240 --> 00:56:49.040
[Amit Varma]: as part of his work do you think it affects that in some way?

00:56:49.240 --> 00:56:53.040
[Guest]: I think you know Amit I think it's the literature is also very influenced

00:56:53.240 --> 00:56:55.040
[Guest]: by the age in which you are writing.

00:56:55.240 --> 00:56:59.040
[Guest]: I mean he's writing at a time when firstly there is no literature in Hindi

00:56:59.240 --> 00:57:03.040
[Guest]: which can be called serious literature and then he's writing at a time

00:57:03.240 --> 00:57:08.040
[Guest]: of great social unrest he's sort of trying to you know sort of oppose

00:57:08.040 --> 00:57:11.840
[Guest]: the British and he's trying to you know he has his literature has a purpose

00:57:12.040 --> 00:57:15.840
[Guest]: he wants to do something with that so he and he wants to write a lot

00:57:16.040 --> 00:57:20.840
[Guest]: he wants to you know hurry through it when you forward towards his mission.

00:57:21.040 --> 00:57:23.840
[Guest]: So I think that changes the tone of the whole thing.

00:57:24.040 --> 00:57:27.840
[Guest]: So it's a different sort of literature I wouldn't say that this is not literature

00:57:28.040 --> 00:57:30.840
[Guest]: and that is literature because Milan Kundera or somebody in the West

00:57:31.040 --> 00:57:35.840
[Guest]: I mean they have grown out of the circumstances that they have experienced.

00:57:35.840 --> 00:57:40.640
[Guest]: So it all depends on that and also depends on what you're trying to do with it.

00:57:40.840 --> 00:57:44.640
[Guest]: So he has a very definite purpose and I think it's very fine literature.

00:57:44.840 --> 00:57:47.640
[Guest]: I mean he's uneven Premchand is very uneven some of his things

00:57:47.840 --> 00:57:51.640
[Guest]: are much finer than others but on the whole I would say that he writes

00:57:51.840 --> 00:57:55.640
[Guest]: something that for the common man in India I mean you go anywhere

00:57:55.840 --> 00:57:58.640
[Guest]: everybody has read something of Premchand.

00:57:58.840 --> 00:58:03.640
[Guest]: So for him to touch some kind of deep core in such a vast you know part

00:58:03.640 --> 00:58:08.440
[Guest]: of Indian society at any rate so there has to be something in it.

00:58:08.640 --> 00:58:13.440
[Guest]: It can't just be this is not literature there's something else that is finer.

00:58:13.640 --> 00:58:17.440
[Guest]: This I mean this is a much later thing when you talk of Kundera

00:58:17.640 --> 00:58:20.440
[Guest]: or talk of the writers of the West this is a later thing.

00:58:20.640 --> 00:58:24.440
[Guest]: This whole development in this thing of writing how does it take place?

00:58:24.640 --> 00:58:29.440
[Guest]: I mean the writing itself becomes much more dense you're spending more time

00:58:29.640 --> 00:58:32.440
[Guest]: over it you're sort of thinking about things in a different way.

00:58:32.440 --> 00:58:36.240
[Guest]: So it comes from there I think it's hard to compare the two.

00:58:36.440 --> 00:58:39.240
[Guest]: I mean there's you know the situation is completely different.

00:58:39.440 --> 00:58:43.240
[Amit Varma]: Right so let's get back to your growth in this period of time where

00:58:43.440 --> 00:58:47.240
[Amit Varma]: you grew up in this atmosphere you're reading a lot you're observing a lot

00:58:47.440 --> 00:58:51.240
[Amit Varma]: though you said it's with you know just because it's so dull but I don't

00:58:51.440 --> 00:58:54.240
[Amit Varma]: completely buy that but you're observing a lot you're growing a lot you want to

00:58:54.440 --> 00:58:57.240
[Amit Varma]: write you've written that early story I think Lucky Horace or something.

00:58:57.440 --> 00:59:01.240
[Guest]: It's just a copy of one of the enlightened stories I'd been reading at the time.

00:59:01.240 --> 00:59:03.040
[Amit Varma]: The title sounds very enlightening.

00:59:03.240 --> 00:59:07.040
[Guest]: Yes I mean it's not I don't call it my first story actually it was a discovery

00:59:07.240 --> 00:59:11.040
[Guest]: that I could write rather than a story that I wrote I would put it like that.

00:59:11.240 --> 00:59:17.040
[Guest]: I mean of course this was something unstated inside me that I would write

00:59:17.240 --> 00:59:21.040
[Guest]: that I would be a writer I mean I never said it to myself but I somehow that

00:59:21.240 --> 00:59:24.040
[Guest]: knowledge was there because it was just something that one did it was just

00:59:24.240 --> 00:59:28.040
[Guest]: something that one fell into I would say because everyone around me was writing

00:59:28.040 --> 00:59:31.840
[Guest]: my entire family my mother wrote my grandmother wrote my aunt wrote on both

00:59:32.040 --> 00:59:35.840
[Guest]: sides my uncle wrote his wife wrote I mean everybody was writing so it was it

00:59:36.040 --> 00:59:40.840
[Guest]: felt like this is something that one does you know this is what one will do

00:59:41.040 --> 00:59:46.840
[Guest]: and then I when I started reading it also sort of sets off something we knew

00:59:47.040 --> 00:59:50.840
[Guest]: so at a point when I was reading and I was trying to decide which language to

00:59:51.040 --> 00:59:55.840
[Guest]: write in and it came to me very late that I could actually write in both and

00:59:55.840 --> 01:00:00.640
[Guest]: also the reading set off this thing I could be reading about something set in

01:00:00.840 --> 01:00:04.640
[Guest]: Paris or in New York or wherever but somehow the stories the universal story

01:00:04.840 --> 01:00:08.640
[Guest]: was the same so I just felt that all these stories about me you know they are

01:00:08.840 --> 01:00:13.640
[Guest]: like about me so it was a very peculiar realization at that point you know this

01:00:13.840 --> 01:00:18.640
[Guest]: was my journey of reading in my school days or college early college days so I

01:00:18.840 --> 01:00:21.640
[Guest]: would just spend days reading there was nothing else to do we did not have

01:00:21.640 --> 01:00:25.440
[Guest]: television and thank goodness we didn't you know we didn't have TV or any other

01:00:25.640 --> 01:00:32.440
[Guest]: screen to look at so you either read the world or you world outside or you read

01:00:32.640 --> 01:00:36.440
[Guest]: your book you know so it was basically a choice between the two and I did both I

01:00:36.640 --> 01:00:41.440
[Guest]: mean I looked around me the house and the plants and the insects and whatever

01:00:41.640 --> 01:00:46.440
[Guest]: so I mean this thing of nature became very strong in me and plus reading all

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:49.440
[Guest]: these other books that were set in different places but I felt that they

01:00:49.440 --> 01:00:53.240
[Guest]: resonated with me and they were all about me and at some point they generated the

01:00:53.440 --> 01:00:57.240
[Guest]: thought that perhaps I too can create a world of my own like these people have

01:00:57.440 --> 01:01:02.240
[Guest]: written I can also write no so it I thought about these things when I was

01:01:02.440 --> 01:01:06.240
[Amit Varma]: not writing yeah I mean in a sense I think about current times and I wonder

01:01:06.440 --> 01:01:10.240
[Amit Varma]: how the sensory overload of the modern times affects us as people like if I was

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:14.240
[Amit Varma]: growing up today I don't know if I'd become the kind of reader I did become I

01:01:14.440 --> 01:01:18.240
[Amit Varma]: read a lot as a kid that's a habit I lost as an adult but you know today you

01:01:18.240 --> 01:01:21.040
[Amit Varma]: know today you're surrounded with so many things there's always YouTube

01:01:21.240 --> 01:01:25.040
[Amit Varma]: there's Instagram and it's very fleeting like an observation that I think

01:01:25.240 --> 01:01:29.040
[Amit Varma]: Jonathan Haidt once made is that you would imagine that today because of the

01:01:29.240 --> 01:01:33.040
[Amit Varma]: internet you have access to all the knowledge all the art of ages past which

01:01:33.240 --> 01:01:38.040
[Amit Varma]: you know people like us didn't but the counter to that is that what most people

01:01:38.240 --> 01:01:42.040
[Amit Varma]: are consuming most of this time is something produced in the last three days

01:01:42.240 --> 01:01:47.040
[Amit Varma]: and that's it whereas I think you know that you and I growing up you know a

01:01:47.040 --> 01:01:50.840
[Amit Varma]: decade and a half apart but whatever couple of decades apart would still have

01:01:51.040 --> 01:01:53.840
[Amit Varma]: lived in a time where you read whatever you could get where you didn't have

01:01:54.040 --> 01:01:58.840
[Amit Varma]: smartphones to look at all day and 300 television channels and so on no while

01:01:59.040 --> 01:02:01.840
[Amit Varma]: we were having lunch earlier you know I told you an anecdote and then you told

01:02:02.040 --> 01:02:05.840
[Amit Varma]: me about the short story that you read that you remembered vividly and I think

01:02:06.040 --> 01:02:08.840
[Amit Varma]: it's called jealousy I'm not very sure but I think it's called jealousy yeah

01:02:09.040 --> 01:02:12.840
[Amit Varma]: possibly great I'll look it up and link it in the show notes if it's available

01:02:12.840 --> 01:02:16.840
[Guest]: anywhere yeah but please check the title because I don't remember it so well I

01:02:17.040 --> 01:02:20.640
[Guest]: think it's called jealousy if I seem to remember I do that so whatever we whatever

01:02:20.840 --> 01:02:23.640
[Guest]: I'll get back home and tell you what it is because I probably have the book

01:02:23.840 --> 01:02:28.640
[Amit Varma]: somewhere on my Kindle I think okay so my question here is is that even I find

01:02:28.840 --> 01:02:33.640
[Amit Varma]: sometimes that things I remember really vividly in terms of books that I have

01:02:33.840 --> 01:02:37.640
[Amit Varma]: read or stories that I have read or you know movies that I have seen are things

01:02:37.840 --> 01:02:41.640
[Amit Varma]: that I saw at a particular phase in life where I won't remember something I saw

01:02:41.640 --> 01:02:46.440
[Amit Varma]: five years ago so vividly but something that I saw when I was 15 or 20 I'll still

01:02:46.640 --> 01:02:50.440
[Amit Varma]: remember even if it didn't move me so hard then it's something that I'll still

01:02:50.640 --> 01:02:54.440
[Amit Varma]: kind of remember like recently I was like chatting with a friend and I suddenly

01:02:54.640 --> 01:02:58.440
[Amit Varma]: remembered this and I read all the Russians when I was a kid and I remember

01:02:58.640 --> 01:03:02.440
[Amit Varma]: this very powerful story which didn't strike me so hard at the time but I

01:03:02.640 --> 01:03:06.440
[Amit Varma]: suddenly remembered it and I was like wow by Leonard Andreev called the abyss

01:03:06.640 --> 01:03:10.440
[Amit Varma]: which if I remember correctly and now I'm remembering from memory is about a

01:03:10.440 --> 01:03:15.240
[Amit Varma]: guy who goes on this hike with a bunch of friends they find a girl and they rape

01:03:15.440 --> 01:03:19.240
[Amit Varma]: her and they kill her but he doesn't participate and then later on he goes

01:03:19.440 --> 01:03:23.240
[Amit Varma]: back alone and he has sex with the dead body and that's a whole story and it's a

01:03:23.440 --> 01:03:28.240
[Unknown]: very interior kind of story you know these bare details don't suffice and it's

01:03:28.440 --> 01:03:33.240
[Amit Varma]: it's such a sort of powerful memory even though at the time I kind of didn't

01:03:33.440 --> 01:03:38.240
[Amit Varma]: notice it who were the writers who sort of that I mean you're recounting this

01:03:38.240 --> 01:03:42.040
[Guest]: story actually put me in mind of another one which is fairly not very similar but

01:03:42.240 --> 01:03:48.040
[Guest]: fairly similar I mean like there's this it's by Raymond Carver and it's called

01:03:48.240 --> 01:03:52.040
[Guest]: I think so much water so close to home have you read that story?

01:03:52.240 --> 01:03:55.040
[Amit Varma]: I definitely have but I don't remember the specific story but I'm a big Carver

01:03:55.240 --> 01:03:58.040
[Guest]: fan I think it's one of the stories Robert Altman also made in his film

01:03:58.240 --> 01:04:02.040
[Guest]: Shortcuts. Yes he did yeah Shortcuts so this one this group of friends I think

01:04:02.240 --> 01:04:06.040
[Guest]: three or four of them have gone out for a picnic or they've gone out for an outing

01:04:06.040 --> 01:04:11.840
[Guest]: fishing I think and when they are sitting there they see that there's a dead body

01:04:12.040 --> 01:04:16.840
[Guest]: which is sort of stuck on a plant on a tree somewhere there and they look at it

01:04:17.040 --> 01:04:20.840
[Guest]: and they wonder who it could be it's a woman you know clothing torn and all that

01:04:21.040 --> 01:04:24.840
[Guest]: she's just there and they wonder who it could be but they don't give much

01:04:25.040 --> 01:04:29.840
[Guest]: attention to it and they carry on with their fishing and their little picnic and

01:04:30.040 --> 01:04:33.840
[Guest]: all that and they spend the time that they were there for and they go home and

01:04:33.840 --> 01:04:37.640
[Guest]: then this guy tells his wife that there was this woman that they found on the

01:04:37.840 --> 01:04:42.640
[Guest]: tree over there so this wife she's completely stunned by what these people

01:04:42.840 --> 01:04:46.640
[Guest]: how they could still you know gone have gone on fishing and with this woman

01:04:46.840 --> 01:04:49.640
[Guest]: there and she begins to doubt the kind of person and she begins to think that

01:04:49.840 --> 01:04:53.640
[Guest]: what if they have killed this girl or if he has killed the girl you know so all

01:04:53.840 --> 01:04:58.640
[Guest]: sorts of doubts get created in her mind and I think this story goes on like that

01:04:58.840 --> 01:05:01.640
[Guest]: and then there's too much that that thing comes between them and it sort of

01:05:01.640 --> 01:05:06.440
[Guest]: splits them up I think it ends like that that they split up or I mean I don't

01:05:06.640 --> 01:05:09.440
[Guest]: remember the ending I seem to forget endings it's something like that I think

01:05:09.640 --> 01:05:12.440
[Guest]: they probably split up or there's certainly a great coldness between them

01:05:12.640 --> 01:05:17.440
[Guest]: after that incident but of course I mean it's got a similar theme of you know

01:05:17.640 --> 01:05:24.440
[Guest]: Kavya is great at that you know he's just so I mean he writes in so few words

01:05:24.640 --> 01:05:28.440
[Unknown]: and he just puts it across like you know it just gets straight to you and there's

01:05:28.440 --> 01:05:35.240
[Guest]: a wonderful poem by him which is called I think limits limits have you read I

01:05:35.440 --> 01:05:40.240
[Guest]: haven't read limits so limits is this poem his poems are also like his short

01:05:40.440 --> 01:05:43.240
[Guest]: stories because his short stories are like poems they are short and the poems

01:05:43.440 --> 01:05:48.240
[Guest]: are long this one certainly is longish and it's like a short story so in this

01:05:48.440 --> 01:05:52.240
[Guest]: these people have gone out duck shooting and these two friends have gone duck

01:05:52.440 --> 01:05:55.240
[Guest]: shooting in their shooting and shooting and they're killing and all the ducks

01:05:55.240 --> 01:06:00.040
[Guest]: falling around them and they are they still have so much shooting left in them

01:06:00.240 --> 01:06:04.040
[Guest]: but they get you know they want to meal they are hungry so they go to this farm

01:06:04.240 --> 01:06:10.040
[Guest]: which is there and the farmer has this barrel in which he has it's a goose

01:06:10.240 --> 01:06:15.040
[Guest]: actually they are not ducks but the geese so this farmer has got a goose in that

01:06:15.240 --> 01:06:19.040
[Guest]: thing and the goose can't get out and it's just being given food and it's just

01:06:19.240 --> 01:06:24.040
[Guest]: stuck there it just stays there always and it's a great decoy for the other

01:06:24.040 --> 01:06:28.840
[Guest]: geese to come and they're just thinking then these geese come and they get a good

01:06:29.040 --> 01:06:33.840
[Guest]: shot and all that so but this sight of that goose gets him thinking this person

01:06:34.040 --> 01:06:38.840
[Guest]: who's writing the story the narrator and he thinks of limits that if a person can

01:06:39.040 --> 01:06:42.840
[Guest]: be limited in that world and it can live it can survive you know then then you

01:06:43.040 --> 01:06:46.840
[Guest]: can survive anything you can just you know so it's so beautifully done that

01:06:47.040 --> 01:06:50.840
[Guest]: poem you know that it's just about the limits of human endurance with limits of

01:06:50.840 --> 01:06:54.640
[Guest]: endurance that can also become human endurance that duck goose becomes a

01:06:54.840 --> 01:06:59.640
[Guest]: metaphor for endurance so I found it wonderful that poem it's I mean just

01:06:59.840 --> 01:07:03.640
[Guest]: stayed with me because I just affected me very deeply when I read it.

01:07:03.840 --> 01:07:07.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah Kavar is great I mean Cathedral is a particular favorite and the interesting

01:07:07.840 --> 01:07:11.640
[Amit Varma]: thing about Kavar is that some of the credit for his short stories during that

01:07:11.840 --> 01:07:14.640
[Unknown]: golden period you know what we talk about when we talk about love and yeah

01:07:14.840 --> 01:07:18.640
[Unknown]: Cathedral and that whole period is given to his editor at Esquire Gordon Lish

01:07:18.640 --> 01:07:22.440
[Unknown]: if I remember correctly yeah who was apparently a great editor and would

01:07:22.640 --> 01:07:26.440
[Unknown]: really cut cut them down and make them sparse yeah and Kavar after he split

01:07:26.640 --> 01:07:31.440
[Guest]: from Lish couldn't quite repeat that same kind of magic which is also.

01:07:31.640 --> 01:07:35.440
[Guest]: Yeah but apparently I mean the stories are there because of his editor and

01:07:35.640 --> 01:07:39.440
[Guest]: there's stories originally written by Kavar just not like that at all so in a

01:07:39.640 --> 01:07:43.440
[Guest]: sense half the credit goes to the editor also yeah for this whole thing that

01:07:43.640 --> 01:07:47.440
[Guest]: Kavar is known for is you know brevity and all that so it actually that is the

01:07:47.440 --> 01:07:51.240
[Guest]: credit to the editor doing that because his own stories apparently were not as

01:07:51.440 --> 01:07:54.240
[Amit Varma]: short in sort of brevity as they are now.

01:07:54.440 --> 01:07:57.240
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense that also speaks to the art versus artist debate where in this

01:07:57.440 --> 01:08:01.240
[Guest]: case the art is just standing on its own anyway you know what is Kavar but a name

01:08:01.440 --> 01:08:04.240
[Guest]: you know who cares if Shakespeare wrote Shakespeare's plays.

01:08:04.440 --> 01:08:06.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah exactly yeah who cares yeah.

01:08:06.440 --> 01:08:13.240
[Amit Varma]: So the question I was coming at was who are the writers who affected you greatly

01:08:13.440 --> 01:08:16.240
[Amit Varma]: when you were a child I won't say influence because one really never knows

01:08:16.240 --> 01:08:20.040
[Unknown]: somebody's influence for a long time it's all subterranean but who were the

01:08:20.240 --> 01:08:24.040
[Amit Varma]: writers you really liked then or was there ever a period of time where you

01:08:24.240 --> 01:08:28.040
[Amit Varma]: read someone and you said I want to write like this person this is so amazing.

01:08:28.240 --> 01:08:31.040
[Guest]: Childhood I mean there were of course many of these books at home that I read

01:08:31.240 --> 01:08:35.040
[Guest]: without understanding them you know they were all these like you said

01:08:35.240 --> 01:08:39.040
[Guest]: Jampal Sathra and people like that I mean who one could not make sense of at

01:08:39.240 --> 01:08:42.040
[Guest]: that time but one felt good that one had read them.

01:08:42.040 --> 01:08:46.840
[Guest]: And then of course I discovered the Russians Chekhov, Chekhov is a particular

01:08:47.040 --> 01:08:50.840
[Guest]: favorite and then as I grew older that Kafka became a great favorite of mine.

01:08:51.040 --> 01:08:55.840
[Guest]: I loved Kafka completely you know just I used to search out books I used to there

01:08:56.040 --> 01:09:00.840
[Guest]: was in the library at college there was this picture book of Kafka's Prague I

01:09:01.040 --> 01:09:04.840
[Guest]: used to sit somewhere in the behind the shelves and just to pour over it and you

01:09:05.040 --> 01:09:09.840
[Guest]: know just hours and hours of Kafka so he was one of my favorite writers at that

01:09:09.840 --> 01:09:14.640
[Guest]: point and I think he I may have tried to copy him I mean I certainly put on that

01:09:14.840 --> 01:09:18.640
[Guest]: stance which I wrote about in my essay that this despairing stance you know

01:09:18.840 --> 01:09:23.640
[Guest]: Kafka and it was completely absurd in my situation but I mean one tries to emulate

01:09:23.840 --> 01:09:28.640
[Guest]: some people that one begins to admire so Kafka was one of those writers and then

01:09:28.840 --> 01:09:32.640
[Guest]: of course there were many people I read it's very hard to I became very fond of

01:09:32.840 --> 01:09:36.640
[Guest]: WG Sebald at one place Sebald, Sebald I don't know how you pronounce it.

01:09:36.840 --> 01:09:38.640
[Amit Varma]: Sebald, Sebald whatever.

01:09:38.640 --> 01:09:42.440
[Guest]: Anyway I became very fond of him and this was also because I came across his

01:09:42.640 --> 01:09:48.440
[Guest]: books when I was in Norwich I went there on residency at the University of East

01:09:48.640 --> 01:09:52.440
[Guest]: Anglia and my room had this whole collection of Sebald's displayed there

01:09:52.640 --> 01:09:56.440
[Guest]: because he had actually taught in that at that University and he had died just the

01:09:56.640 --> 01:10:02.440
[Guest]: year before so I came upon him and I just loved the way he wrote I mean it was

01:10:02.640 --> 01:10:04.440
[Guest]: very kind of textured writing.

01:10:04.640 --> 01:10:06.440
[Guest]: And using photographs and all that.

01:10:06.440 --> 01:10:12.240
[Guest]: Using photographs as well, yes very and he sort of the way he could encapsulate a

01:10:12.440 --> 01:10:17.240
[Guest]: whole civilization in a walk I mean like he's walking I think the book is Rings of

01:10:17.440 --> 01:10:22.240
[Guest]: Saturn I think it is and in which he's taking a walk along the East Anglia coast

01:10:22.440 --> 01:10:26.240
[Guest]: and how he's the thoughts in his head and how entire civilizations are covered

01:10:26.440 --> 01:10:35.240
[Guest]: during that walk so it's that this whole the largeness of his concepts and the

01:10:35.240 --> 01:10:39.040
[Guest]: same thing I came upon in a very different way in Proust also like he's

01:10:39.240 --> 01:10:44.040
[Guest]: describing a woman's sleeve the sleeve of a dress which is sort of very loose

01:10:44.240 --> 01:10:48.040
[Guest]: and big and how he describes the sleeve it's a sentence goes on for pages and

01:10:48.240 --> 01:10:53.040
[Guest]: pages as Proust often tends to do and he starts somewhere and he ends up somewhere

01:10:53.240 --> 01:10:56.040
[Guest]: completely different so and in the middle he's covered this entire lifetime

01:10:56.240 --> 01:11:00.040
[Guest]: and entire sort of you know whole gamut of things he's just covered in that one

01:11:00.040 --> 01:11:05.840
[Guest]: description of a dress you know so it's it was fascinating to me how these things

01:11:06.040 --> 01:11:09.840
[Guest]: can you know they can be done like this this kind of and it's not particularly

01:11:10.040 --> 01:11:14.840
[Guest]: experimental style or anything this is the way his thoughts have gone and I

01:11:15.040 --> 01:11:18.840
[Guest]: realized that writing is actually just just what it is a way of thinking you

01:11:19.040 --> 01:11:23.840
[Amit Varma]: know you think like that so you write like that you know so there are no

01:11:24.040 --> 01:11:28.840
[Guest]: limits as yeah yeah yeah no limits absolutely so these these have been some

01:11:28.840 --> 01:11:32.640
[Guest]: of my favorites and of course then Urdu Nair Masood who's staring me in the face

01:11:32.840 --> 01:11:36.640
[Guest]: right here I'm really fond of him in fact I was thinking of translating him

01:11:36.840 --> 01:11:41.640
[Guest]: also and I went and met him once and he was very keen that yeah but he was he

01:11:41.840 --> 01:11:46.640
[Guest]: wanted his stories more in Hindi rather than English because English already had

01:11:46.840 --> 01:11:52.640
[Guest]: been done by Umar Memon who's his great friend and editor in America so he was

01:11:52.840 --> 01:11:56.640
[Guest]: very keen that they should come out in the Hindi script because people here

01:11:56.640 --> 01:12:01.440
[Guest]: couldn't read his Urdu so I thought of doing that too but then I mean I even

01:12:01.640 --> 01:12:05.440
[Guest]: took along a contract Harper Collins had given me a contract to go and get it

01:12:05.640 --> 01:12:09.440
[Guest]: signed he said oh you just put what you like in it and sign it but as it turned

01:12:09.640 --> 01:12:13.440
[Guest]: out it was a very daunting task because his stories are very difficult I don't

01:12:13.640 --> 01:12:17.440
[Guest]: know if you've read any Nair Masood or I mean not in the original obviously

01:12:17.640 --> 01:12:23.440
[Guest]: yeah because he's he's very very in fact a bit Kafka maybe that's why it appealed

01:12:23.440 --> 01:12:30.240
[Guest]: to me in the first place but but his thoughts are very very like a distillation

01:12:30.440 --> 01:12:35.240
[Guest]: I mean there's something going on in the and and they are always set in these

01:12:35.440 --> 01:12:40.240
[Guest]: very sort of lower class Muslim localities and the kind of things he

01:12:40.440 --> 01:12:44.240
[Guest]: describes are almost read like magic realism because we don't know that world

01:12:44.440 --> 01:12:48.240
[Guest]: no so that and his thoughts and very very subtle like there's this story

01:12:48.240 --> 01:12:55.040
[Guest]: called Essence of Camphor which is the Ithre Kafur it's called in Urdu and it's

01:12:55.240 --> 01:12:59.040
[Guest]: about the whole process of making perfume and how the vapors rise from it

01:12:59.240 --> 01:13:02.040
[Guest]: and you know it's just he describes very kind of abstract things and he links

01:13:02.240 --> 01:13:06.040
[Guest]: them up with something completely different so he has this wonderful feel

01:13:06.240 --> 01:13:11.040
[Guest]: so Nair Masood was also one of the people I was reading and Isma Chuktai

01:13:11.240 --> 01:13:16.040
[Guest]: in the Urdu writers Isma Chuktai is fantastic she's she's very nice and we

01:13:16.040 --> 01:13:19.840
[Guest]: also have like Alok my cousin and Francesca I don't know if you know

01:13:20.040 --> 01:13:23.840
[Guest]: Francesca Orsini I mean she's also a close friend so when she comes so three

01:13:24.040 --> 01:13:28.840
[Guest]: of us form an Urdu reading group so we pick up these and Francesca usually

01:13:29.040 --> 01:13:32.840
[Guest]: brings something nice along from England and then we sit together and we read

01:13:33.040 --> 01:13:38.840
[Guest]: these Urdu texts so one of the things we read was Umrao Jaana Da and I did not

01:13:39.040 --> 01:13:41.840
[Guest]: know how what a wonderful book it is you know it's just absolutely fantastic I

01:13:41.840 --> 01:13:46.640
[Guest]: mean it's set in that time 1857 it captures the events of that era and this

01:13:46.840 --> 01:13:51.640
[Guest]: and it's so I mean it moves so quickly and so that was one of the things we

01:13:51.840 --> 01:13:55.640
[Guest]: read and these are the Urdu books I'm talking of then Hindi of course my

01:13:55.840 --> 01:13:59.640
[Guest]: favorites have been Vinod Kumar Shukla and Jyotsna Millan I don't know if you

01:13:59.840 --> 01:14:04.640
[Guest]: read her but she's she's a fine writer my friend also she was my friend who

01:14:04.840 --> 01:14:08.640
[Guest]: died a few years ago sadly so she's there's a Hindi also there's there's

01:14:08.640 --> 01:14:14.440
[Guest]: enough to read you know there's plenty to read in Hindi and Urdu of course

01:14:14.640 --> 01:14:18.440
[Amit Varma]: this is sort of the other thought that strikes me and it struck me a lot over

01:14:18.640 --> 01:14:22.440
[Amit Varma]: the last three or four years because before that for most of my life I've

01:14:22.640 --> 01:14:26.440
[Amit Varma]: assumed that hey it's a globalized world it's open there is a internet everybody

01:14:26.640 --> 01:14:30.440
[Amit Varma]: can read everything everything is open to me in a sense it's accessible to me

01:14:30.640 --> 01:14:35.440
[Amit Varma]: and I've realized recently that that's not true it's it's an illusion that

01:14:35.440 --> 01:14:39.240
[Amit Varma]: English-speaking elites can sometimes have because they think that you know

01:14:39.440 --> 01:14:43.240
[Unknown]: English is the center of the universe or everything and you know in past

01:14:43.440 --> 01:14:47.240
[Amit Varma]: episodes I've realized that there is you know for example just moving for a

01:14:47.440 --> 01:14:52.240
[Amit Varma]: moment to politics I've understood that Ram Guha had written this excellent essay

01:14:52.440 --> 01:14:56.240
[Amit Varma]: about how there are no right-wing intellectuals in India and that's

01:14:56.440 --> 01:14:59.240
[Amit Varma]: something I broadly believed in I thought everything that you see from the

01:14:59.440 --> 01:15:04.240
[Amit Varma]: right is bigotry which is cloaked up in a kind of pseudo intellectualism but I

01:15:04.240 --> 01:15:08.040
[Amit Varma]: have since kind of been convinced by friends who've been on this show who've

01:15:08.240 --> 01:15:11.040
[Amit Varma]: done their reading in Hindi and other languages that there is an intellectual

01:15:11.240 --> 01:15:14.040
[Amit Varma]: tradition one may disagree with it strongly but there is a coherent

01:15:14.240 --> 01:15:19.040
[Amit Varma]: intellectual tradition of ideas which English speakers are kind of missing out

01:15:19.240 --> 01:15:23.040
[Amit Varma]: and sort of moving back to literature I had that same sense where I was trying

01:15:23.240 --> 01:15:27.040
[Amit Varma]: to read things by you and I read a couple of some of your essays and a

01:15:27.240 --> 01:15:30.040
[Amit Varma]: couple of stories in the magazine Pratilipi which I'll link to from the

01:15:30.040 --> 01:15:34.840
[Amit Varma]: show notes which I absolutely loved and I'd also like to discuss but nothing else

01:15:35.040 --> 01:15:37.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean everything else is in Hindi and I can read in Hindi and I intend to start

01:15:38.040 --> 01:15:41.840
[Amit Varma]: reading more in Hindi anyway so I will get down to reading them but that world

01:15:42.040 --> 01:15:45.840
[Amit Varma]: is close to me you know when someone sits there and they talk about writers

01:15:46.040 --> 01:15:48.840
[Amit Varma]: who write in English and have you read so-and-so and have you read so-and-so

01:15:49.040 --> 01:15:52.840
[Unknown]: and I've generally read them you know I've read Sebald, I've read Kavar, I've

01:15:53.040 --> 01:15:55.840
[Unknown]: read all these people but I haven't read the other names that you took in the

01:15:55.840 --> 01:15:59.640
[Amit Varma]: other languages it's like that world is completely close to me now my question

01:15:59.840 --> 01:16:06.640
[Amit Varma]: is is that world in a sense then lost or is there hope because you know how do we

01:16:06.840 --> 01:16:11.640
[Amit Varma]: kind of reach that more or more more and more what you have is sort of a

01:16:11.840 --> 01:16:16.640
[Amit Varma]: homogenization of cultures and societies and economies like even in English

01:16:16.840 --> 01:16:19.640
[Amit Varma]: Snigdha Poonam the journalist had been on the show before she's written a book

01:16:19.840 --> 01:16:23.640
[Amit Varma]: called Dreamers where she writes about how in small towns there is this craze

01:16:23.640 --> 01:16:28.440
[Amit Varma]: for everyone to learn English at first just at a functional level but there is

01:16:28.640 --> 01:16:33.440
[Amit Varma]: this kind of craze and also there is this kind of snobbery the reverse of what

01:16:33.640 --> 01:16:36.440
[Amit Varma]: you probably felt at home where people are embarrassed to talk in their

01:16:36.640 --> 01:16:41.440
[Unknown]: vernaculars and their specific you know I had a question from a friend of mine

01:16:41.640 --> 01:16:45.440
[Amit Varma]: who had done my writing course where he said that he writes in Kannada but he

01:16:45.640 --> 01:16:48.440
[Unknown]: writes in a particular dialect of Kannada not the mainstream thing so he's

01:16:48.640 --> 01:16:51.440
[Amit Varma]: saying that should I write in that because that's what comes most naturally

01:16:51.440 --> 01:16:57.240
[Amit Varma]: or should I try to write in proper Kannada and it's a I don't know how to

01:16:57.440 --> 01:17:00.240
[Amit Varma]: answer that because part of me says that no you got to be authentic to yourself

01:17:00.440 --> 01:17:03.240
[Unknown]: and write in that dialect where everything is coming naturally to you

01:17:03.440 --> 01:17:08.240
[Amit Varma]: it's authentic but you also want to be read and maybe that's a dying language

01:17:08.440 --> 01:17:12.240
[Guest]: yeah is this something that you kind of think I have thought about it quite a lot

01:17:12.440 --> 01:17:17.240
[Guest]: actually but I think it's something to do with our education system I mean like

01:17:17.240 --> 01:17:23.040
[Guest]: we are not taught any of our own texts you know Sanskrit or Farsi or Urdu or

01:17:23.240 --> 01:17:26.040
[Guest]: whatever we are not taught at the school level we should have something like that

01:17:26.240 --> 01:17:30.040
[Guest]: and the text that they do prescribe in Hindi for instance is one language that

01:17:30.240 --> 01:17:34.040
[Guest]: they do have texts in but they are so boring they are so utterly boring which

01:17:34.240 --> 01:17:38.040
[Guest]: child will read you know Jago Mohan Pyare or something like I mean you know

01:17:38.240 --> 01:17:42.040
[Guest]: one of those things why will they read all these moralistic and weird sort of

01:17:42.040 --> 01:17:48.840
[Guest]: narratives or like lives of patriots or things like that who will read those I

01:17:49.040 --> 01:17:51.840
[Guest]: mean you have to have interesting material for children to start with I

01:17:52.040 --> 01:17:54.840
[Guest]: mean you are doing the language a service if you have something interesting

01:17:55.040 --> 01:17:58.840
[Guest]: and they could have Sanskrit texts you know there's so much erotic literature

01:17:59.040 --> 01:18:02.840
[Guest]: in Sanskrit for instance there's so much poetry there's so much nature writing

01:18:03.040 --> 01:18:05.840
[Guest]: the Kalidas I think of Kalidas and Meghdootam and you know things like that

01:18:06.040 --> 01:18:10.840
[Guest]: we are completely cut off from that all because of I think our education system

01:18:10.840 --> 01:18:16.640
[Guest]: which is all skewed and it is very heavily weighted in favor of English and

01:18:16.840 --> 01:18:20.640
[Guest]: the lower middle classes who do not have access to that education are still

01:18:20.840 --> 01:18:25.640
[Guest]: reading very widely in other languages in Hindi like when I when I started

01:18:25.840 --> 01:18:29.640
[Guest]: writing in Hindi I used to get so much so many letters from everywhere I got a

01:18:29.840 --> 01:18:33.640
[Guest]: letter from Goa jail I remember people are reading these things and they are

01:18:33.840 --> 01:18:38.640
[Guest]: probably not buying their own books but they are circulating the same books so

01:18:38.640 --> 01:18:42.440
[Guest]: much is being read I think it's a problem of the middle class rather than

01:18:42.640 --> 01:18:46.440
[Guest]: other classes and middle class is a small class but still it's the most

01:18:46.640 --> 01:18:52.440
[Guest]: powerful class and English is perceived as the language of success or power or

01:18:52.640 --> 01:18:56.440
[Guest]: whatever you know English so the whole world becomes open to you so I don't

01:18:56.640 --> 01:19:00.440
[Guest]: blame these people I mean it's just I think we should introduce some of these

01:19:00.640 --> 01:19:04.440
[Guest]: nice texts in at the school level so that people don't go away from the

01:19:04.640 --> 01:19:07.440
[Guest]: languages I mean they behave as if English Hindi is a foreign language you

01:19:07.440 --> 01:19:11.240
[Guest]: know they behave as if they are sort of native speakers of English and Hindi has

01:19:11.440 --> 01:19:15.240
[Guest]: somehow come in and this is some foreign language that they have to learn so the

01:19:15.440 --> 01:19:19.240
[Guest]: education system I think has to be overhauled in a very big way for people

01:19:19.440 --> 01:19:23.240
[Guest]: to develop an interest in I mean it's not the same situation for Marathi or

01:19:23.440 --> 01:19:28.240
[Guest]: Bangla or Malayalam I mean people are you know doing work they are sort of

01:19:28.440 --> 01:19:33.240
[Guest]: being read I mean it's not the same it's the northern India the Hindi belt I

01:19:33.240 --> 01:19:39.040
[Guest]: would say Delhi, UP you know all these places where English is gains primacy

01:19:39.240 --> 01:19:49.040
[Guest]: for other reasons I think than literary so it's just I think it can be fixed if

01:19:49.240 --> 01:19:54.040
[Guest]: I don't know I mean if they'll have to really sort of do hack job, hack it job,

01:19:54.240 --> 01:19:59.040
[Guest]: hatchet job whatever you call it hatchet job with the education system and

01:19:59.040 --> 01:20:03.840
[Amit Varma]: overhaul it completely. I have no hopes of a top-down interventions working or

01:20:04.040 --> 01:20:07.840
[Amit Varma]: even the education system necessarily changing this I'm more interested in how

01:20:08.040 --> 01:20:10.840
[Amit Varma]: things happen in a bottom-up way through the culture and all that and there's an

01:20:11.040 --> 01:20:14.840
[Amit Varma]: interesting sort of anecdote you mentioned in your essay in the Premchand

01:20:15.040 --> 01:20:17.840
[Amit Varma]: book where you talk about how you went to the village where he was born for his

01:20:18.040 --> 01:20:24.840
[Amit Varma]: 125th anniversary in 2006 and while you were waiting for things to happen and all

01:20:24.840 --> 01:20:29.640
[Amit Varma]: of that you notice that there were so many people sitting around everywhere you know

01:20:29.840 --> 01:20:33.640
[Amit Varma]: under shelter not under shelter sitting on the ground just waiting for this whole

01:20:33.840 --> 01:20:37.640
[Amit Varma]: thing to happen and at that point you're musing is that okay I know why I am here

01:20:37.840 --> 01:20:41.640
[Amit Varma]: but why are these people here and you pointed out how some of them obviously

01:20:41.840 --> 01:20:45.640
[Amit Varma]: many of them must be Premchand readers and some of them could in fact be

01:20:45.840 --> 01:20:49.640
[Amit Varma]: characters out of his stories as you said and that struck me is again something

01:20:49.640 --> 01:20:55.440
[Amit Varma]: interesting to explore because I think there was a time in our culture where individual

01:20:55.640 --> 01:20:59.440
[Amit Varma]: figures could play that kind of a very profound part in people's lives where

01:20:59.640 --> 01:21:03.440
[Amit Varma]: people are reading a writer in this case Premchand and finding so much to

01:21:03.640 --> 01:21:08.440
[Amit Varma]: identify with that you know it becomes something that is important for them and

01:21:08.640 --> 01:21:13.440
[Amit Varma]: what has happened in modern times I think and tell me what you feel about

01:21:13.640 --> 01:21:17.440
[Amit Varma]: this is that in my view what has happened is that this kind of thing is

01:21:17.440 --> 01:21:21.240
[Amit Varma]: becoming less and less possible in the sense that one there is a lot more art

01:21:21.440 --> 01:21:26.240
[Amit Varma]: and many more artists which is a good thing but also whatever experiences we

01:21:26.440 --> 01:21:30.240
[Amit Varma]: are having a very fragmented in a sense so it won't just be one writer who moves

01:21:30.440 --> 01:21:34.240
[Amit Varma]: me with his five books it will be many many writers whose snippets I'll read on

01:21:34.440 --> 01:21:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Instagram or Facebook or whatever which will have an effect on me and the whole

01:21:38.440 --> 01:21:42.240
[Amit Varma]: sort of thing kind of gets broken down leading me to wonder whether another

01:21:42.440 --> 01:21:46.240
[Amit Varma]: Premchand is even possible today or maybe another Premchand is possible in

01:21:46.240 --> 01:21:52.040
[Amit Varma]: a new medium like vlogs or you know Instagram for example I mean what would

01:21:52.240 --> 01:21:57.040
[Amit Varma]: an Instagram Premchand look like I can't imagine maybe like the humans of New York

01:21:57.240 --> 01:22:01.040
[Amit Varma]: blog that took off a few years ago but I'm just thinking aloud so what's your

01:22:01.240 --> 01:22:06.040
[Amit Varma]: thought on the changing nature of the role that writers play within a culture

01:22:06.240 --> 01:22:10.040
[Amit Varma]: or I'll say in a general sense I'll say artists or creators whatever term you

01:22:10.240 --> 01:22:14.040
[Amit Varma]: would like to use the role that they play within a culture and is that

01:22:14.040 --> 01:22:18.840
[Amit Varma]: diminishing partly because there is less dullness people have so much to do in

01:22:19.040 --> 01:22:23.840
[Amit Varma]: their lives they don't have to read it's no longer the one entertaining thing

01:22:24.040 --> 01:22:26.840
[Amit Varma]: that there is for them there is so much else to do what's your sense of this

01:22:27.040 --> 01:22:30.840
[Guest]: well I think as far as I mean you mentioned all those people who had come

01:22:31.040 --> 01:22:35.840
[Guest]: for Premchand's that ceremony that they had but that had also something to do

01:22:36.040 --> 01:22:41.840
[Guest]: with the fact that Premchand actually established the common man as a valid

01:22:41.840 --> 01:22:46.640
[Guest]: character in literature before that the stories were not about the common man and

01:22:46.840 --> 01:22:51.640
[Guest]: people could not identify with those and these people are almost it's they are

01:22:51.840 --> 01:22:56.640
[Guest]: vindicated in some sense that they have been the existence had been noticed

01:22:56.840 --> 01:23:01.640
[Guest]: their lives are worthy of being written about you know so it's a moral value

01:23:01.840 --> 01:23:05.640
[Guest]: that he brings to those writings so and this question also ties up with the

01:23:05.640 --> 01:23:12.440
[Guest]: later one that you asked about writers what can who can replace Premchand that

01:23:12.640 --> 01:23:17.440
[Guest]: kind of thing but I think it's a moral universe the moral universe has

01:23:17.640 --> 01:23:22.440
[Guest]: completely radically changed and the role of the writer has also changed

01:23:22.640 --> 01:23:25.440
[Guest]: correspondingly the role of the writer the image of the writer has also

01:23:25.640 --> 01:23:29.440
[Guest]: undergone a sea change because of that you know I mean earlier writers like we

01:23:29.640 --> 01:23:32.440
[Guest]: perceived the writer as someone who's you know hiding away in some corner

01:23:32.440 --> 01:23:37.240
[Guest]: scribbling his things and you know he's committed he lives in poverty he lives

01:23:37.440 --> 01:23:41.240
[Guest]: you know hand-to-mouth very much like the figure Premchand is and he's like

01:23:41.440 --> 01:23:46.240
[Guest]: that and now but now that has changed writers are no longer like that writers

01:23:46.440 --> 01:23:49.240
[Guest]: like to be seen I mean you see them everywhere you see them at literary

01:23:49.440 --> 01:23:54.240
[Guest]: festivals you see them when you get a prize for in that a prize ceremony I

01:23:54.440 --> 01:23:58.240
[Guest]: mean everyone is visible there's so many cameras there's so many lights there's

01:23:58.240 --> 01:24:02.040
[Guest]: so much you know flashing thing going on you know writers are much more in the

01:24:02.240 --> 01:24:08.040
[Guest]: limelight but in a sense I mean I know I'm making this horrible generalization

01:24:08.240 --> 01:24:15.040
[Guest]: but it's like people are becoming clones you know very kind of many books that

01:24:15.240 --> 01:24:19.040
[Guest]: you read feel very much like the other book you know there's not much it's

01:24:19.240 --> 01:24:23.040
[Guest]: because there's a lot of emptiness I think in books that are being written

01:24:23.240 --> 01:24:26.040
[Guest]: because they're being written in a hurry they are being written for a particular

01:24:26.040 --> 01:24:29.840
[Guest]: reason they are being written maybe because they can get a prize or maybe

01:24:30.040 --> 01:24:33.840
[Guest]: they can be published so they are being I don't really understand the need for

01:24:34.040 --> 01:24:39.840
[Guest]: this kind of frothy writing and creative schools creative writing schools I think

01:24:40.040 --> 01:24:43.840
[Guest]: have maybe contributed to this to a certain kind of writing which is the

01:24:44.040 --> 01:24:46.840
[Guest]: same for everyone you know they have this smart writing which comes from

01:24:47.040 --> 01:24:50.840
[Guest]: there you learn how to show not tell is the typical phrase that is used now in

01:24:50.840 --> 01:24:57.640
[Guest]: the West so that on describing things and but you sometimes you are you search

01:24:57.840 --> 01:25:02.640
[Guest]: for a single insight in a book you don't find it you know there are lots of

01:25:02.840 --> 01:25:06.640
[Guest]: descriptions very authentic stuff and the very much related to what is going

01:25:06.840 --> 01:25:11.640
[Guest]: on outside in the society but somehow it just lacks that spark because they don't

01:25:11.840 --> 01:25:15.640
[Guest]: give any original insight many books of course there'll be many exceptions to

01:25:15.840 --> 01:25:19.640
[Guest]: this too but this is what I have found that there's a certain sameness to the

01:25:19.640 --> 01:25:25.440
[Guest]: writing that's happening and maybe it's because of the hurry or because I mean

01:25:25.640 --> 01:25:31.440
[Guest]: everyone is absorbing similar stuff around and writing in English definitely

01:25:31.640 --> 01:25:35.440
[Guest]: can only come from a certain class because a lower middle class person is

01:25:35.640 --> 01:25:40.440
[Guest]: never going to write in English so it reflects that class background too so

01:25:40.640 --> 01:25:44.440
[Guest]: well that's I think it strikes me that there are really two kinds of writers

01:25:44.440 --> 01:25:50.240
[Amit Varma]: and one kind of writer is in love with the notion of being a writer everything

01:25:50.440 --> 01:25:54.240
[Unknown]: that it involves I will write these kind of serious literary books and I'll get

01:25:54.440 --> 01:25:58.240
[Amit Varma]: long-listed for the booker and blah blah blah and I think the kind of writers I

01:25:58.440 --> 01:26:02.240
[Amit Varma]: end up liking are just writers who just want to write and therefore there is less

01:26:02.440 --> 01:26:06.240
[Amit Varma]: artifice in that there is you know it's not contrived they are trying to write a

01:26:06.440 --> 01:26:10.240
[Amit Varma]: particular kind of book which is in vogue I want to sort of double click on a

01:26:10.240 --> 01:26:16.040
[Amit Varma]: phrase that you used at the start of your answer which was moral universe

01:26:16.240 --> 01:26:19.040
[Amit Varma]: where you pointed out that the moral universe has changed and therefore so has

01:26:19.240 --> 01:26:24.040
[Guest]: a writer within it what do you mean by that well moral universe has suppose I

01:26:24.240 --> 01:26:29.040
[Guest]: mean that the world is much more complex now and it's not so easy to chart out a

01:26:29.240 --> 01:26:34.040
[Guest]: course in which in which you can know which is what is the right thing to do

01:26:34.240 --> 01:26:39.040
[Guest]: you know I mean there's nothing really it's it's in a sense much much more

01:26:39.040 --> 01:26:42.840
[Guest]: fragmented than the times that Plameson lived in and when there was a definite

01:26:43.040 --> 01:26:47.840
[Guest]: goal that we were trying to achieve independence and the you know stopping

01:26:48.040 --> 01:26:53.840
[Guest]: the oppression of the farmers of the poor people so all that has changed and

01:26:54.040 --> 01:26:57.840
[Guest]: I mean I presume we are talking only of English writing in English just now

01:26:58.040 --> 01:27:01.840
[Guest]: whatever sense you meant that in when you spoke of moral yeah moral universe is

01:27:02.040 --> 01:27:06.840
[Guest]: I think just this you know just the whole urban mess that we live in it's

01:27:06.840 --> 01:27:11.640
[Guest]: very very fragmented very diverse there's too much happening there's not

01:27:11.840 --> 01:27:18.640
[Guest]: enough direction no so it's it's a very confused world so I mean to find

01:27:18.840 --> 01:27:24.640
[Guest]: something of value is can be a struggle in this kind of world and I'm not sure

01:27:24.840 --> 01:27:29.640
[Guest]: that every many writers are up to it I don't know I can't give you concrete

01:27:29.840 --> 01:27:33.640
[Guest]: examples just now but I have my feeling is that there is nothing that we are

01:27:33.640 --> 01:27:39.440
[Guest]: striving for as such you mean in an individual sense or social sense

01:27:39.640 --> 01:27:43.440
[Guest]: individual sense in an individual sense there is not what is one has to have

01:27:43.640 --> 01:27:48.440
[Guest]: some kind of thing that one is trying to achieve when you are writing a book

01:27:48.640 --> 01:27:52.440
[Amit Varma]: yeah in the in the sense that you mean that Plameson very clearly did in terms

01:27:52.640 --> 01:27:58.440
[Guest]: of the social messaging he's trying to reach some thing he's trying to you know

01:27:58.440 --> 01:28:04.240
[Guest]: anti-colonial fighting colonialism fighting whatever you know all that

01:28:04.440 --> 01:28:10.240
[Guest]: stuff is gone so now we have this of course there's much fine writing

01:28:10.440 --> 01:28:16.240
[Guest]: happening even now as we have recently discovered but there's there's much more

01:28:16.440 --> 01:28:21.240
[Guest]: writing going on and I'm not sure that all of it will is worth the read I think

01:28:21.440 --> 01:28:25.240
[Amit Varma]: like that I'm just thinking aloud another way of thinking of that is

01:28:25.240 --> 01:28:30.040
[Amit Varma]: there's something called Sturgeon's law which basically it was first I think

01:28:30.240 --> 01:28:34.040
[Amit Varma]: meant for science fiction but it applies to everything eventually and Sturgeon's

01:28:34.240 --> 01:28:39.040
[Amit Varma]: law is that 95% of everything is crap that's Sturgeon's law and what happens

01:28:39.240 --> 01:28:42.040
[Amit Varma]: sometimes is that we look at the past and there's some selection bias creeping

01:28:42.240 --> 01:28:45.040
[Amit Varma]: in because obviously what we remember of the past is all the good stuff the

01:28:45.240 --> 01:28:49.040
[Unknown]: highlights but when we look at the present it's all hundred percent that is

01:28:49.240 --> 01:28:53.040
[Amit Varma]: out there so it seems like oh those were golden times but these are not and I

01:28:53.040 --> 01:28:56.840
[Amit Varma]: think that one there must have been as much crap back then and to a lot of the

01:28:57.040 --> 01:28:59.840
[Amit Varma]: crap wouldn't have got published because it was so much harder to get published

01:29:00.040 --> 01:29:06.840
[Amit Varma]: in terms of gatekeepers while today without reference to anything that we

01:29:07.040 --> 01:29:09.840
[Amit Varma]: might have gone through in the recent past in terms of the reading we've done

01:29:10.040 --> 01:29:12.840
[Amit Varma]: without reference to that I think publishers are a lot more indiscriminate

01:29:13.040 --> 01:29:16.840
[Amit Varma]: in that they'll put out anything yeah and in a sense that's a good thing that

01:29:17.040 --> 01:29:20.840
[Amit Varma]: the barriers of publishing are much lower but you know so therefore you will

01:29:20.840 --> 01:29:25.640
[Unknown]: simply have more of the crap and that 5% just seems to be so little and

01:29:25.840 --> 01:29:29.640
[Unknown]: swimming in that sea and a lot of it lost to people like me because I might be

01:29:29.840 --> 01:29:33.640
[Guest]: restricted to reading one language or a particular I never discovered that right

01:29:33.840 --> 01:29:38.640
[Guest]: yeah and we also we also don't have the advantage of time I mean like if we were

01:29:38.840 --> 01:29:43.640
[Guest]: to look at the same stuff say 50 years down the line we would probably the good

01:29:43.840 --> 01:29:47.640
[Guest]: names or whatever names that we remember now from the past the similar names

01:29:47.640 --> 01:29:51.440
[Guest]: would have cropped up then but we don't have the advantage of that because we

01:29:51.640 --> 01:29:54.440
[Guest]: don't know that will only show itself with time in the classics or whatever

01:29:54.640 --> 01:29:59.440
[Guest]: you call them you know the good books of this time will only pop up you know

01:29:59.640 --> 01:30:06.440
[Guest]: later so how do we I mean who has withstood the stand of time we can't find that out now you know

01:30:06.640 --> 01:30:10.440
[Amit Varma]: so in the interest of following the digressive nature of this podcast the thought

01:30:10.640 --> 01:30:14.440
[Amit Varma]: that just comes to mind and I'll throw it at you I was watching this vlog by this

01:30:14.440 --> 01:30:19.240
[Amit Varma]: fantastic musician called Rick Beato he's a 59 year old guy he does this thing on

01:30:19.440 --> 01:30:23.240
[Amit Varma]: YouTube where he'll talk about music or he has a series which is called what makes

01:30:23.440 --> 01:30:26.240
[Unknown]: this song great where he'll break down a three-minute song and yeah talk about

01:30:26.440 --> 01:30:30.240
[Amit Varma]: different aspects of that one of his recent videos was this complete rant

01:30:30.440 --> 01:30:34.240
[Amit Varma]: very completely lost it because he came across an article this guy had written

01:30:34.440 --> 01:30:38.240
[Amit Varma]: where this guy said that you know Paul Simon will not be remembered 200 years

01:30:38.440 --> 01:30:42.240
[Amit Varma]: from now and he was saying that listen let me tell you something the people who

01:30:42.240 --> 01:30:46.040
[Amit Varma]: will be remembered 200 years from now we may not have heard of them today and he

01:30:46.240 --> 01:30:51.040
[Unknown]: gave the example of Johann Sebastian Bach the classical composer talking about

01:30:51.240 --> 01:30:56.040
[Amit Varma]: how in his own lifetime he wasn't a particularly big deal after his death

01:30:56.240 --> 01:31:00.040
[Amit Varma]: there was a kind of Bach reclamation or something I forget there's a term for it

01:31:00.240 --> 01:31:04.040
[Amit Varma]: but that made him the legend that we think of him today as well in his own

01:31:04.240 --> 01:31:08.040
[Amit Varma]: lifetime he was completely obscure and that seems a fascinating thought to me

01:31:08.040 --> 01:31:12.840
[Amit Varma]: that someone who is a great artist today maybe somebody we haven't even heard of

01:31:13.040 --> 01:31:16.840
[Unknown]: but 200 years later is regarded that way not that it necessarily makes a

01:31:17.040 --> 01:31:20.840
[Unknown]: difference to an artist how he is regarded 200 years later he wants it now

01:31:21.040 --> 01:31:24.840
[Amit Varma]: and the other thing is also the role of happenstance in getting noticed

01:31:25.040 --> 01:31:28.840
[Amit Varma]: like someone recently put up this long thread about Billy Joel that when Billy

01:31:29.040 --> 01:31:33.840
[Amit Varma]: Joel's first album Piano Man came out it was completely unnoticed it wasn't

01:31:33.840 --> 01:31:38.640
[Amit Varma]: selling anywhere radio stations weren't playing it it was basically lost and the

01:31:38.840 --> 01:31:41.640
[Amit Varma]: music company decided not to do anything with it they were washing their hands off

01:31:41.840 --> 01:31:45.640
[Amit Varma]: but there was one listener who felt passionate about it who happened to have

01:31:45.840 --> 01:31:49.640
[Amit Varma]: a copy and he went to radio station after radio station after radio station

01:31:49.840 --> 01:31:53.640
[Amit Varma]: trying to make them play it and eventually did a quid pro quo with the radio

01:31:53.840 --> 01:31:57.640
[Unknown]: station RJ and made him play it and then it became the sensation that it was

01:31:57.840 --> 01:32:02.640
[Unknown]: and Billy Joel would probably have gone back to his day job if that hadn't taken

01:32:02.640 --> 01:32:06.440
[Guest]: off so the role of happenstance is so incredible.

01:32:06.640 --> 01:32:10.440
[Guest]: And I think that's I mean somebody should do a separate project on this the making

01:32:10.640 --> 01:32:14.440
[Guest]: of a legend how do legends get made because I mean if you go into individual

01:32:14.640 --> 01:32:19.440
[Guest]: lives I mean what is it that has brought them to the fore I mean to a layman

01:32:19.640 --> 01:32:24.440
[Guest]: layperson like me one song or one piece of music would perhaps sound very much

01:32:24.640 --> 01:32:29.440
[Guest]: similar to the other one but I mean there's something about that one that is

01:32:29.440 --> 01:32:34.240
[Guest]: better than this one and of course how does how does it happen that some

01:32:34.440 --> 01:32:37.240
[Guest]: people get noticed and some don't there's so much fine writing around but

01:32:37.440 --> 01:32:39.240
[Guest]: only some gets noticed.

01:32:39.440 --> 01:32:42.240
[Amit Varma]: No and it's not even that the fine writing gets noticed and the non-fine

01:32:42.440 --> 01:32:46.240
[Amit Varma]: doesn't like I think there was a social science experiment a few years ago

01:32:46.440 --> 01:32:51.240
[Amit Varma]: where people gave a whole the subjects in the experiment these apps which have

01:32:51.440 --> 01:32:54.240
[Amit Varma]: and I'm kind of paraphrasing it so obviously the mechanism was slightly

01:32:54.440 --> 01:32:57.240
[Amit Varma]: different but in principle it's like this but all these people were given an

01:32:57.240 --> 01:33:02.040
[Amit Varma]: app with like 2,000 songs or whatever and they had to listen to whatever they

01:33:02.240 --> 01:33:07.040
[Amit Varma]: wanted over a period of time except that in some of them were shown a chart of

01:33:07.240 --> 01:33:11.040
[Amit Varma]: what is popular and what is not and they were all shown different charts and in

01:33:11.240 --> 01:33:15.040
[Amit Varma]: these different mini universes of these users that they built different songs

01:33:15.240 --> 01:33:19.040
[Amit Varma]: rose to the top or went down just depending on pure happenstance you know

01:33:19.240 --> 01:33:23.040
[Amit Varma]: you five people could accidentally listen to something and like it and not

01:33:23.040 --> 01:33:26.840
[Unknown]: have noticed something else and suddenly just by those five people liking it the

01:33:27.040 --> 01:33:29.840
[Guest]: algorithm stayed over and rose to the top.

01:33:30.040 --> 01:33:32.840
[Guest]: So it's all a bit of an accident really.

01:33:33.040 --> 01:33:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Everything is an accident.

01:33:36.040 --> 01:33:40.840
[Amit Varma]: So let's go back more to the accident of life itself in particular yours.

01:33:41.040 --> 01:33:44.840
[Amit Varma]: So you know you're a prolific reader you've written this story Lucky Horace

01:33:45.040 --> 01:33:50.840
[Amit Varma]: at the age of 8 and gotten published and then you next write when you're late

01:33:50.840 --> 01:33:53.640
[Unknown]: 30s 40s whatever much decades pass almost.

01:33:53.840 --> 01:33:57.640
[Amit Varma]: What's happening during this period of time and also what is your

01:33:57.840 --> 01:34:00.640
[Amit Varma]: conception of yourself and how is it changing because you've said that even

01:34:00.840 --> 01:34:03.640
[Amit Varma]: if you didn't articulate it to yourself you felt that there was a writer inside

01:34:03.840 --> 01:34:07.640
[Unknown]: you, it was natural. Tell me a little bit about the young Serarai

01:34:07.840 --> 01:34:10.640
[Amit Varma]: for example what did you see yourself as and so on.

01:34:10.840 --> 01:34:14.640
[Guest]: Well at that point I mean I don't know if I was having any very clear thoughts

01:34:14.840 --> 01:34:19.640
[Guest]: about what I am or what where I'm headed or what I'm going to do it was all like

01:34:19.640 --> 01:34:26.440
[Guest]: experiencing things as they came along I mean as far as literally pursuit goes

01:34:26.640 --> 01:34:31.440
[Guest]: I think my first experiment apart from that story was I also wrote a few

01:34:31.640 --> 01:34:34.440
[Guest]: horrible poems which I have completely I've hidden them away and I've thrown

01:34:34.640 --> 01:34:39.440
[Guest]: them and nobody has seen them so that little thing happened and then after

01:34:39.640 --> 01:34:43.440
[Guest]: that I suppose the translation was the next thing that I tried to bring my hand

01:34:43.640 --> 01:34:48.440
[Guest]: to and it started with I think Premchand's story first story that

01:34:48.440 --> 01:34:53.240
[Guest]: translated was Bade Bhai Sahib or one of those stories years back I mean

01:34:53.440 --> 01:34:57.240
[Guest]: when I may have been in my 20s early 20s something like that so it's been a long

01:34:57.440 --> 01:35:02.240
[Guest]: process of groping about for a language that I could write in and the translation

01:35:02.440 --> 01:35:08.240
[Guest]: was also a part of that you know because translation and fiction or your own

01:35:08.440 --> 01:35:12.240
[Guest]: writing comes from the same place I mean it's the same storehouse of words that

01:35:12.440 --> 01:35:16.240
[Guest]: you have inside you so in one you're trying to fish out from that storehouse

01:35:16.240 --> 01:35:24.040
[Guest]: and extend it by translations which are someone else's work but you become

01:35:24.240 --> 01:35:28.040
[Guest]: they become intimate for you because you have been interacting with them so

01:35:28.240 --> 01:35:34.040
[Guest]: closely and the other is your own writing and the translated stuff is also

01:35:34.240 --> 01:35:39.040
[Guest]: expanding your own vocabulary your own thoughts you're getting ideas I mean

01:35:39.240 --> 01:35:44.040
[Guest]: like someone else's voice that is allowing your own voice to come out you

01:35:44.040 --> 01:35:47.840
[Guest]: know you get I mean that happens a lot with reading as well I mean when you

01:35:48.040 --> 01:35:51.840
[Guest]: read something and you feel oh this is something that I have something like

01:35:52.040 --> 01:35:56.840
[Guest]: this in my own life so you begin to write something which has been set off

01:35:57.040 --> 01:36:02.840
[Guest]: a spark has been set off by something else so this I see it as I mean what I

01:36:03.040 --> 01:36:08.840
[Guest]: have called it I think somewhere is your life is a series of organic moments

01:36:09.040 --> 01:36:12.840
[Guest]: like when you feel lit up by something you see something you experience

01:36:12.840 --> 01:36:17.640
[Guest]: something and you feel that there's something special about that moment and

01:36:17.840 --> 01:36:22.640
[Guest]: you get a kind of lit up is the word I can think for it so that is somewhere

01:36:22.840 --> 01:36:26.640
[Guest]: being stored inside you and when you're writing those moments fall together

01:36:26.840 --> 01:36:31.640
[Guest]: somehow and they come out and then the style also depends on what you are

01:36:31.840 --> 01:36:36.640
[Guest]: writing so the style will be geared to that and the language too will be geared

01:36:36.840 --> 01:36:41.640
[Guest]: to that like if I'm writing the atmospheres say if I'm writing about a

01:36:41.640 --> 01:36:46.440
[Guest]: Muslim family like my story which is called Bulbulaiya it's the labyrinth

01:36:46.640 --> 01:36:51.440
[Guest]: which is set inside this it's in Banaras so it's a very old town and there's

01:36:51.640 --> 01:36:56.440
[Guest]: this very old house in it and a very old woman living inside that house and

01:36:56.640 --> 01:37:00.440
[Guest]: so the it's a whole thing of labyrinth various kinds of labyrinths like the

01:37:00.640 --> 01:37:03.440
[Guest]: town itself is a labyrinth because of all those gullies and all those little

01:37:03.640 --> 01:37:07.440
[Guest]: bylanes and you know it's a very complicated sort of map geographical map

01:37:07.440 --> 01:37:12.240
[Guest]: of the city and the house which is also very old is about two or three hundred

01:37:12.440 --> 01:37:17.240
[Guest]: years old this is actually my mother's home as it used to be and that is also a

01:37:17.440 --> 01:37:22.240
[Guest]: very big house with many rooms many sort of courtyards and passages and it's

01:37:22.440 --> 01:37:26.240
[Guest]: goes back it has a I've written about that too in the autobiographical essays

01:37:26.440 --> 01:37:31.240
[Guest]: so it's that house and there's this old woman who is dwelling on her memories

01:37:31.440 --> 01:37:35.240
[Guest]: so she's caught in the labyrinth of her memories so it's a very kind of

01:37:35.240 --> 01:37:39.040
[Guest]: interactive sort of labyrinth which is town and house and old woman with her

01:37:39.240 --> 01:37:45.040
[Guest]: years and so it I developed a style for writing that which is not a linear style

01:37:45.240 --> 01:37:50.040
[Guest]: but it's like a shell I mean it goes around you know you she has she

01:37:50.240 --> 01:37:54.040
[Guest]: remembers the past and then she's in the present so it's all structured like

01:37:54.240 --> 01:37:59.040
[Guest]: that so the structure of a story and also the style the language is also

01:37:59.240 --> 01:38:04.040
[Guest]: dictated by the material that's what I started out saying and in the meantime

01:38:04.040 --> 01:38:07.840
[Guest]: I've forgotten your question I've also forgotten it because I got lost

01:38:08.040 --> 01:38:13.840
[Amit Varma]: in my answer so let me move on to kind of quoting you on the writing process

01:38:14.040 --> 01:38:16.840
[Amit Varma]: because this was such a lovely passage and I think all my listeners will really

01:38:17.040 --> 01:38:19.840
[Amit Varma]: enjoy it again from your essay where you wrote quote it took me a long time to

01:38:20.040 --> 01:38:23.840
[Amit Varma]: realize that the process of writing begins much before one has put anything

01:38:24.040 --> 01:38:27.840
[Amit Varma]: down that one has so to speak always been writing it was while chasing

01:38:28.040 --> 01:38:31.840
[Amit Varma]: butterflies in the garden as a child or watching a tortoise shell cat slink away

01:38:31.840 --> 01:38:35.640
[Amit Varma]: into a dark alley that the writing has taken place like an invisible letter

01:38:35.840 --> 01:38:38.640
[Amit Varma]: written with lime juice that only shows up when a hot iron is put to it the

01:38:38.840 --> 01:38:42.640
[Amit Varma]: impressions that have been written onto the memory all the while that life is

01:38:42.840 --> 01:38:45.640
[Amit Varma]: being lived are revealed in the catalyzing moment where pen meets paper

01:38:45.840 --> 01:38:49.640
[Amit Varma]: the city buried underground and long forgotten about is chanced upon and not

01:38:49.840 --> 01:38:53.640
[Amit Varma]: without a shock or surprise so it was that years after the house of my

01:38:53.840 --> 01:38:58.640
[Amit Varma]: childhood had slipped into oblivion I found myself writing stop quote and I'm

01:38:58.640 --> 01:39:03.440
[Amit Varma]: fascinated by what you also said about the act of translation because the act

01:39:03.640 --> 01:39:08.440
[Amit Varma]: of translation is obviously an act of creation itself because in one sense you

01:39:08.640 --> 01:39:13.440
[Amit Varma]: know any language must be impossible to actually translate into another like you

01:39:13.640 --> 01:39:18.440
[Amit Varma]: said of Urdu so while translating did it help that you were looking closely at

01:39:18.640 --> 01:39:22.440
[Amit Varma]: both the languages the language that you're translating from and the language

01:39:22.640 --> 01:39:26.440
[Amit Varma]: that you're translating into I would imagine that that act of mindfully

01:39:26.440 --> 01:39:31.240
[Amit Varma]: looking at each sentence and figuring out how to get something across that act

01:39:31.440 --> 01:39:36.240
[Amit Varma]: of mindfulness itself shapes your own writing and then does that to take a

01:39:36.440 --> 01:39:40.240
[Amit Varma]: step further shape the way that you look at the world around you you know like if

01:39:40.440 --> 01:39:45.240
[Amit Varma]: you see Proust for example going into these deep observations and just going

01:39:45.440 --> 01:39:50.240
[Amit Varma]: you know does that sort of shape the next time that you are going into your

01:39:50.440 --> 01:39:54.240
[Amit Varma]: description of a particular thing do you feel that translation therefore played

01:39:54.240 --> 01:39:59.040
[Amit Varma]: an important part in helping you find your voice as it were.

01:39:59.240 --> 01:40:05.040
[Guest]: Well actually to put it in a very broad sense I think even when you're writing

01:40:05.240 --> 01:40:10.040
[Guest]: your own fiction you're translating because you have seen the world and

01:40:10.240 --> 01:40:13.040
[Guest]: seeing the world and absorbing it is itself an act of translation I mean you

01:40:13.240 --> 01:40:17.040
[Guest]: are seeing visuals around you you're not seeing it in words but to put that world

01:40:17.240 --> 01:40:22.040
[Guest]: in words is already an act of translation so in that sense a fiction writer is

01:40:22.040 --> 01:40:27.840
[Guest]: always a translator and that can be said for any medium of art I suppose I mean

01:40:28.040 --> 01:40:32.840
[Guest]: poetry or fiction or whatever you know it's the same thing I mean you're seeing

01:40:33.040 --> 01:40:36.840
[Guest]: something and you're in your head the pictures are being formed into words and

01:40:37.040 --> 01:40:39.840
[Guest]: those words are then formed into sentences and then you are sort of

01:40:40.040 --> 01:40:43.840
[Guest]: working on those sentences and even those sentences when you are translating

01:40:44.040 --> 01:40:48.840
[Guest]: them into say English then your English is also going to be changed by the way

01:40:48.840 --> 01:40:53.640
[Guest]: you have been brought up the kind of social class that you belong to where you

01:40:53.840 --> 01:40:57.640
[Guest]: have grown up the regional and the cultural parameters of that would affect

01:40:57.840 --> 01:41:03.640
[Guest]: the way you write English also so there are many factors that go into it and it's

01:41:03.840 --> 01:41:07.640
[Guest]: a constant process of the which is ongoing you know you there's nothing

01:41:07.840 --> 01:41:11.640
[Guest]: that you can say I look at this sentence and I think I wonder how to translate it

01:41:11.840 --> 01:41:16.640
[Guest]: it's not like that really for me I mean a translator has to look beyond the text

01:41:16.640 --> 01:41:20.440
[Guest]: you know you have to sort of absorb the text that you have read and then you have

01:41:20.640 --> 01:41:24.440
[Guest]: to because very often a sentence to sentence translation will absolutely not work

01:41:24.640 --> 01:41:31.440
[Guest]: so you have to get somehow creatively transmit what you have read and even if

01:41:31.640 --> 01:41:36.440
[Guest]: it's not exactly what you read it's a kind of you know distillation of what you

01:41:36.640 --> 01:41:43.440
[Guest]: have found in the originary text and you are going to describe it in your own words

01:41:43.440 --> 01:41:49.240
[Guest]: so so I think translation is more and more a thing of absorption you have to

01:41:49.440 --> 01:41:53.240
[Guest]: absorb it in a particular way and you have to get a sense of the language that

01:41:53.440 --> 01:41:58.240
[Guest]: you're translating from and the language you're translating into because the

01:41:58.440 --> 01:42:02.240
[Guest]: the way both languages are structured is very different so one thing may work in

01:42:02.440 --> 01:42:06.240
[Guest]: this language and it may not work in the other language you know so it's you just

01:42:06.440 --> 01:42:10.240
[Guest]: have to have a kind of I suppose you have to look at it in a particular way to be

01:42:10.240 --> 01:42:15.040
[Guest]: able to get it right or there's no question of right or wrong but I mean to

01:42:15.240 --> 01:42:20.040
[Guest]: make it work I mean it has to you there are many factors that are at work

01:42:20.240 --> 01:42:25.040
[Amit Varma]: also you know earlier you spoke about how literature is so sort of dependent on

01:42:25.240 --> 01:42:29.040
[Amit Varma]: the context of the times and the circumstances and all that and somewhere

01:42:29.240 --> 01:42:33.040
[Amit Varma]: you've written about how just being a woman closed you off to a set of

01:42:33.240 --> 01:42:37.040
[Amit Varma]: experiences like you can't go walking the streets of your city yet after

01:42:37.040 --> 01:42:40.840
[Amit Varma]: midnight and you know there are certain experiences you just won't have that if

01:42:41.040 --> 01:42:44.840
[Amit Varma]: you go to a panwala and you're just hanging out everyone else is conscious

01:42:45.040 --> 01:42:48.840
[Amit Varma]: that there's a woman there and therefore they are behaving differently so there

01:42:49.040 --> 01:42:54.840
[Amit Varma]: is a limit to what experiences are open to you how has your sort of way of seeing

01:42:55.040 --> 01:42:59.840
[Amit Varma]: the world evolved over a period of time in the sense that just speaking as a man

01:43:00.040 --> 01:43:04.840
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me that there is a layer of social interaction that was completely

01:43:04.840 --> 01:43:09.640
[Amit Varma]: invisible to me till a few years ago which is really that extra layer of

01:43:09.840 --> 01:43:13.640
[Amit Varma]: awareness that women have to carry with them you know as a man like I can go out

01:43:13.840 --> 01:43:17.640
[Amit Varma]: walking after midnight I can enter a lift with five other people and not think

01:43:17.840 --> 01:43:21.640
[Amit Varma]: for a moment about who they are you know whereas women have to carry this kind of

01:43:21.840 --> 01:43:26.640
[Amit Varma]: extra layer of them and just becoming aware of that layer then just opens one

01:43:26.840 --> 01:43:31.640
[Amit Varma]: out to more kind of complexity now it seems from your writing that you're very

01:43:31.640 --> 01:43:35.440
[Amit Varma]: self-reflective right so there's nothing in that sense there aren't so many

01:43:35.640 --> 01:43:38.440
[Amit Varma]: unknown unknowns there might be known unknowns like what is a city like at

01:43:38.640 --> 01:43:42.440
[Amit Varma]: night but they aren't unknown unknowns like there was for me when I didn't

01:43:42.640 --> 01:43:46.440
[Unknown]: realize that people had this other layer of awareness they had to go through so

01:43:46.640 --> 01:43:51.440
[Amit Varma]: how has your gaze your way of looking at the world in all its aspects you know

01:43:51.640 --> 01:43:55.440
[Amit Varma]: not just from the point of view of gender but just how has your gaze overall

01:43:55.640 --> 01:43:59.440
[Amit Varma]: of looking at the world changed through your life and I ask this not just in a

01:43:59.440 --> 01:44:04.240
[Amit Varma]: writerly context of the things you write but just as a person in general I think

01:44:04.440 --> 01:44:09.240
[Guest]: women in general do carry a lot of baggage that men don't carry but then men

01:44:09.440 --> 01:44:12.240
[Guest]: also carry some baggage that women don't so I don't know whether we can sort of

01:44:12.440 --> 01:44:18.240
[Guest]: draw some kind of thing there but women I think live with a lot of anxiety I mean

01:44:18.440 --> 01:44:23.240
[Guest]: if you're traveling on a bus for instance you're traveling on a train you

01:44:23.440 --> 01:44:27.240
[Guest]: constantly have to be aware of who the next person is why that person is that

01:44:27.240 --> 01:44:31.040
[Guest]: person looking at you where they tend to especially in a bus in a crowded bus I

01:44:31.240 --> 01:44:35.040
[Guest]: have experienced I don't think there'd be any woman possibly who has traveled on

01:44:35.240 --> 01:44:40.040
[Guest]: an Indian bus and not been groped or not been you know sort of so that kind of

01:44:40.240 --> 01:44:45.040
[Guest]: experience will never be a man's experience or never be or sometimes it

01:44:45.240 --> 01:44:50.040
[Guest]: could be a man's experience too but I mean it's it's the norm for women so

01:44:50.240 --> 01:44:54.040
[Guest]: it's that kind of anxiety plus there's so many other anxieties or even as a

01:44:54.040 --> 01:44:57.840
[Guest]: writerly person I mean if you're trying to write there are so many things that

01:44:58.040 --> 01:45:01.840
[Guest]: crowd your mind even if you say get four hours a day or that's that's luxury but

01:45:02.040 --> 01:45:06.840
[Guest]: say two hours a day but your mind has to be empty for you to be able to write but

01:45:07.040 --> 01:45:11.840
[Guest]: the woman will often have the kitchen or the children or something else like that

01:45:12.040 --> 01:45:18.840
[Guest]: domestic worries on her mind whereas a man I think from my sense of it if a man

01:45:19.040 --> 01:45:22.840
[Guest]: gets a two or three hours then the mind can be free of many other things unless

01:45:22.840 --> 01:45:26.640
[Guest]: of course there are other worries that other worries in the world that you are

01:45:26.840 --> 01:45:31.640
[Guest]: worried about or your bank staff or something else you know which you are

01:45:31.840 --> 01:45:35.640
[Guest]: worrying about but otherwise these domestic worries are not a man's worry

01:45:35.840 --> 01:45:39.640
[Guest]: as such you know you are and then people say we did get that much time but do

01:45:39.840 --> 01:45:44.640
[Guest]: somehow that my mind space has always been crowded by other things so in many

01:45:44.840 --> 01:45:48.640
[Guest]: ways women do have a much more difficult time of it especially you were trying to

01:45:48.640 --> 01:45:53.440
[Guest]: do something like writing which needs hours and hours and hours of time and you

01:45:53.640 --> 01:45:56.440
[Guest]: may not produce a single line at the end of it you know people will not understand

01:45:56.640 --> 01:45:59.440
[Guest]: that you spend so much time and what were you doing all this while if you

01:45:59.640 --> 01:46:04.440
[Guest]: didn't write you know that's the normal question so but that of course is the

01:46:04.640 --> 01:46:09.440
[Guest]: same for both men and women but I mean women will often have this worry about

01:46:09.640 --> 01:46:14.440
[Guest]: you know other things on their minds when even when they are writing and one

01:46:14.440 --> 01:46:19.240
[Amit Varma]: of the things writers do is just using the power of imagination they can

01:46:19.440 --> 01:46:22.240
[Amit Varma]: obviously come out of their own skin get into someone else's skin transmit that

01:46:22.440 --> 01:46:26.240
[Amit Varma]: to the reader and the reader experiences herself in a different way because that

01:46:26.440 --> 01:46:29.240
[Amit Varma]: has happened and I noticed this particularly how well you've done this

01:46:29.440 --> 01:46:32.240
[Amit Varma]: in your story Other Skies which you published in Patalipi which you

01:46:32.440 --> 01:46:36.240
[Amit Varma]: translated your own story basically so I've obviously read it in English where

01:46:36.440 --> 01:46:41.240
[Amit Varma]: the character is a guy called Altaf Ahmed and I was very struck by this bit where

01:46:41.240 --> 01:46:46.040
[Amit Varma]: it's after 2001 the riots have happened in Gujarat he's far away from that but

01:46:46.240 --> 01:46:50.040
[Amit Varma]: you capture his interior life so well where you talk about how he sees a woman

01:46:50.240 --> 01:46:53.040
[Amit Varma]: in a burqa and he starts thinking about how long it would take for the burqa to

01:46:53.240 --> 01:46:59.040
[Amit Varma]: burn or when he sort of when somebody asks him his name he stammers while

01:46:59.240 --> 01:47:03.040
[Amit Varma]: telling his name because he is so aware of it and I absolutely love that story

01:47:03.240 --> 01:47:08.040
[Amit Varma]: because it started off with this stark interior life of this guy and then went

01:47:08.040 --> 01:47:11.840
[Amit Varma]: into this really magical place and I won't give a spoiler alert but there were

01:47:12.040 --> 01:47:17.840
[Amit Varma]: these sort of two sort of introductions of magic within the story we just took it

01:47:18.040 --> 01:47:21.840
[Amit Varma]: to another different level and in some ways I mean I was also going to saving a

01:47:22.040 --> 01:47:24.840
[Amit Varma]: question for later about whether you've read Murakami because it seemed almost

01:47:25.040 --> 01:47:28.840
[Amit Varma]: Murakami-esque what you did with that story but to get first get back to the

01:47:29.040 --> 01:47:32.840
[Amit Varma]: question where you've entered this character's head these are not thoughts

01:47:33.040 --> 01:47:35.840
[Amit Varma]: you would have had you would never have had to stammer while saying your name

01:47:35.840 --> 01:47:39.640
[Unknown]: you would not have wondered about how long it takes a burqa to burn

01:47:39.840 --> 01:47:45.640
[Amit Varma]: yeah you know so what is that process then like of you know being able to do

01:47:45.840 --> 01:47:49.640
[Amit Varma]: something like this of widening your gaze like this is it something that came

01:47:49.840 --> 01:47:53.640
[Amit Varma]: to you with age is this something you would have been able to do at 20 or is

01:47:53.840 --> 01:47:56.640
[Amit Varma]: it the Therav of being a little older and

01:47:56.840 --> 01:48:03.640
[Guest]: hmm well yes you are you're right I mean I do get into the character but I mean

01:48:03.640 --> 01:48:07.440
[Guest]: this is something I mean I don't know if it's particular to me I think everyone

01:48:07.640 --> 01:48:12.440
[Guest]: was every writer yeah I mean not just writer I mean that that was a time when

01:48:12.640 --> 01:48:15.440
[Guest]: this was very much a topic of conversation everywhere people were

01:48:15.640 --> 01:48:18.440
[Guest]: discussing the Gujarat riot and what happened and you know this so-and-so

01:48:18.640 --> 01:48:22.440
[Guest]: happened this this is what somebody felt on the train this is what somebody

01:48:22.640 --> 01:48:25.440
[Guest]: walking down the road experienced you know so constantly there was talk in the

01:48:25.640 --> 01:48:32.440
[Guest]: air of this thing so I mean it was not very difficult actually to get into that

01:48:32.440 --> 01:48:37.240
[Guest]: person's shoes I mean after all I mean what would a person with a Muslim name

01:48:37.440 --> 01:48:42.240
[Guest]: at that time be thinking you know there's a great anxiety around and there's fear

01:48:42.440 --> 01:48:49.240
[Guest]: spilling or you know out of every Muslim home every person and but since then I

01:48:49.440 --> 01:48:54.240
[Guest]: have changed my view a little I mean now of course it might be more true but at

01:48:54.440 --> 01:48:59.240
[Guest]: that point I mean they were like we went out and you often met Muslims who were

01:48:59.240 --> 01:49:04.040
[Guest]: not anxious at all or possibly because they had not been aware of what was going

01:49:04.240 --> 01:49:07.040
[Guest]: on they had not heard they were in UP and this is something happening Gujarat

01:49:07.240 --> 01:49:10.040
[Guest]: I don't know but people were saying their names people were happily sort of doing

01:49:10.240 --> 01:49:15.040
[Guest]: going about their jobs so it wasn't as if everyone was nervous but I think the

01:49:15.240 --> 01:49:19.040
[Guest]: people around us people in the middle class that gets to hear of these things

01:49:19.240 --> 01:49:25.040
[Guest]: much more we were nervous we used to think like this and once you are thinking

01:49:25.040 --> 01:49:30.840
[Guest]: in such terms in then it's not difficult to get into at least I think it's not

01:49:31.040 --> 01:49:35.840
[Guest]: difficult to get into such a person's shoes I mean there's another story which

01:49:36.040 --> 01:49:39.840
[Guest]: I thought might be more difficult to get into there's a story that I wrote which

01:49:40.040 --> 01:49:42.840
[Guest]: is now going to be part of my new collection that's about to be out the

01:49:43.040 --> 01:49:45.840
[Guest]: proofs have arrived and I have not been able to look at them because I'm here

01:49:46.040 --> 01:49:49.840
[Guest]: so anyway there's this story I wrote called Mujrim Farar which is about a

01:49:49.840 --> 01:49:55.640
[Guest]: rapist and it's from it's written in the rapist voice you know and I broadly I

01:49:55.840 --> 01:49:59.640
[Guest]: was reacting to I read reports of the rape that took place in the Shakti Mills

01:49:59.840 --> 01:50:04.640
[Guest]: in Bombay and it kind of set off something in me you know what happens

01:50:04.840 --> 01:50:09.640
[Guest]: what goes on in a person who's done this heinous crime what does such a person

01:50:09.840 --> 01:50:14.640
[Guest]: think so I tried to look at it from his point of view and to give it his voice

01:50:14.640 --> 01:50:20.440
[Guest]: so it's basically written like that I mean I shouldn't again give spoilers but

01:50:20.640 --> 01:50:24.440
[Guest]: it's he is following and if the whole act of raping that girl is described and

01:50:24.640 --> 01:50:28.440
[Guest]: I've given him a certain language which is a part of UP speak and a part of

01:50:28.640 --> 01:50:34.440
[Guest]: Bombay lingo you know the filmy Bollywood lingo rather the languages

01:50:34.640 --> 01:50:38.440
[Guest]: language that he's probably absorbed from watching films so it's from his

01:50:38.640 --> 01:50:41.440
[Guest]: point of view and how he does this act and then he runs away and you know I

01:50:41.440 --> 01:50:46.240
[Guest]: shouldn't tell you the whole story but basically it's trying to inhabit a rapist

01:50:46.440 --> 01:50:52.240
[Guest]: shoes so that's and I'm trying to give it some kind I mean I'm giving it a I

01:50:52.440 --> 01:50:56.240
[Guest]: mean it's a story of protest basically let me put it in a very wide sort of

01:50:56.440 --> 01:51:00.240
[Guest]: sense so it's that and the other stories I've written which are also about

01:51:00.440 --> 01:51:05.240
[Guest]: characters I mean somebody once asked me do you think of yourself as a political

01:51:05.440 --> 01:51:10.240
[Guest]: writer so actually I don't I don't think of myself as an overtly political

01:51:10.240 --> 01:51:14.040
[Guest]: writer but I mean if you're writing about things around you which are happening

01:51:14.240 --> 01:51:19.040
[Guest]: everything is political that goes on in this country but it's also experienced

01:51:19.240 --> 01:51:25.040
[Guest]: through your own persona which and I think I'm not sure I approve of the

01:51:25.240 --> 01:51:30.040
[Guest]: completely statement political statement type stories you know because I think

01:51:30.240 --> 01:51:33.040
[Guest]: there are two different kinds of stories one is of course when you are trying to

01:51:33.240 --> 01:51:38.040
[Guest]: comment on what's going on around you and sort of pick up some incident that's

01:51:38.040 --> 01:51:42.840
[Guest]: happened or some movement that's going on and you write about it in a kind of

01:51:43.040 --> 01:51:47.840
[Guest]: expository sort of style and there's the other thing in which you leave yourself

01:51:48.040 --> 01:51:51.840
[Guest]: empty and you absorb impressions and somehow your writer's voice comes out it

01:51:52.040 --> 01:51:55.840
[Guest]: is not your conscious voice it's something else that has been happening

01:51:56.040 --> 01:51:59.840
[Guest]: inside you and there's a certain logic to that writing that is not trying to

01:52:00.040 --> 01:52:03.840
[Guest]: make a comment on what's going on it's not a statement it's not so I have

01:52:03.840 --> 01:52:08.640
[Guest]: tended more to the second style of writing but because I live in a certain

01:52:08.840 --> 01:52:12.640
[Guest]: environment then obviously what I'm writing will be political because I'm

01:52:12.840 --> 01:52:16.640
[Guest]: absorbing things from around and how can you not be political in Indian

01:52:16.840 --> 01:52:21.640
[Guest]: environment so it's like that so inhabiting shoes a writer has to inhabit

01:52:21.840 --> 01:52:25.640
[Guest]: someone else's shoes how will you write you can't write just about yourself you

01:52:25.840 --> 01:52:29.640
[Amit Varma]: have to write about someone else which sort of brings me to this modern kind of

01:52:29.640 --> 01:52:34.440
[Amit Varma]: dilemma about the how the environment around us is changing in terms of how

01:52:34.640 --> 01:52:38.440
[Amit Varma]: people receive writing like I completely agree with you a writer has to occupy

01:52:38.640 --> 01:52:41.440
[Amit Varma]: other people's heads wear other people's shoes I mean that's a whole that's a

01:52:41.640 --> 01:52:45.440
[Amit Varma]: whole game but at the same time you have people talk about things like cultural

01:52:45.640 --> 01:52:50.440
[Amit Varma]: appropriation and so on and I can totally imagine somebody criticizing you

01:52:50.640 --> 01:52:53.440
[Amit Varma]: daring to put yourself in the head of someone called Altaf Ahmed and saying

01:52:53.440 --> 01:52:59.240
[Amit Varma]: that that's appropriation you know seed the platform and all of that and and

01:52:59.440 --> 01:53:04.240
[Amit Varma]: that's just one sort of political aspect that kind of comes into commentary on

01:53:04.440 --> 01:53:09.240
[Amit Varma]: literature but I see other commentary on literature also come from political

01:53:09.440 --> 01:53:14.240
[Amit Varma]: places like that you know you're showing you're showing male toxicity and blah

01:53:14.440 --> 01:53:17.240
[Amit Varma]: blah blah as if you know I mean characters have to be real the world is

01:53:17.440 --> 01:53:22.240
[Amit Varma]: what it is you know that's it's our job to kind of write about that so what do

01:53:22.240 --> 01:53:27.040
[Amit Varma]: you think about this kind of strident politics which is so often even

01:53:27.240 --> 01:53:32.040
[Amit Varma]: evaluating literature through a political lens rather than just seeing a book for

01:53:32.240 --> 01:53:37.040
[Guest]: what it is yeah I mean I have my problems with it frankly because what I

01:53:37.240 --> 01:53:40.040
[Guest]: mean what does cultural appropriation even mean I mean if you're going to

01:53:40.240 --> 01:53:44.040
[Guest]: write about some something anything any person who is not yourself then it's

01:53:44.240 --> 01:53:48.040
[Guest]: cultural appropriation isn't it who will you write about at the end of the day

01:53:48.040 --> 01:53:52.840
[Guest]: you will come down to yourself and you're only allowed to write about yourself and

01:53:53.040 --> 01:53:58.840
[Guest]: even that is not one self one as we know we contain many people inside

01:53:59.040 --> 01:54:02.840
[Guest]: ourselves too so that too is appropriation then so where does this

01:54:03.040 --> 01:54:06.840
[Guest]: argument lead so it just seems to me a very very flawed kind of thing and it's

01:54:07.040 --> 01:54:10.840
[Guest]: a it's basically a political argument it's not a literary argument at all

01:54:11.040 --> 01:54:14.840
[Guest]: because literature means other people how can you write literature without

01:54:14.840 --> 01:54:19.640
[Guest]: talking about other people it would be no literature then so and that's so much

01:54:19.840 --> 01:54:22.640
[Amit Varma]: of literature is looked at through a political lens not just in the context

01:54:22.840 --> 01:54:27.640
[Amit Varma]: of creation but other context yeah where you know only a woman of color is allowed

01:54:27.840 --> 01:54:31.640
[Amit Varma]: to write about another woman of color and so on things like that do you feel

01:54:31.840 --> 01:54:34.640
[Amit Varma]: that then people start approaching literature in the long way and in a

01:54:34.840 --> 01:54:37.640
