01:58:00.240 --> 01:58:04.040
[Amit Varma]: my question here really is that as a writer I think that there is sort of

01:58:04.240 --> 01:58:14.040
[Amit Varma]: this dual imperative which pushes you in opposite directions and one imperative

01:58:14.040 --> 01:58:18.360
[Amit Varma]: to you want your work to be read you want to be relevant and that might lead you towards

01:58:18.360 --> 01:58:22.280
[Amit Varma]: changing your voice in a particular way to be more accessible that might lead you to picking

01:58:22.280 --> 01:58:28.920
[Amit Varma]: subjects that are more in vogue so to say but the other part of that dual imperative is that you

01:58:28.920 --> 01:58:33.320
[Amit Varma]: also just want to be true to yourself that there are things that you care about and whatever kind

01:58:33.320 --> 01:58:37.960
[Amit Varma]: of comes out whatever you care the most about you want to write about that whether or not there are

01:58:37.960 --> 01:58:42.760
[Amit Varma]: readers and and of course the danger of that is that it can be a path to self-indulgence

01:58:42.760 --> 01:58:47.800
[Amit Varma]: if you you know especially if in terms of the style and the idiom you don't think of the reader

01:58:47.800 --> 01:58:53.800
[Amit Varma]: at all and so these are kind of dual imperatives the danger on one side is that you lose yourself

01:58:53.800 --> 01:58:58.920
[Amit Varma]: in the quest for finding more readers and the danger on the other side is that you become

01:58:58.920 --> 01:59:04.360
[Amit Varma]: self-indulgent and no one can relate to you so is this something that you have kind of

01:59:04.360 --> 01:59:10.840
[Guest]: thought about or yeah i mean yeah i've been asked this question before and i think it's uh

01:59:10.840 --> 01:59:18.440
[Guest]: uh when one is actually writing one one doesn't have a reader in mind i i don't i mean it's

01:59:18.440 --> 01:59:24.280
[Guest]: there's some kind of in critic inside you which is trying to get the writing to reach a certain

01:59:24.280 --> 01:59:29.320
[Guest]: standard so you're writing following that voice your own voice and to see whether the story is

01:59:29.320 --> 01:59:33.320
[Guest]: reaching where you wanted it to reach and the reader of course is important but the reader

01:59:33.320 --> 01:59:38.360
[Guest]: comes in later you know so when you're at the point of writing if you started tailoring your

01:59:38.360 --> 01:59:42.120
[Guest]: narrative to the reader then you'd really get nowhere because i mean there are so many readers

01:59:42.120 --> 01:59:46.760
[Guest]: and they'd all be wanting different things so at the point of writing it really doesn't matter

01:59:46.760 --> 01:59:50.440
[Guest]: and in fact if you think about a reader then it's usually there's two or three friends or

01:59:50.440 --> 01:59:55.080
[Guest]: somebody who you know has read you or some you think what would they think you know sometime

01:59:55.080 --> 02:00:00.760
[Guest]: but even that doesn't really enter at the point of writing and yes the other thing of course is

02:00:00.760 --> 02:00:05.320
[Guest]: true i mean if you started tailoring your narrative then you have lost what you wanted to

02:00:05.320 --> 02:00:11.480
[Guest]: write you know and the voice also can't you can't tailor the voice to the reader and the content

02:00:11.480 --> 02:00:17.960
[Guest]: certainly not you know your content is i mean of course you may choose the language like you gave

02:00:17.960 --> 02:00:25.240
[Guest]: the example of Premchand or my mothers i like to call them both mothers so they were writing and

02:00:25.240 --> 02:00:31.240
[Guest]: they of course my my the fact that my father was also publishing kahaani at that time that may have

02:00:31.240 --> 02:00:36.840
[Guest]: played a role in the choice of language too but then i mean this was a hindi literary scene that

02:00:36.840 --> 02:00:41.640
[Guest]: they were aware of whereas i'm not sure that they knew about what was a comparable journal in urdu

02:00:41.640 --> 02:00:46.520
[Guest]: for instance if they had wanted to publish there must have been but i don't know i mean i don't

02:00:46.520 --> 02:00:52.680
[Guest]: know whether they knew of it also so it was wider dissemination ease of publication and for Premchand

02:00:52.680 --> 02:00:59.000
[Guest]: of course uh it's true that he did it because it had a wider reach and he was wanting his message

02:00:59.000 --> 02:01:04.440
[Guest]: to go to as many people as possible so in his case it was certainly true and in their case too

02:01:04.440 --> 02:01:11.720
[Guest]: it was with a slight difference in the stress of it but yes it was true that they changed the

02:01:11.720 --> 02:01:16.680
[Guest]: language but changing the language didn't mean that they changed the i mean the language was

02:01:16.680 --> 02:01:21.240
[Guest]: the same it was a different script just the script was changed so it didn't really make

02:01:21.240 --> 02:01:25.240
[Guest]: a difference whereas in Premchand of course the urdu versions and the hindi versions are completely

02:01:25.240 --> 02:01:30.760
[Guest]: different and there's a whole in fact a lot of confusion about which work was written first

02:01:30.760 --> 02:01:35.880
[Guest]: in urdu and which one because there are many of them which are both versions and you know so you

02:01:35.880 --> 02:01:39.400
[Guest]: don't know which one in many cases you don't know which version was written first and which was

02:01:39.400 --> 02:01:45.880
[Guest]: written second and there were also translations that he commissioned a commission or he got other

02:01:45.880 --> 02:01:50.440
[Guest]: people to do commissioned is like a very modern word he didn't commission them in that sense but

02:01:50.440 --> 02:01:55.560
[Guest]: i mean other people were also transcribing his stories from one language to the other so we

02:01:55.560 --> 02:02:00.680
[Guest]: don't know which ones were done by him he himself had done something or somebody else had done it

02:02:00.680 --> 02:02:04.760
[Guest]: and which one came first which one came second for often the versions are completely different

02:02:05.560 --> 02:02:11.400
[Amit Varma]: like a lot of difference well tell me a little bit about like you often mentioned that you

02:02:11.400 --> 02:02:17.400
[Amit Varma]: write in hindustani which i find is an important distinction now like you said at one level hindi

02:02:17.400 --> 02:02:22.600
[Amit Varma]: and urdu are the same you know the same roots and everything at another level they are now different

02:02:22.600 --> 02:02:28.040
[Amit Varma]: you know driven to that difference by forces of politics and so on and so forth so tell my

02:02:28.040 --> 02:02:32.520
[Amit Varma]: listeners a little bit more about that i know both your uncle amritra and your cousin alokra

02:02:32.520 --> 02:02:36.920
[Amit Varma]: have written books on this subject but you know just enlighten me a little bit more about what

02:02:36.920 --> 02:02:40.920
[Amit Varma]: this process is because most people listening to this would think hindi and urdu are different

02:02:40.920 --> 02:02:45.480
[Amit Varma]: languages and hindi is the language of the hindus of india and urdu is a language of people in

02:02:45.480 --> 02:02:50.200
[Amit Varma]: pakistan and actually the thing is they are both the same language and that language itself which

02:02:50.200 --> 02:02:56.600
[Amit Varma]: they were was a confluence of many many influences and sources from all over the place so yeah tell

02:02:56.600 --> 02:03:02.040
[Guest]: me a little bit about this i don't know if i'll be able to tell you uh so very exactly about the

02:03:02.040 --> 02:03:06.200
[Guest]: because alok has written a book on it and he would be absolutely the person you should talk

02:03:06.200 --> 02:03:11.960
[Guest]: to about this but then of course politics has entered into it and hindi becomes you know for

02:03:11.960 --> 02:03:18.360
[Guest]: reasons that we all know it starts to eliminate all the urdu words and in fact it's so difficult

02:03:18.360 --> 02:03:23.560
[Guest]: to eliminate the urdu words from hindi because simple words like pani or you know stuff like

02:03:23.560 --> 02:03:28.360
[Guest]: that you know very very basic words are you know urdu origin words so how can you sort of divorce

02:03:28.360 --> 02:03:32.840
[Guest]: the two things but this process is going on in and it's tying in with the larger politics of

02:03:32.840 --> 02:03:38.920
[Guest]: the country as the country is becoming sort of more and more hinduized let's call it the irony

02:03:38.920 --> 02:03:45.240
[Guest]: of it is that urdu was actually called hindi first you know urdu was hindi i mean hindi meant urdu

02:03:45.240 --> 02:03:51.160
[Guest]: and then later these names became i mean there's a whole history there so it's like i don't know

02:03:51.160 --> 02:03:57.000
[Guest]: if i'm uh competent enough to speak on this kind of thing just now but i mean of course there's a

02:03:57.000 --> 02:04:01.320
[Guest]: whole story behind it which perhaps if you have a look on your show one day you might be able to

02:04:01.320 --> 02:04:05.080
[Amit Varma]: enlighten you okay that's the plan i'll get you to put in touch with him and i'll also link his

02:04:05.080 --> 02:04:09.000
[Amit Varma]: book from the show notes for those who want more the interesting is like i read at the start of

02:04:09.000 --> 02:04:13.880
[Amit Varma]: your uncle's book and samritra's book on this is that hindi was actually a general term used for

02:04:13.880 --> 02:04:19.560
[Amit Varma]: people who lived in india so there is even like an old text which talks about how i think amir

02:04:19.560 --> 02:04:25.160
[Amit Varma]: khusrow's text about how uh you know people under a certain emperor if hindus came to his attention

02:04:25.160 --> 02:04:30.440
[Amit Varma]: they would they would be trampled by elephants but other hindis like the muslimans would be spared

02:04:30.440 --> 02:04:35.240
[Unknown]: you know so it's interesting how words also evolve to take on particular meanings and

02:04:35.240 --> 02:04:40.520
[Amit Varma]: people forget the origin and in fact so much of what we consider uh indian authentically indian

02:04:40.520 --> 02:04:44.840
[Guest]: and sanskari today actually came from outside like yeah yeah like the elegant churidar kurtas

02:04:44.840 --> 02:04:49.800
[Guest]: of modiji oh absolutely everything there's so much in the way of food in the way of dress i

02:04:49.800 --> 02:04:54.920
[Guest]: mean everything i mean it's such a very mixed culture you know it's just impossible to separate

02:04:54.920 --> 02:05:00.760
[Guest]: things into how can you do that i mean it's just complete bloody mindedness i think that these

02:05:00.760 --> 02:05:05.800
[Guest]: people are trying to push this down people's throats before we get to talking more about your

02:05:05.800 --> 02:05:11.560
[Amit Varma]: writing processes and all which also i do let's take this digression into how this country is

02:05:11.560 --> 02:05:17.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of changing and in a sense your own family is a great example of a syncretic india this

02:05:17.000 --> 02:05:22.360
[Amit Varma]: khichdi where everything is mixing easily of course you know premchand was progressive in

02:05:22.360 --> 02:05:27.480
[Amit Varma]: the sense that he married a child widow his second wedding was to a very formidable lady

02:05:27.480 --> 02:05:31.960
[Amit Varma]: and a writer in her own right who i'll ask you to speak about as well and so on down the line

02:05:31.960 --> 02:05:36.760
[Amit Varma]: there have been mixed marriages as just you know in a sense your family reflects the khichdi that

02:05:36.760 --> 02:05:43.800
[Amit Varma]: india is and yet today we live in a time where simplified narratives that sort of reduce our

02:05:43.800 --> 02:05:49.560
[Amit Varma]: culture that reduce individuals to a particular thing are in vogue where you know hinduism is

02:05:49.560 --> 02:05:55.720
[Amit Varma]: being reduced to sort of a particular brahminical strain of it you know or and in some ways almost

02:05:55.720 --> 02:06:00.280
[Amit Varma]: carrying or almost sort of harking back to the tradition of other western religions which are

02:06:00.280 --> 02:06:04.360
[Amit Varma]: religions of the book so to say and we of course don't have a book it's a completely open culture

02:06:04.360 --> 02:06:09.480
[Amit Varma]: but there is a sense that you know uh you're trying to center around one of our great gods

02:06:09.480 --> 02:06:14.520
[Amit Varma]: which is ram and you're trying to you know reduce it down to that and similarly in terms of language

02:06:14.520 --> 02:06:19.240
[Amit Varma]: like a quick summary for readers who might not be aware of it is that the politicization of you know

02:06:19.240 --> 02:06:24.520
[Amit Varma]: how language changed really began because there was a political movement to mark out hindi as

02:06:24.520 --> 02:06:31.000
[Amit Varma]: separate from urdu and hindi in devanagari as a language of the hindus of india and for that one

02:06:31.000 --> 02:06:36.600
[Amit Varma]: of the idioms kind of created was this very artificial sanskritized hindi shudh hindi as

02:06:36.600 --> 02:06:41.880
[Amit Varma]: it were which i remember being taught in my school which no one actually speaks like like your own

02:06:41.880 --> 02:06:47.160
[Amit Varma]: writing is much more the way everyday people speak the colloquial speak but there is this

02:06:47.160 --> 02:06:50.920
[Amit Varma]: artificial kind of shudh hindi ness which has come up and the prime minister speaks in it

02:06:50.920 --> 02:06:55.320
[Amit Varma]: which is very interesting because i don't know how people relate to that you know he's otherwise

02:06:55.320 --> 02:06:59.480
[Amit Varma]: in terms of polemics and speech making and all for whatever it's worth you got to give him credit he

02:06:59.480 --> 02:07:04.040
[Amit Varma]: does reach out to many people and he's built a cult around himself but i don't i don't understand

02:07:04.040 --> 02:07:09.000
[Amit Varma]: how the language works because it's a language nobody really speaks but all that apart a lot

02:07:09.000 --> 02:07:14.360
[Amit Varma]: of the change that is happening in our country uh in many alarming ways is something which people

02:07:14.360 --> 02:07:19.160
[Amit Varma]: locate in the hindi heartland in up in the places where you live yeah tell me from your lived

02:07:19.160 --> 02:07:26.920
[Amit Varma]: experiences of whether culturally uh the change is as drastic as it seems or it is only vocal

02:07:26.920 --> 02:07:32.440
[Amit Varma]: elements of this current time and vocal elements of this political movement who make it seem that

02:07:32.440 --> 02:07:39.080
[Guest]: way it's very much present i think it's just very present in your everyday lives i mean the sounds

02:07:39.080 --> 02:07:43.560
[Guest]: around you have changed the way people walk has changed the way people laugh has changed i think

02:07:43.560 --> 02:07:49.000
[Guest]: i mean this whole thing that's going on this hinduization let's call it i mean it's very very

02:07:49.000 --> 02:07:55.400
[Guest]: present and especially uh in up because i mean and you can see even among the people who are

02:07:55.400 --> 02:08:02.680
[Guest]: around you who were not sort of so very right-wing so i mean things have changed but now more people

02:08:02.680 --> 02:08:09.560
[Guest]: you meet are sort of going to sort of be i mean you will be noticed much more as a kind of anomaly

02:08:09.560 --> 02:08:16.680
[Guest]: in society rather than you know somebody who's part of a structure and when my parents got

02:08:16.680 --> 02:08:22.040
[Guest]: married in 1948 i mean it was a hindu muslim marriage and this we are talking of the year

02:08:22.040 --> 02:08:27.800
[Guest]: right after partition and there was nothing no furor made over it you know it happened

02:08:27.800 --> 02:08:35.240
[Guest]: peacefully nobody noticed before that my uncle had also married a hindu wife and i mean then too

02:08:35.240 --> 02:08:39.720
[Guest]: i mean it was not i mean like today there's this whole business of love jihad carrying on you know

02:08:39.720 --> 02:08:44.600
[Guest]: i mean nobody thought of it like that earlier i mean it's just something very it's a political

02:08:44.600 --> 02:08:49.560
[Guest]: thing that's being imposed on people's lives you know and it's impacting everyone i think in a very

02:08:49.560 --> 02:08:58.040
[Guest]: very obvious in a very negative way so lots of people you meet i mean it's just the whole experience

02:08:58.040 --> 02:09:04.040
[Amit Varma]: of living has changed in very drastic ways and and you you kind of mentioned about how you know

02:09:04.040 --> 02:09:08.200
[Amit Varma]: love jihad wasn't a big deal then i did an episode on the gita press with akshay mukul

02:09:08.200 --> 02:09:12.840
