[Guest]: meantime so you don't know what has caused this to happen so yes it is we become different people

02:26:27.720 --> 02:26:31.720
[Guest]: throughout our lives i suppose we keep changing and by the end of it we probably wouldn't

02:26:31.720 --> 02:26:38.280
[Amit Varma]: recognize that earlier person who we were so what do you think of the earlier Sarah Rai the person

02:26:38.280 --> 02:26:45.160
[Amit Varma]: in her 20s like you know when i look back on the younger me i am kind of filled with astonishment

02:26:45.160 --> 02:26:49.560
[Amit Varma]: that that person managed to become this older me i mean i just don't like him at all it's like

02:26:49.560 --> 02:26:54.200
[Unknown]: another person i'm like what and then you begin to kind of question your sense of self and say

02:26:54.200 --> 02:26:59.160
[Amit Varma]: that what is it that that person and i have in common apart from the name and apart from all

02:26:59.160 --> 02:27:05.720
[Guest]: that and yeah have you reflected on your younger self well at that point of what i do think is that

02:27:05.720 --> 02:27:10.840
[Guest]: one was not thinking of anything at all one was just going through life just as as the days came

02:27:10.840 --> 02:27:15.800
[Guest]: you just lived it and you went on so there was no process of thinking really about where i'm headed

02:27:15.800 --> 02:27:20.920
[Guest]: what should i be doing there was no kind of conceptual framing of a life at that stage

02:27:20.920 --> 02:27:25.480
[Guest]: you know and now i regret it almost that i should have done this i should have done that why didn't

02:27:25.480 --> 02:27:29.720
[Guest]: i read this why didn't i write that why didn't i start my writing career much earlier all the

02:27:29.720 --> 02:27:34.360
[Guest]: all those regrets i do have but then one was leading you had all the time in the world

02:27:34.360 --> 02:27:38.680
[Guest]: now i feel that time is finishing i have to do what i have there's a kind of urgency that has

02:27:38.680 --> 02:27:44.040
[Guest]: taken over my life you know and then one didn't think of it i mean it was just a whole life

02:27:44.040 --> 02:27:48.760
[Guest]: stretching ahead in front of you and you could do what with it what you liked so most of it was

02:27:48.760 --> 02:27:53.720
[Guest]: spent just going out with friends or reading or listening to music or whatever i mean there was

02:27:53.720 --> 02:27:59.080
[Guest]: no direction as such but i don't know how this whole direction business came in in the first

02:27:59.080 --> 02:28:04.840
[Guest]: place because well i was not as such i mean i wanted to be a writer but i was not really doing

02:28:04.840 --> 02:28:10.680
[Guest]: anything about it you know i was not going about it with any kind of seriousness but suddenly i

02:28:10.680 --> 02:28:16.120
[Guest]: mean it did take me by surprise i suppose that i wrote my first story i was in australia then

02:28:16.920 --> 02:28:20.840
[Guest]: and we were there my husband was doing his research there so we were there for about six years

02:28:21.480 --> 02:28:27.320
[Guest]: and i wrote my first story there it was already quite late i mean i was in my 30s not 40s but 30s

02:28:27.320 --> 02:28:33.960
[Guest]: 40s but 30s and i sent my stories to my father who at that point was quite all right i mean he

02:28:33.960 --> 02:28:40.280
[Guest]: didn't have this dementia thing that i spoke of later and so he read my stories he liked them

02:28:40.280 --> 02:28:45.480
[Guest]: he sort of he felt sort of happy that somebody had taken after you know whatever somebody was

02:28:45.480 --> 02:28:50.920
[Guest]: also writing in the family in among this generation so all that did take place but

