[Guest]: i mean if i had to live it all again which of course i won't i would have started this much

02:28:56.680 --> 02:29:03.640
[Guest]: earlier and i just feel a sense of waste of a wasted life in a sense that you come to things

02:29:03.640 --> 02:29:09.880
[Guest]: very late and then when you realize there's so little left it's that sadness of it takes

02:29:10.600 --> 02:29:16.360
[Amit Varma]: i had a episode i really like doing with kavita rao who's written a wonderful books on our lady

02:29:16.360 --> 02:29:21.560
[Amit Varma]: doctors and we spoke a lot about late blooming there and like her mother started learning sitar

02:29:21.560 --> 02:29:28.280
[Amit Varma]: at 75 and now at 77 she apparently plays it very well and i remembered you know penelope

02:29:28.280 --> 02:29:33.160
[Unknown]: fitzgerald the great novelist who started writing in her 60s and mother booker and all that and just

02:29:33.160 --> 02:29:39.160
[Amit Varma]: lovely novels so here's the thing you know you start your essay in caravan by talking about how

02:29:39.160 --> 02:29:44.040
[Amit Varma]: your dad when he met you uh you know made made you sit down and you're already around 40 at this time

02:29:44.040 --> 02:29:49.800
[Unknown]: or thereabouts and made you write uh the following words quote katharine mansfield you will be the

02:29:49.800 --> 02:29:56.040
[Amit Varma]: katharine mansfield of india stop quote and what strikes me here is that he has a vision for you

02:29:56.040 --> 02:30:03.160
[Amit Varma]: he wants you to be this and this is somehow important and equally in your words when you

02:30:03.160 --> 02:30:08.760
[Amit Varma]: talk about starting too late or feeling that there is not enough time there is sort of the

02:30:08.760 --> 02:30:15.240
[Amit Varma]: implication that you have set out for yourself something to do or something to achieve and you

02:30:15.240 --> 02:30:20.360
[Amit Varma]: know and i also have those regrets sometimes that oh i could have written 10 books by now i never

02:30:20.360 --> 02:30:26.920
[Amit Varma]: had this and all of that but also i tell myself that it is sometimes dangerous to have that one

02:30:26.920 --> 02:30:32.040
[Amit Varma]: vision of yourself or those big dreams because they never happen what is more important is to

02:30:32.040 --> 02:30:36.040
[Amit Varma]: keep doing what you love doing and whatever happens happens and you live in the moment

02:30:36.040 --> 02:30:40.520
[Amit Varma]: and when you're gone you're gone anyway you know this whole concept of a legacy i don't know what

02:30:40.520 --> 02:30:46.120
[Amit Varma]: it means so what do you think about that especially you know given the pressure of the sort of family

02:30:46.120 --> 02:30:50.520
[Amit Varma]: you came from and if you also then think of yourself as a writer there might be the sense

02:30:50.520 --> 02:30:56.920
[Amit Varma]: that oh i have to become x y z and even now when you speak of uh you know not enough time which i

02:30:56.920 --> 02:31:00.920
[Guest]: don't agree with there is enough time for all of us and too little time for all of us in another

02:31:00.920 --> 02:31:07.320
[Guest]: respect but how do you actually actually i mean i think the struggle was not to become someone

02:31:07.320 --> 02:31:14.680
[Guest]: like i mean it was not an i mean not ambitious in that sense but a desire to have a better utilized

02:31:14.680 --> 02:31:19.640
[Guest]: life you know not to have wasted so much you know because there's so much that one doesn't know so

02:31:19.640 --> 02:31:24.520
[Guest]: little one has read so much of other systems of knowledge that one is completely oblivious to i

02:31:24.520 --> 02:31:31.720
[Guest]: mean you just what do we know of you know sort of muslim learning or even sanskrit or you know

02:31:31.720 --> 02:31:37.480
[Guest]: there's so many vast sort of areas of knowledge that are completely sort of dark for me you know

02:31:37.480 --> 02:31:43.160
[Guest]: so i just wish that i had done more with that time and one doesn't get the urgency at that point of

02:31:43.160 --> 02:31:47.480
[Guest]: time because one thinks that one has all the time and you're not even thinking along those lines

02:31:47.480 --> 02:31:52.840
[Guest]: you're not thinking that i should be doing this or i wish i knew this so uh it was not so much of

02:31:52.840 --> 02:31:59.800
[Guest]: of wanting to become or having written 10 books or whatever but a kind of engagement with life

02:31:59.800 --> 02:32:05.720
[Guest]: that could have become begun earlier and that started late for me i thought in a certain kind

02:32:05.720 --> 02:32:13.400
[Guest]: of way of thinking that i could have got into earlier and i did think and well it was a little

02:32:13.400 --> 02:32:18.600
[Guest]: all over the place i thought i mean i it could have been more focused so if you had to give

02:32:18.600 --> 02:32:23.640
[Amit Varma]: advice to your younger self in specific terms what would that be right every day

02:32:26.040 --> 02:32:29.560
[Unknown]: because writing also sharpens the vision you see it's not just what you're producing but

02:32:29.560 --> 02:32:34.040
[Guest]: you're learning to see you know seeing is so important is such an important part of being a

02:32:34.040 --> 02:32:41.560
[Amit Varma]: writer i couldn't agree more this is almost like a sort of a lament i share about myself

02:32:41.560 --> 02:32:48.760
[Unknown]: so let's actually now talk about your sort of your writing process yeah when you begin writing

02:32:48.760 --> 02:32:54.040
[Amit Varma]: seriously like my biggest problem is that you know if there is a structure to something i'm

02:32:54.040 --> 02:32:58.040
[Amit Varma]: doing for example with the scene in the unseen i know that i have to release it on monday

02:32:58.040 --> 02:33:03.080
[Amit Varma]: and therefore i have to get the files ready by so and so time yeah and i'm there's a structure so i

02:33:03.080 --> 02:33:08.120
[Amit Varma]: get it done but when there isn't a structure like i want to write a book or i want to do this it's

02:33:08.120 --> 02:33:13.560
[Amit Varma]: very hard for me to be able to discipline myself because in the moment there is always something

02:33:13.560 --> 02:33:20.600
[Amit Varma]: that is in the way so how have you arrived at your sort of writing discipline and writing habits

02:33:20.600 --> 02:33:27.560
[Guest]: and what are your sort of processes like well uh i suppose it means that you spend a lot of time

02:33:27.560 --> 02:33:34.520
[Guest]: at the job and say if one can manage to while i'm in the process of actually writing the story then

02:33:34.520 --> 02:33:41.240
[Guest]: i do spend time with it i mean i can never rush through a story i mean and i never make drafts

02:33:41.800 --> 02:33:46.600
[Guest]: it's like when i'm working on a story i keep changing it as i go along and this this used

02:33:46.600 --> 02:33:50.360
[Guest]: to be a problem when i wrote longhand because then you have to cut and slash and copy out the

02:33:50.360 --> 02:33:55.400
[Guest]: whole thing again which for much of my earlier writing life i did have these registers full of

02:33:55.400 --> 02:34:01.560
[Guest]: stories and i would cancel them out and rewrite them and all that but this has changed of course

02:34:01.560 --> 02:34:07.880
[Guest]: with the coming of the computer but you do spend a lot of time thinking and thinking and polishing

02:34:07.880 --> 02:34:13.480
[Guest]: and the thought and integrating what you're trying to say with the language with the structure

02:34:14.360 --> 02:34:19.480
[Guest]: i mean i also tend to use metaphors sometimes like the whole story might be a metaphor for

02:34:19.480 --> 02:34:24.760
[Guest]: instance there's this story that i wrote called Amar Vallari which is about losing which about

02:34:24.760 --> 02:34:32.440
[Guest]: losing things like and lost spaces it's about lost spaces really i mean about a space that and a

02:34:32.440 --> 02:34:37.960
[Guest]: space can be a metaphor you know it can be in the story it is a metaphor it's a space of childhood

02:34:37.960 --> 02:34:44.840
[Guest]: of memory of of an actual physical space which is now being like it's set in a bungalow which is

02:34:44.840 --> 02:34:50.600
[Guest]: very much like my own bungalow which is all wild and it has gone and it's in the middle of this

02:34:50.600 --> 02:34:56.760
[Guest]: residential sort of high-rise apartments around it and now it's just this one space of wildness left

02:34:56.760 --> 02:35:01.000
[Guest]: so it's that and wildness i've been kind of obsessed with wildness a little bit in my writing

02:35:01.000 --> 02:35:07.000
[Guest]: and wildness not just as physical wildness but as a metaphor also like wildness in the sense of

02:35:07.000 --> 02:35:13.400
[Guest]: solitude like there's a story i wrote called Biaban Mei which is in the wilderness literally

02:35:13.400 --> 02:35:18.360
[Guest]: so in that you can be in a sort of mental wilderness i mean there's a little girl in it

02:35:18.360 --> 02:35:24.840
[Guest]: who's sort of dumb you've read that story i love that story yes and so i mean wildness has been

02:35:24.840 --> 02:35:31.160
[Guest]: kind of occupied me a lot and i and it has never been a negative thing it i think it's a space of

02:35:31.160 --> 02:35:38.040
[Guest]: solitude that one needs and which is very necessary especially for a writer and in solitude it is in

02:35:38.040 --> 02:35:43.400
[Guest]: solitude only that the thought will come to you the idea will come to you and you will be able to

02:35:43.400 --> 02:35:50.520
[Guest]: to see you know a certain clarity comes when you're alone and you're in solitude so for me

02:35:50.520 --> 02:35:57.320
[Guest]: the wildness and solitude has become like together it have got merged together as an idea and i think

02:35:57.320 --> 02:36:03.960
[Guest]: it's very necessary for a writer so that has happened and what was i saying i mean i've

02:36:03.960 --> 02:36:09.160
[Guest]: forgotten this how we started out yeah no we were just sort of talking about your processes of

02:36:09.160 --> 02:36:14.760
[Guest]: writing yeah so it's the solitude and you need to be completely by yourself you need to empty your

02:36:14.760 --> 02:36:18.840
[Guest]: mind there should not be anything else happening around you which is always a very difficult thing

02:36:18.840 --> 02:36:23.400
[Guest]: because something or the other is always happening so it's very hard to just do that but then you

02:36:23.400 --> 02:36:30.840
[Guest]: have to empty yourself out and allow the voice to take shape you know so it often you just sit

02:36:30.840 --> 02:36:35.880
[Guest]: for hours and hours and nothing comes so at the end of a day if you come up with a paragraph that's

02:36:35.880 --> 02:36:41.080
[Guest]: a good day you know and sometimes nothing may come at all and that's a bad day so it's basically

02:36:41.080 --> 02:36:46.760
[Guest]: it's just that i mean you keep thinking and meditating and you know just waiting for the

02:36:46.760 --> 02:36:51.800
[Amit Varma]: thing to arrive i love wilderness i wanted to talk about it i don't have a particular question

02:36:51.800 --> 02:36:56.440
[Amit Varma]: as such but what i loved about wilderness was again in in a magic realist kind of sense that

02:36:56.440 --> 02:37:03.880
[Amit Varma]: moment at the end which just kind of transcends the story and just is so so profound and how do

02:37:03.880 --> 02:37:09.320
[Amit Varma]: you arrive at that in the sense of not in the mechanistic sense of how did you think of this

02:37:09.320 --> 02:37:15.000
[Amit Varma]: but more in a sense of in terms of process like did you have to write different drafts of the

02:37:15.000 --> 02:37:19.720
[Amit Varma]: story or were you stuck at that point how do i take it forward or when you begin the story do

02:37:19.720 --> 02:37:23.240
[Amit Varma]: you know the way it's going to end and you just know what's going to happen and it's not just

02:37:23.240 --> 02:37:29.640
[Amit Varma]: that story it's also other uh skies for example where that that crazy end which is again right

02:37:29.640 --> 02:37:33.960
[Unknown]: out of magic realism and it's such a striking image like imagine a cinematic image like that

02:37:33.960 --> 02:37:38.040
[Amit Varma]: and i don't want to give any spoilers but my listeners we can read those themselves

02:37:38.040 --> 02:37:44.120
[Amit Varma]: so how does that happen and is it then also a conscious process that you think about how in

02:37:44.120 --> 02:37:50.120
[Amit Varma]: every story you want to find this moment which kind of crystallizes everything which is like

02:37:50.120 --> 02:37:54.840
[Guest]: this revelatory moment which is it's a bit of a mystery actually because it comes sort of in a

02:37:54.840 --> 02:37:59.880
[Guest]: flash i mean it is not something i mean when i start writing there's no story as such that i have

02:37:59.880 --> 02:38:05.560
[Guest]: in my head the story as it happens you know it just takes over when you are writing the story

02:38:05.560 --> 02:38:10.520
[Guest]: you know shapes itself one sentence follows the other and somehow you know the story gets created

02:38:10.520 --> 02:38:15.560
[Guest]: i'm also not very sure how exactly it happens it's a sort of accident i suppose and but that

02:38:15.560 --> 02:38:20.440
[Guest]: ending that you're talking of that did come to me in a flash i mean these there are these two people

02:38:20.440 --> 02:38:26.280
[Guest]: who are locked into the wildernesses of different kinds and suddenly what can unite them and get

02:38:26.280 --> 02:38:32.200
[Guest]: them out of it is this bus that's totally instead of moving forward it starts rising because they

02:38:32.200 --> 02:38:36.920
[Guest]: also see themselves at that point they see themselves they see the whole town especially

02:38:36.920 --> 02:38:43.400
[Guest]: for the writer who is not for the little girl but the writer who must see around her so when

02:38:43.400 --> 02:38:49.320
[Guest]: she's up there she can see everything very clearly and she also finds that she has got some kind of

02:38:49.320 --> 02:38:56.280
[Guest]: release from this being locked as she thinks you know she's got a writer's block so that block

02:38:56.280 --> 02:39:02.200
[Guest]: gets removed for her too and maybe presumably now she'll be able to write so it's all about

02:39:02.200 --> 02:39:06.360
[Guest]: the writing process too that story is about the girl and it's also about the writer's own writing

02:39:06.360 --> 02:39:11.400
[Guest]: process so it happened like that and then the other story i mean i don't really have many magical

02:39:11.400 --> 02:39:16.280
[Guest]: moments as such in the stories in my stories maybe just the two i've read just the two and

02:39:16.280 --> 02:39:21.960
[Guest]: maybe a couple more i mean i don't quite know how they how they enter the story like

02:39:23.240 --> 02:39:29.080
[Guest]: there's another story i wrote which is called Kam Bolne Wale Bhai which is set in Chhattisgarh

02:39:29.080 --> 02:39:33.480
[Guest]: and it's got in the backdrop some mysterious happenings that are taking place we know what

02:39:33.480 --> 02:39:39.640
[Guest]: they are you know and the sort of people getting killed and all that but at the end also there's

02:39:39.640 --> 02:39:44.200
[Guest]: a moment in which this person i mean i shouldn't tell you this story don't tell me don't give the

02:39:44.200 --> 02:39:49.640
[Guest]: spoiler yeah yeah but anyway there's this moment in which all these Jugnus suddenly become it's

02:39:49.640 --> 02:39:54.840
[Guest]: like a sheet of Jugnus and they are they are signaling hope i mean there's also this sort

02:39:54.840 --> 02:40:02.200
[Guest]: of symbolism tied in with some of the stories in which a certain description will add up to hope

02:40:02.200 --> 02:40:06.680
[Guest]: or will add up to something that's not consciously done but i find that it happens it becomes like

02:40:06.680 --> 02:40:12.520
[Guest]: that when i'm writing the story that i'm kind of in a very subtle way giving a message so it's not

02:40:12.520 --> 02:40:19.640
[Guest]: really a message as such but it's tied in with the story but it does lead you to some kind of hopeful

02:40:19.640 --> 02:40:25.960
[Amit Varma]: ending and how consciously do you think about technique or craft number one and a second

02:40:25.960 --> 02:40:32.120
[Amit Varma]: question kind of tied into this which is what i have recently been wondering whether art and craft

02:40:32.120 --> 02:40:37.560
[Amit Varma]: are really the same thing that art is just craft except it is craft at a subconscious level so

02:40:37.560 --> 02:40:42.040
[Amit Varma]: you're doing something without knowing how you did it but it is really craft you've gotten to that

02:40:42.040 --> 02:40:45.960
[Unknown]: point because you've done something again and again and it seems magical and beautiful and it

02:40:45.960 --> 02:40:51.160
[Amit Varma]: doesn't seem like there is it seems to transcend craft which almost has a mundane implication

02:40:51.160 --> 02:40:55.480
[Amit Varma]: but actually they are the same thing and one of them you understand and you can break it down

02:40:55.480 --> 02:41:01.160
[Amit Varma]: and the other one is happening at a subterranean level yeah well in some ways uh you're right i

02:41:01.160 --> 02:41:06.440
[Guest]: mean uh one is of course i mean craft is very important in the writing of a story and sometimes

02:41:06.440 --> 02:41:12.440
[Guest]: the story is dictated by the craft also so uh i mean the two things are obviously very tied together

02:41:12.440 --> 02:41:18.920
[Guest]: but uh when the craft and art they are separate too i mean i mean there you firstly i think what

02:41:18.920 --> 02:41:23.480
[Guest]: differentiates it is that there has to be an idea behind the art there has to be something there

02:41:23.480 --> 02:41:29.080
[Guest]: it's not just the making of patterns or a making of and there has to be something central to the

02:41:29.080 --> 02:41:33.560
[Guest]: narrative something integrated there has to be some kind of vision some kind of vision to the

02:41:33.560 --> 02:41:40.120
[Guest]: story and for that vision you choose the appropriate craft you choose the narrative style you choose

02:41:40.120 --> 02:41:44.920
[Guest]: the structure you choose the language everything falls in with that central vision so if that

02:41:44.920 --> 02:41:51.320
[Guest]: central vision is missing then i don't think it can be possibly be called art then it becomes just a

02:41:51.320 --> 02:41:57.560
[Guest]: random pattern finely drawn but it's a pattern so i think that is the main thing that is different

02:41:57.560 --> 02:42:03.640
[Amit Varma]: and when you kind of look at the books that you've written uh and obviously a couple of

02:42:03.640 --> 02:42:08.680
[Amit Varma]: decades have passed since uh you know you kind of resumed uh writing in that sense after Lucky

